1
00:00:00,120 --> 00:00:01,530
- So Rome always wins

2
00:00:01,649 --> 00:00:03,328
because even if they lose battles,

3
00:00:03,330 --> 00:00:05,519
they go to the Italian allies and half citizens

4
00:00:05,519 --> 00:00:06,989
and raise new armies.

5
00:00:06,990 --> 00:00:08,550
So how do you beat them?

6
00:00:08,550 --> 00:00:11,460
He can never raise that many troops himself.

7
00:00:11,460 --> 00:00:14,879
And Hannibal, I think, correctly figures out

8
00:00:14,880 --> 00:00:17,040
the one way to maybe defeat Rome

9
00:00:17,039 --> 00:00:19,079
is to cut them away from their allies.

10
00:00:19,079 --> 00:00:20,609
Well, how do you do this?

11
00:00:20,609 --> 00:00:21,808
Hannibal's plan is,

12
00:00:21,809 --> 00:00:23,878
I'm not gonna wait and fight the Romans

13
00:00:23,879 --> 00:00:25,709
in Spain or North Africa.

14
00:00:25,710 --> 00:00:28,080
I'm gonna invade Italy.

15
00:00:28,079 --> 00:00:29,789
So I'm gonna strike at the heart

16
00:00:29,789 --> 00:00:32,818
of this growing Roman Empire,

17
00:00:32,820 --> 00:00:35,550
and my hope is that if I can win

18
00:00:35,549 --> 00:00:38,819
a couple big battles against Rome in Italy,

19
00:00:38,820 --> 00:00:41,790
the Italians will want their freedom back,

20
00:00:41,789 --> 00:00:43,409
and they'll rebel from Rome

21
00:00:43,409 --> 00:00:45,328
and maybe even join me.

22
00:00:45,329 --> 00:00:47,099
Because most people who have been conquered

23
00:00:47,100 --> 00:00:48,210
want their freedom back,

24
00:00:48,210 --> 00:00:51,359
so this is a reasonable plan.

25
00:00:51,359 --> 00:00:54,749
So Hannibal famously crosses the Alps with elephants.

26
00:00:54,750 --> 00:00:55,680
Dramatic stuff.

27
00:00:55,679 --> 00:00:57,058
Nobody expects them to do this.

28
00:00:57,060 --> 00:00:58,830
Nobody thinks you can do this.

29
00:00:58,829 --> 00:01:00,508
Shows up in northern Italy,

30
00:01:00,509 --> 00:01:01,738
Romans send an army,

31
00:01:01,740 --> 00:01:03,090
Hannibal massacres them.

32
00:01:03,090 --> 00:01:04,860
He is a military genius.

33
00:01:04,859 --> 00:01:06,359
Rome takes a year,

34
00:01:06,359 --> 00:01:08,729
raises a second army, we know this story,

35
00:01:08,730 --> 00:01:09,959
sends it against Hannibal,

36
00:01:09,959 --> 00:01:11,162
Hannibal wipes 'em out.

37
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:13,417
Rome gets clever this time.

38
00:01:13,417 --> 00:01:15,150
They say, "Okay, Hannibal's different.

39
00:01:15,150 --> 00:01:16,980
We're gonna take two years,

40
00:01:16,980 --> 00:01:18,300
raise two armies,

41
00:01:18,299 --> 00:01:21,749
and send them both out at the same time against Hannibal."

42
00:01:21,750 --> 00:01:22,723
So they do this,

43
00:01:22,722 --> 00:01:24,089
and this is the Battle of Cannae,

44
00:01:24,090 --> 00:01:27,480
which is one of the most famous battles in history.

45
00:01:27,480 --> 00:01:32,190
Hannibal is facing this army of 80,000 Romans about,

46
00:01:32,189 --> 00:01:34,679
and he comes up with strategy called double envelopment.

47
00:01:34,680 --> 00:01:36,150
I mean, we can go into it later if you want,

48
00:01:36,150 --> 00:01:37,319
but it's this famous strategy

49
00:01:37,319 --> 00:01:39,448
where he basically kind of sucks the Romans in,

50
00:01:39,450 --> 00:01:41,400
surrounds them on all sides,

51
00:01:41,400 --> 00:01:43,230
and in one afternoon,

52
00:01:43,230 --> 00:01:44,760
at the Battle of Cannae,

53
00:01:44,760 --> 00:01:49,760
Hannibal kills about 60,000 Romans.

54
00:01:50,579 --> 00:01:52,889
Now, just to put that in perspective,

55
00:01:52,890 --> 00:01:55,709
that's more Romans hacked to death

56
00:01:55,709 --> 00:01:58,108
in one afternoon with swords

57
00:01:58,109 --> 00:02:01,201
than Americans died in 20 years in Vietnam.

58
00:02:03,359 --> 00:02:07,378
- The following is a conversation with Gregory Aldrete,

59
00:02:07,379 --> 00:02:10,738
a historian specializing in Ancient Rome

60
00:02:10,740 --> 00:02:13,530
and military history.

61
00:02:13,530 --> 00:02:15,419
This is Lex Fridman podcast.

62
00:02:15,419 --> 00:02:17,308
To support it, please check out our sponsors

63
00:02:17,310 --> 00:02:18,539
in the description.

64
00:02:18,539 --> 00:02:21,902
And now, dear friends, here's Gregory Aldrete.

65
00:02:23,069 --> 00:02:24,629
What do you think is the big difference

66
00:02:24,629 --> 00:02:28,229
between the ancient world and the modern world?

67
00:02:28,229 --> 00:02:29,819
- Well, the easy answer,

68
00:02:29,819 --> 00:02:32,428
the one you often get is technology.

69
00:02:32,430 --> 00:02:35,070
And obviously, there's huge differences in technology

70
00:02:35,069 --> 00:02:36,508
between the ancient world and today.

71
00:02:36,509 --> 00:02:38,428
But I think some of the more interesting stuff

72
00:02:38,430 --> 00:02:40,590
is a little bit more amorphous things,

73
00:02:40,590 --> 00:02:41,940
more structural things.

74
00:02:41,939 --> 00:02:43,709
So I would say,

75
00:02:43,710 --> 00:02:45,813
first of all, childhood mortality.

76
00:02:46,770 --> 00:02:47,700
In the ancient world,

77
00:02:47,699 --> 00:02:49,529
and this is true of Greeks, Romans, Egyptians,

78
00:02:49,530 --> 00:02:52,470
really anybody up until about the Industrial Revolution,

79
00:02:52,469 --> 00:02:57,388
about 30 to 40% of kids died before they hit puberty.

80
00:02:57,389 --> 00:02:58,859
So I mean, put yourself in the place

81
00:02:58,860 --> 00:03:01,049
of an average inhabitant of the ancient world.

82
00:03:01,050 --> 00:03:03,179
If you were an ancient person,

83
00:03:03,180 --> 00:03:05,670
three or four of your kids probably would've died.

84
00:03:05,669 --> 00:03:07,048
You would've buried your children.

85
00:03:07,050 --> 00:03:09,239
And nowadays, we think of that as an unusual thing.

86
00:03:09,240 --> 00:03:11,820
And just psychologically, that's a huge thing.

87
00:03:11,819 --> 00:03:14,282
You would've seen multiple of your siblings die.

88
00:03:15,150 --> 00:03:16,650
If you were a woman, for example,

89
00:03:16,650 --> 00:03:18,750
if you were lucky enough to make it to,

90
00:03:18,750 --> 00:03:20,639
let's say, age 13,

91
00:03:20,639 --> 00:03:25,528
you probably would have to give birth four or five times

92
00:03:25,530 --> 00:03:29,039
in order just to keep the population from dying out.

93
00:03:29,039 --> 00:03:32,999
So those kind of grim mortality statistics,

94
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:35,220
I think, are a huge difference, psychologically,

95
00:03:35,219 --> 00:03:37,138
between the ancient world and the modern.

96
00:03:37,139 --> 00:03:39,859
- But fundamentally, do you think human nature changed much?

97
00:03:39,860 --> 00:03:43,619
Do you think the same elements of what we see today,

98
00:03:43,620 --> 00:03:47,189
fear, greed, love, hope,

99
00:03:47,189 --> 00:03:49,318
optimism, and the cynicism,

100
00:03:49,319 --> 00:03:53,218
you know, the underlying forces that result in war,

101
00:03:53,219 --> 00:03:56,072
all of that permeates human history?

102
00:03:56,909 --> 00:03:58,379
- Crude answer, yes.

103
00:03:58,379 --> 00:04:01,888
I think human nature is roughly constant.

104
00:04:01,889 --> 00:04:04,438
And for me, as an ancient historian,

105
00:04:04,439 --> 00:04:07,258
the kind of documents that I really like dealing with

106
00:04:07,259 --> 00:04:10,859
are not the traditional literary sources,

107
00:04:10,860 --> 00:04:13,409
but they're the things that give us those little glimpse

108
00:04:13,409 --> 00:04:14,848
into everyday life.

109
00:04:14,849 --> 00:04:17,969
So stuff like tombstones or graffiti,

110
00:04:17,970 --> 00:04:21,630
or just something that survives on a scrap of parchment

111
00:04:21,629 --> 00:04:24,448
that records a financial transaction.

112
00:04:24,449 --> 00:04:26,279
And whenever I read some of those,

113
00:04:26,279 --> 00:04:29,916
I'll have this moment of, you know, feeling,

114
00:04:29,916 --> 00:04:32,158
"Oh, I know exactly how that person felt."

115
00:04:32,160 --> 00:04:34,439
Here across 2000 years of time,

116
00:04:34,439 --> 00:04:35,999
completely different cultures,

117
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:39,870
I have this spark of sympathy with someone from antiquity.

118
00:04:39,870 --> 00:04:41,370
And I think, as a historian,

119
00:04:41,370 --> 00:04:43,590
the way you begin to understand

120
00:04:43,589 --> 00:04:45,478
an alien, a foreign culture,

121
00:04:45,480 --> 00:04:47,129
which is what these cultures are,

122
00:04:47,129 --> 00:04:49,619
is to look for those little moments of sympathy.

123
00:04:49,620 --> 00:04:50,910
But on the other hand,

124
00:04:50,910 --> 00:04:53,220
there's ways in which ancient cultures

125
00:04:53,220 --> 00:04:55,679
are wildly different from us.

126
00:04:55,680 --> 00:04:58,176
So you also look for those moments where you just think,

127
00:04:58,177 --> 00:05:00,269
"How the hell could these people have done that?

128
00:05:00,269 --> 00:05:01,859
I just don't understand

129
00:05:01,860 --> 00:05:04,440
how they could have thought or acted in this way."

130
00:05:04,439 --> 00:05:07,499
And it's lining up those moments of sympathy

131
00:05:07,500 --> 00:05:09,569
and kind of disconnection

132
00:05:09,569 --> 00:05:12,359
that I think is when you begin to start to understand

133
00:05:12,360 --> 00:05:14,880
a foreign culture or an ancient culture.

134
00:05:14,879 --> 00:05:16,888
- I love the idea of assembling the big picture

135
00:05:16,889 --> 00:05:18,719
from the details and the little pieces,

136
00:05:18,720 --> 00:05:20,970
because that is the thing that makes up life.

137
00:05:20,970 --> 00:05:23,039
The big picture is nothing without the details.

138
00:05:23,040 --> 00:05:24,390
- Yep, yep, and those details

139
00:05:24,389 --> 00:05:25,919
would bring it to life, you know.

140
00:05:25,920 --> 00:05:28,440
I mean, it's not the grand sweep of things.

141
00:05:28,439 --> 00:05:31,499
It's seeing those little hopes and fears.

142
00:05:31,500 --> 00:05:33,720
Another thing that I think is a huge difference

143
00:05:33,720 --> 00:05:36,630
between the modern world and the ancient

144
00:05:36,629 --> 00:05:39,959
is just, basically, everybody's a farmer.

145
00:05:39,959 --> 00:05:41,878
Everybody's a small family farmer.

146
00:05:41,879 --> 00:05:42,989
And we forget this. - Yeah.

147
00:05:42,990 --> 00:05:44,730
- I was just writing a lecture

148
00:05:44,730 --> 00:05:47,100
for my next Great Courses course,

149
00:05:47,100 --> 00:05:49,530
and I was writing about farming in the ancient world.

150
00:05:49,529 --> 00:05:51,089
And I was really thinking,

151
00:05:51,089 --> 00:05:53,939
if we were to write a realistic textbook

152
00:05:53,939 --> 00:05:56,068
of, let's say, the Roman Empire,

153
00:05:56,069 --> 00:05:57,629
9 out of 10 chapter

154
00:05:57,629 --> 00:05:59,159
should be details of what it was like

155
00:05:59,160 --> 00:06:01,049
to be a small-time family farmer,

156
00:06:01,050 --> 00:06:03,659
because that's what 90% of the people

157
00:06:03,660 --> 00:06:05,460
in the ancient world did.

158
00:06:05,459 --> 00:06:07,259
They weren't soldiers, they weren't priests,

159
00:06:07,259 --> 00:06:09,029
they weren't kings, they weren't authors,

160
00:06:09,029 --> 00:06:10,619
they weren't artists,

161
00:06:10,620 --> 00:06:13,050
they were small town family farmers.

162
00:06:13,050 --> 00:06:15,150
And they lived in a little village,

163
00:06:15,149 --> 00:06:17,818
they never traveled 20 miles from that village,

164
00:06:17,819 --> 00:06:18,809
they were born there,

165
00:06:18,810 --> 00:06:20,100
they married somebody from there,

166
00:06:20,100 --> 00:06:20,1000
they raised kids,

167
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:23,370
they mucked around in the dirt for a couple decades,

168
00:06:23,370 --> 00:06:24,720
and they died.

169
00:06:24,720 --> 00:06:26,040
They never saw a battle,

170
00:06:26,040 --> 00:06:27,269
they never saw a work of art,

171
00:06:27,269 --> 00:06:28,918
they never saw a philosopher,

172
00:06:28,920 --> 00:06:30,989
they never took part in any of the things

173
00:06:30,990 --> 00:06:33,183
we define as being history.

174
00:06:34,319 --> 00:06:36,149
So that's what life should be,

175
00:06:36,149 --> 00:06:37,348
and that's representative.

176
00:06:37,350 --> 00:06:38,220
- Nevertheless,

177
00:06:38,220 --> 00:06:40,320
it is the emperors and the philosophers

178
00:06:40,319 --> 00:06:42,149
and the artists and the warriors

179
00:06:42,149 --> 00:06:43,229
who carve history.

180
00:06:43,230 --> 00:06:44,429
- And it is the important stuff.

181
00:06:44,430 --> 00:06:46,530
So, I mean, you know, that's true.

182
00:06:46,529 --> 00:06:48,208
There's a reason we focus on that.

183
00:06:48,209 --> 00:06:49,289
- That's a good reminder though.

184
00:06:49,290 --> 00:06:50,760
If we want to truly empathize

185
00:06:50,759 --> 00:06:53,339
and understand what life was like,

186
00:06:53,339 --> 00:06:56,279
we have to represent it fully.

187
00:06:56,279 --> 00:06:58,379
- And I would say, let's not forget them.

188
00:06:58,379 --> 00:07:00,599
So let's not forget what life was like

189
00:07:00,600 --> 00:07:03,090
for 80, 90% of the people in the ancient world,

190
00:07:03,089 --> 00:07:04,649
the ones we don't talk about,

191
00:07:04,649 --> 00:07:06,838
because that's important too.

192
00:07:06,839 --> 00:07:10,529
- So the Roman Empire is widely considered

193
00:07:10,529 --> 00:07:12,569
to be the most powerful, influential,

194
00:07:12,569 --> 00:07:16,439
and impactful empire in human history.

195
00:07:16,439 --> 00:07:18,689
What are some reasons for that?

196
00:07:18,689 --> 00:07:21,599
- Yeah, I mean, Rome is,

197
00:07:21,600 --> 00:07:24,240
has been hugely influential, I think,

198
00:07:24,240 --> 00:07:26,369
just because of the image.

199
00:07:26,370 --> 00:07:28,170
I mean, there's all these practical ways.

200
00:07:28,170 --> 00:07:31,350
I mean, the words I'm using to speak with you today,

201
00:07:31,350 --> 00:07:32,789
30% are direct from Latin,

202
00:07:32,790 --> 00:07:36,359
another 30% are from Latin descended languages.

203
00:07:36,360 --> 00:07:37,589
Our law codes,

204
00:07:37,589 --> 00:07:40,079
I mean, our habits, our holidays,

205
00:07:40,079 --> 00:07:43,349
everything comes fairly directly from the ancient world.

206
00:07:43,350 --> 00:07:45,150
But the image of Rome,

207
00:07:45,149 --> 00:07:47,158
at least, again, in Western civilization,

208
00:07:47,160 --> 00:07:50,853
has really been the dominant image of a successful empire.

209
00:07:51,990 --> 00:07:55,019
And I think that's what gives it a lot of its fascination.

210
00:07:55,019 --> 00:07:57,119
This idea that, "Oh, it was this great,

211
00:07:57,120 --> 00:07:59,579
powerful, culturally influential empire."

212
00:07:59,579 --> 00:08:01,199
And there's a lot of 'em, other empires.

213
00:08:01,199 --> 00:08:03,569
I mean, we could talk about Ancient China,

214
00:08:03,569 --> 00:08:06,118
which, arguably, was just as big as Rome,

215
00:08:06,120 --> 00:08:07,559
just as culturally sophisticated,

216
00:08:07,560 --> 00:08:09,870
lasted about the same amount of time.

217
00:08:09,870 --> 00:08:11,939
But, at least in Western civilization,

218
00:08:11,939 --> 00:08:13,979
Rome is the paradigm.

219
00:08:13,980 --> 00:08:15,720
But Rome is a little schizophrenic

220
00:08:15,720 --> 00:08:18,090
in that it's both the empire

221
00:08:18,089 --> 00:08:19,559
when it was ruled by emperors,

222
00:08:19,560 --> 00:08:20,997
which is one kind of model,

223
00:08:20,997 --> 00:08:23,340
and it's the Roman Republic

224
00:08:23,339 --> 00:08:25,859
when it was a pseudo democracy,

225
00:08:25,860 --> 00:08:27,480
which is a different model.

226
00:08:27,480 --> 00:08:31,170
And it's interesting how some later civilizations

227
00:08:31,170 --> 00:08:33,900
tend to either focus on one or the other of those.

228
00:08:33,899 --> 00:08:35,669
So, you know, the United States,

229
00:08:35,669 --> 00:08:36,749
revolutionary France,

230
00:08:36,750 --> 00:08:40,020
they were very obsessed with the Roman Republic as a model.

231
00:08:40,019 --> 00:08:40,859
But other people,

232
00:08:40,860 --> 00:08:43,139
Mussolini, Hitler, Napoleon,

233
00:08:43,139 --> 00:08:45,119
they were very obsessed with the empire,

234
00:08:45,120 --> 00:08:47,970
Victorian Britain, as a model.

235
00:08:47,970 --> 00:08:51,479
So Rome itself has different aspects,

236
00:08:51,480 --> 00:08:53,129
but what I think is actually another big difference

237
00:08:53,129 --> 00:08:55,468
between the modern world and the ancient

238
00:08:55,470 --> 00:08:58,470
is our relationship with the past.

239
00:08:58,470 --> 00:09:03,420
So one of the keys to understanding all of Roman history

240
00:09:03,419 --> 00:09:05,189
is to understand that this was a people

241
00:09:05,190 --> 00:09:07,199
who were obsessed with the past

242
00:09:07,200 --> 00:09:10,950
and for whom the past had power,

243
00:09:10,950 --> 00:09:13,139
not just as something inspirational,

244
00:09:13,139 --> 00:09:14,969
but it actually dictated

245
00:09:14,970 --> 00:09:17,220
what you would do in your daily life.

246
00:09:17,220 --> 00:09:19,979
And today, especially in the United States,

247
00:09:19,980 --> 00:09:22,680
we don't have much of a relationship with the past.

248
00:09:22,679 --> 00:09:24,598
We see ourselves as free agents,

249
00:09:24,600 --> 00:09:25,829
just floating along,

250
00:09:25,830 --> 00:09:28,229
not tethered to what came before.

251
00:09:28,230 --> 00:09:29,700
And the classical story

252
00:09:29,700 --> 00:09:31,290
that I sometimes tell in my classes

253
00:09:31,289 --> 00:09:32,379
to illustrate this is

254
00:09:33,809 --> 00:09:35,998
Rome started out as a monarchy.

255
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:37,199
They had kings,

256
00:09:37,200 --> 00:09:39,089
they were kind of unhappy with their kings,

257
00:09:39,090 --> 00:09:41,489
around 500 BC,

258
00:09:41,490 --> 00:09:42,719
they held a revolution

259
00:09:42,720 --> 00:09:44,190
and they kicked out the kings.

260
00:09:44,190 --> 00:09:46,050
And one of the guys who played a key role in this

261
00:09:46,049 --> 00:09:48,632
was a man named Lucius Junius Brutus, okay.

262
00:09:49,919 --> 00:09:51,745
500 years later,

263
00:09:51,745 --> 00:09:54,989
500 years down the road,

264
00:09:54,990 --> 00:09:56,879
a guy comes along, Julius Caesar,

265
00:09:56,879 --> 00:09:59,609
who starts to act like a king.

266
00:09:59,610 --> 00:10:02,850
So if you have trouble with kings in Roman society,

267
00:10:02,850 --> 00:10:04,229
who are you gonna call?

268
00:10:04,230 --> 00:10:06,030
Somebody named Brutus.

269
00:10:06,029 --> 00:10:07,049
Now, as it happens,

270
00:10:07,049 --> 00:10:10,019
there is a guy named Brutus in Roman society at this time,

271
00:10:10,019 --> 00:10:12,269
who's one of Julius Caesar's best friends,

272
00:10:12,269 --> 00:10:14,548
Marcus Junius Brutus.

273
00:10:14,549 --> 00:10:16,649
Now, before I go further with the story,

274
00:10:16,649 --> 00:10:18,652
and I think you probably know where it ends,

275
00:10:19,799 --> 00:10:22,379
I just talk about how important your ancestors are

276
00:10:22,379 --> 00:10:23,608
in Roman culture.

277
00:10:23,610 --> 00:10:26,489
I mean, if you went to an aristocrat Roman's house

278
00:10:26,490 --> 00:10:28,350
and opened the front door and walked in,

279
00:10:28,350 --> 00:10:31,290
the first thing you would see would be a big wooden cabinet.

280
00:10:31,289 --> 00:10:32,728
And if you open that up,

281
00:10:32,730 --> 00:10:35,910
what you would see would be row after row

282
00:10:35,909 --> 00:10:38,879
of wax death masks.

283
00:10:38,879 --> 00:10:40,379
So when a Roman aristocrat died,

284
00:10:40,379 --> 00:10:42,298
they literally put hot wax on his face

285
00:10:42,299 --> 00:10:44,578
and made an impression of his face at that moment.

286
00:10:44,580 --> 00:10:46,469
And they hung these in a big cabinet

287
00:10:46,470 --> 00:10:48,090
right inside the front door.

288
00:10:48,090 --> 00:10:49,739
So every time you entered your house,

289
00:10:49,740 --> 00:10:53,010
you were literally staring at the faces of your ancestors.

290
00:10:53,009 --> 00:10:55,979
And every child in that family

291
00:10:55,980 --> 00:10:58,799
would have obsessively memorized

292
00:10:58,799 --> 00:11:02,069
every accomplishment of every one of those ancestors.

293
00:11:02,070 --> 00:11:03,540
He would've known their career,

294
00:11:03,539 --> 00:11:04,469
what offices they held,

295
00:11:04,470 --> 00:11:05,520
what battles they fought in,

296
00:11:05,519 --> 00:11:07,139
what they did.

297
00:11:07,139 --> 00:11:09,208
When somebody new in the family died,

298
00:11:09,210 --> 00:11:10,379
there would be a big funeral,

299
00:11:10,379 --> 00:11:11,459
and they would talk about

300
00:11:11,460 --> 00:11:13,739
all the things their ancestors had did.

301
00:11:13,740 --> 00:11:16,800
The kids in the family would literally take out those masks,

302
00:11:16,799 --> 00:11:18,599
tie them onto their own faces,

303
00:11:18,600 --> 00:11:20,760
and wear them in the funeral possession.

304
00:11:20,759 --> 00:11:24,149
So you were like wearing the face of your ancestors.

305
00:11:24,149 --> 00:11:26,189
So you, as an individual, weren't important.

306
00:11:26,190 --> 00:11:29,549
You were just the latest iteration of that family.

307
00:11:29,549 --> 00:11:32,459
And there was enormous weight, huge weight,

308
00:11:32,460 --> 00:11:35,489
to live up to the deeds of your ancestors.

309
00:11:35,490 --> 00:11:37,889
So the Romans were absolutely obsessed with the past,

310
00:11:37,889 --> 00:11:39,778
especially with your own family.

311
00:11:39,779 --> 00:11:41,158
Every Roman kid, who is,

312
00:11:41,159 --> 00:11:42,358
let's say, in aristocrat family,

313
00:11:42,360 --> 00:11:45,569
could tell you every one of his ancestors backed centuries.

314
00:11:45,570 --> 00:11:47,100
I can't go beyond my grandparents,

315
00:11:47,100 --> 00:11:47,933
I don't even know,

316
00:11:47,932 --> 00:11:49,559
but that's, you know, maybe a hundred years.

317
00:11:49,559 --> 00:11:52,168
So it's a completely different attitude towards the past.

318
00:11:52,169 --> 00:11:53,429
- And the level of celebration

319
00:11:53,429 --> 00:11:55,229
that we have now of the ancestors,

320
00:11:55,230 --> 00:11:56,250
even the ones we can name,

321
00:11:56,250 --> 00:11:58,075
is not as intense as it was in the Roman times.

322
00:11:58,075 --> 00:11:58,908
- No, no, I mean,

323
00:11:58,908 --> 00:12:01,620
it was obsessive and oppressive.

324
00:12:01,620 --> 00:12:03,660
It determined what you did. - Oppressive. Oh.

325
00:12:03,659 --> 00:12:05,429
- Yes. Because there's that weight

326
00:12:05,429 --> 00:12:07,919
for you to act like your ancestors did.

327
00:12:07,919 --> 00:12:10,378
- Do you think, not to speak sort of philosophically,

328
00:12:10,379 --> 00:12:12,778
but do you think it was limiting

329
00:12:12,779 --> 00:12:14,939
to the way the society develops to be-

330
00:12:14,940 --> 00:12:18,839
- Yes, absolutely. - deeply constrained by the,

331
00:12:18,840 --> 00:12:21,210
limiting in a good way or a bad way, you think?

332
00:12:21,210 --> 00:12:22,320
- Well, you know, like everything,

333
00:12:22,320 --> 00:12:24,180
it's a little of both, but the bad...

334
00:12:24,179 --> 00:12:26,009
So on the one hand, it gives them enormous strength.

335
00:12:26,009 --> 00:12:27,629
And it gives them this enormous connection,

336
00:12:27,629 --> 00:12:28,529
it gives them guidance.

337
00:12:28,529 --> 00:12:30,448
But the negatives, what's interesting,

338
00:12:30,450 --> 00:12:33,900
is it makes the Romans extremely traditional-minded

339
00:12:33,899 --> 00:12:35,818
and extremely conservative.

340
00:12:35,820 --> 00:12:39,959
And I mean conservative in the sense of resistant to change.

341
00:12:39,960 --> 00:12:41,460
So in the late Republic,

342
00:12:41,460 --> 00:12:42,839
which we'll probably talk about later,

343
00:12:42,840 --> 00:12:45,690
Rome desperately needed to change certain things,

344
00:12:45,690 --> 00:12:48,180
but it was a society that did things

345
00:12:48,179 --> 00:12:49,739
the way the ancestors did it,

346
00:12:49,740 --> 00:12:52,170
and they didn't make some obvious changes,

347
00:12:52,169 --> 00:12:54,389
which might have saved the republic.

348
00:12:54,389 --> 00:12:55,679
So that's the downside

349
00:12:55,679 --> 00:12:57,239
is that it locks you into something

350
00:12:57,240 --> 00:12:58,860
and you can't change.

351
00:12:58,860 --> 00:13:01,080
But to get us back to the Brutuses,

352
00:13:01,080 --> 00:13:05,010
so 500 years after that first Brutus got rid of kings,

353
00:13:05,009 --> 00:13:06,629
Julius Caesar starts to act like a king,

354
00:13:06,629 --> 00:13:09,359
one of his best friends is Marcus Junius Brutus,

355
00:13:09,360 --> 00:13:11,130
and literally, in the middle of the night,

356
00:13:11,129 --> 00:13:12,749
people go to Brutus' house

357
00:13:12,750 --> 00:13:15,067
and write graffiti on it that says,

358
00:13:15,067 --> 00:13:18,300
"Remember your ancestor."

359
00:13:18,299 --> 00:13:22,078
And another one is, I think, "You are no real Brutus."

360
00:13:22,080 --> 00:13:23,400
And at that point,

361
00:13:23,399 --> 00:13:24,899
he really has no choice.

362
00:13:24,899 --> 00:13:26,429
He forms a conspiracy,

363
00:13:26,429 --> 00:13:28,589
and on the Ides of March, 44 BC,

364
00:13:28,590 --> 00:13:31,230
he and 23 other senators take daggers,

365
00:13:31,230 --> 00:13:32,520
stick them in Julius Caesar,

366
00:13:32,519 --> 00:13:34,739
and kill him for acting like a king.

367
00:13:34,740 --> 00:13:37,139
So the way I always pose this to my students is,

368
00:13:37,980 --> 00:13:42,300
how many of you would stick a knife in your best friend

369
00:13:42,299 --> 00:13:44,609
because of what your great, great, great, great,

370
00:13:44,610 --> 00:13:46,259
great, great, great, great, great, great, great,

371
00:13:46,259 --> 00:13:48,899
great grandfather did?

372
00:13:48,899 --> 00:13:50,189
- That's commitment.

373
00:13:50,190 --> 00:13:52,259
- That's the power of the past.

374
00:13:52,259 --> 00:13:55,739
That's a society where the past isn't just influential,

375
00:13:55,740 --> 00:13:57,659
but it dictates what you do.

376
00:13:57,659 --> 00:14:01,259
And that concept, I think, is very alien to us today.

377
00:14:01,259 --> 00:14:03,448
We can't imagine murdering our best friend

378
00:14:03,450 --> 00:14:06,027
because of what some incredibly distant ancestor did

379
00:14:06,027 --> 00:14:07,349
500 years ago.

380
00:14:07,350 --> 00:14:10,019
But to Brutus, there is no choice.

381
00:14:10,019 --> 00:14:11,668
You have to do that.

382
00:14:11,669 --> 00:14:14,968
And a lot of societies have this power of the past.

383
00:14:14,970 --> 00:14:17,530
Today, not so much, but some still do.

384
00:14:17,529 --> 00:14:20,368
About a decade ago, I was in Serbia,

385
00:14:20,370 --> 00:14:22,259
and I was talking to some of the people there

386
00:14:22,259 --> 00:14:24,268
about the breakup of Yugoslavia

387
00:14:24,269 --> 00:14:25,948
and some of the wars that had taken place

388
00:14:25,950 --> 00:14:27,810
where people turned against their neighbors,

389
00:14:27,809 --> 00:14:28,978
basically murdered people

390
00:14:28,980 --> 00:14:31,290
they had lived next to for decades.

391
00:14:31,289 --> 00:14:32,609
And when I was talking to them,

392
00:14:32,610 --> 00:14:35,137
some of them actually brought up things like,

393
00:14:35,136 --> 00:14:36,658
"Oh, well, it was justified

394
00:14:36,659 --> 00:14:39,179
because in this battle in 12 whatever,

395
00:14:39,179 --> 00:14:40,285
they did this."

396
00:14:40,287 --> 00:14:41,1000
And I was thinking, "Wow,

397
00:14:42,000 --> 00:14:44,730
you're citing something from 800 years ago

398
00:14:44,730 --> 00:14:47,069
to justify your actions today."

399
00:14:47,070 --> 00:14:48,989
That's a modern person

400
00:14:48,990 --> 00:14:51,389
who still understands the power of the past,

401
00:14:51,389 --> 00:14:54,148
or maybe is, you know, crippled by it

402
00:14:54,149 --> 00:14:55,739
is another way to view it.

403
00:14:55,740 --> 00:14:57,749
- So this is an interesting point

404
00:14:57,750 --> 00:14:59,340
and an interesting perspective to remember

405
00:14:59,340 --> 00:15:00,810
about the way the Romans thought,

406
00:15:00,809 --> 00:15:05,039
especially in the context of how power is transferred,

407
00:15:05,039 --> 00:15:07,349
whether it's hereditary or not,

408
00:15:07,350 --> 00:15:09,720
which changes throughout Roman history.

409
00:15:09,720 --> 00:15:10,553
So it's interesting.

410
00:15:10,552 --> 00:15:11,909
It's interesting to remember that,

411
00:15:11,909 --> 00:15:14,219
the value of the ancestors. - Yep.

412
00:15:14,220 --> 00:15:15,930
And just the weight of tradition.

413
00:15:15,929 --> 00:15:16,762
- The weight of tradition.

414
00:15:16,763 --> 00:15:18,110
- The Romans, the mos maiorum

415
00:15:18,110 --> 00:15:19,593
is this Latin term which means

416
00:15:19,592 --> 00:15:21,809
'the way the ancestors did it.'

417
00:15:21,809 --> 00:15:23,938
And it's kind of their word for tradition.

418
00:15:23,940 --> 00:15:27,540
So for them, tradition is what your forefathers

419
00:15:27,539 --> 00:15:28,948
and mothers did.

420
00:15:28,950 --> 00:15:30,510
And you have to follow that example

421
00:15:30,509 --> 00:15:31,769
and you have to live up to that.

422
00:15:31,769 --> 00:15:34,048
- Does that mean that class mobility was difficult?

423
00:15:34,049 --> 00:15:36,539
So if your ancestors were farmers,

424
00:15:36,539 --> 00:15:38,309
there was a major constraint

425
00:15:38,309 --> 00:15:40,289
on remaining a farmer, essentially?

426
00:15:40,289 --> 00:15:41,609
- I mean,

427
00:15:41,610 --> 00:15:43,770
the Romans all like to think of themselves as farmers,

428
00:15:43,769 --> 00:15:45,089
even filthy rich Romans.

429
00:15:45,090 --> 00:15:47,009
It was just their national identity

430
00:15:47,009 --> 00:15:49,408
is the citizen, soldier, farmer thing.

431
00:15:49,409 --> 00:15:51,868
But it did, among the aristocrats,

432
00:15:51,870 --> 00:15:53,613
the people who kind of ran things,

433
00:15:54,659 --> 00:15:56,548
yeah, it was hard to break into that

434
00:15:56,549 --> 00:15:59,069
if you didn't have famous ancestors.

435
00:15:59,070 --> 00:16:00,390
And it was such a big deal

436
00:16:00,389 --> 00:16:01,768
that there was a specific term

437
00:16:01,769 --> 00:16:04,409
called a novus homo, a new man,

438
00:16:04,409 --> 00:16:08,038
for someone who was the first person in their family

439
00:16:08,039 --> 00:16:11,068
to get elected to a major office in the Roman government

440
00:16:11,070 --> 00:16:12,630
because that was a weird

441
00:16:12,629 --> 00:16:14,159
and different and new thing,

442
00:16:14,159 --> 00:16:17,159
so you actually designated them by this special term.

443
00:16:17,159 --> 00:16:18,959
So yeah, you're absolutely right.

444
00:16:18,960 --> 00:16:21,390
- So if we may, let us zoom out.

445
00:16:21,389 --> 00:16:23,129
It would help me, maybe it'll help the audience

446
00:16:23,129 --> 00:16:24,239
to look at the different periods

447
00:16:24,240 --> 00:16:26,369
that we've been talking about.

448
00:16:26,370 --> 00:16:28,019
So you mentioned the republic.

449
00:16:28,019 --> 00:16:30,745
You mentioned maybe when it took a form of empire

450
00:16:30,746 --> 00:16:33,089
and maybe there was the age of kings.

451
00:16:33,090 --> 00:16:36,090
What are the different periods of this Roman,

452
00:16:36,090 --> 00:16:37,560
let's call it what the big...

453
00:16:37,559 --> 00:16:39,869
- Roman history. Yep. - Roman history.

454
00:16:39,870 --> 00:16:42,149
And a lot of people just call that whole period

455
00:16:42,149 --> 00:16:44,158
Roman Empire loosely, right?

456
00:16:44,159 --> 00:16:45,743
So maybe can you speak to the different periods firstly?

457
00:16:45,744 --> 00:16:47,490
- Yes, absolutely. So conventionally,

458
00:16:47,490 --> 00:16:51,360
Roman history is divided into three chronological periods.

459
00:16:51,360 --> 00:16:54,880
The first of those is from 773 BC to 509 BC,

460
00:16:56,970 --> 00:16:58,230
which is called the monarchy.

461
00:16:58,230 --> 00:16:59,550
So all the periods get their names

462
00:16:59,549 --> 00:17:01,019
from the form of government.

463
00:17:01,019 --> 00:17:03,838
So this is the earliest phase of Roman history.

464
00:17:03,840 --> 00:17:05,969
It's when Rome is mostly just

465
00:17:05,970 --> 00:17:07,800
a fairly undistinguished

466
00:17:07,799 --> 00:17:09,928
little collection of mud huts, honestly,

467
00:17:09,930 --> 00:17:11,999
just like dozens of other cities

468
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:14,009
of little mud huts in Italy.

469
00:17:14,009 --> 00:17:15,119
So that early phase,

470
00:17:15,119 --> 00:17:18,719
about 750 to around 500 BC,

471
00:17:18,720 --> 00:17:20,940
is the monarchy, they're ruled by kings.

472
00:17:20,940 --> 00:17:22,440
Then there's this revolution,

473
00:17:22,440 --> 00:17:23,460
they kick out the kings,

474
00:17:23,460 --> 00:17:25,050
they become a republic.

475
00:17:25,049 --> 00:17:29,098
That lasts from 500 BC roughly to,

476
00:17:29,099 --> 00:17:31,949
eh, about either 31 or 27 BC,

477
00:17:31,950 --> 00:17:33,839
depending on what date you pick is most important,

478
00:17:33,839 --> 00:17:35,728
but about 500 years.

479
00:17:35,730 --> 00:17:37,409
And the republic is when they have

480
00:17:37,410 --> 00:17:39,780
a Republican form of government.

481
00:17:39,779 --> 00:17:42,479
Some people idealize this as Rome's greatest period.

482
00:17:42,480 --> 00:17:43,709
And the big thing in that period

483
00:17:43,710 --> 00:17:47,149
is Rome first expands to conquer all of Italy

484
00:17:47,150 --> 00:17:50,250
in the first 250 years of that 500 year stretch,

485
00:17:50,250 --> 00:17:51,810
and then the second 250 years,

486
00:17:51,809 --> 00:17:54,299
they conquer all the Mediterranean basin, roughly.

487
00:17:54,299 --> 00:17:56,339
So this is this time of enormous

488
00:17:56,339 --> 00:17:59,638
successful Roman conquest and expansion.

489
00:17:59,640 --> 00:18:01,319
And then you have another switch up

490
00:18:01,319 --> 00:18:04,319
and they become ruled by emperors.

491
00:18:04,319 --> 00:18:06,988
So back to the idea of one guy in charge,

492
00:18:06,990 --> 00:18:09,389
though the Romans try to pretend it's not like a king,

493
00:18:09,390 --> 00:18:10,410
it's something else, and...

494
00:18:10,410 --> 00:18:11,670
Anyway, we can get into that,

495
00:18:11,670 --> 00:18:13,440
but they're very touchy about kings.

496
00:18:13,440 --> 00:18:16,560
So they have emperors, Roman empire.

497
00:18:16,559 --> 00:18:19,108
The first emperor is Augustus.

498
00:18:19,109 --> 00:18:20,548
Starts off as Octavian,

499
00:18:20,549 --> 00:18:23,459
switches the name to Augustus when he becomes emperor.

500
00:18:23,460 --> 00:18:26,069
He kind of sets the model for what happens.

501
00:18:26,069 --> 00:18:29,339
And then how long does the Roman Empire last?

502
00:18:29,339 --> 00:18:31,859
That's one of those great questions.

503
00:18:31,859 --> 00:18:33,209
The conventional answer

504
00:18:33,210 --> 00:18:35,580
is usually sometime in the 5th century,

505
00:18:35,579 --> 00:18:37,319
so the 400s AD.

506
00:18:37,319 --> 00:18:39,629
So about another 500 years, let's say.

507
00:18:39,630 --> 00:18:41,490
So nice kind of even division.

508
00:18:41,490 --> 00:18:44,280
500 years of republic, 500 years of empire.

509
00:18:44,279 --> 00:18:47,848
But you can make very good cases for lots of other dates

510
00:18:47,849 --> 00:18:50,038
for the end of the Roman Empire.

511
00:18:50,039 --> 00:18:51,396
I actually think it goes all the way

512
00:18:51,396 --> 00:18:53,879
through the end of the Byzantine Empire in 1453,

513
00:18:53,880 --> 00:18:56,009
so another 1500 years.

514
00:18:56,009 --> 00:18:57,658
But that's a whole another discussion.

515
00:18:57,660 --> 00:18:59,307
But, so that's your three phases of Roman history.

516
00:18:59,307 --> 00:19:01,099
- And in some fundamental way,

517
00:19:01,099 --> 00:19:02,969
it still persists today

518
00:19:02,970 --> 00:19:06,210
given how much of its ideas

519
00:19:06,210 --> 00:19:07,349
define our modern life,

520
00:19:07,349 --> 00:19:08,879
especially in the Western world.

521
00:19:08,880 --> 00:19:09,713
- Yeah.

522
00:19:09,712 --> 00:19:12,569
- Can you speak to the relationship

523
00:19:12,569 --> 00:19:15,928
between Ancient Greece and Roman Empire,

524
00:19:15,930 --> 00:19:17,550
both in the chronological sense

525
00:19:17,549 --> 00:19:19,859
and in the influence sense?

526
00:19:19,859 --> 00:19:23,099
- Well, I mean, Ancient Greece comes,

527
00:19:23,099 --> 00:19:25,739
the classical era of Greek civilization

528
00:19:25,740 --> 00:19:28,920
is around the 500s BC.

529
00:19:28,920 --> 00:19:31,799
That's when you have the great achievements of Athens.

530
00:19:31,799 --> 00:19:34,589
It becomes the first sort of true democracy.

531
00:19:34,589 --> 00:19:36,478
They defeat the Persian invasions.

532
00:19:36,480 --> 00:19:38,100
A lot of the famous stuff happens

533
00:19:38,099 --> 00:19:41,219
around in the 400s, let's say.

534
00:19:41,220 --> 00:19:44,519
So that is contemporaneous with Rome,

535
00:19:44,519 --> 00:19:47,431
but the Greek civilization sense is peaking earlier.

536
00:19:48,400 --> 00:19:50,429
And one of the things that happens is that

537
00:19:50,430 --> 00:19:52,769
Greece ends up being conquered by Rome

538
00:19:52,769 --> 00:19:55,079
in that second half of the Roman Republic,

539
00:19:55,079 --> 00:19:57,898
between 250 and about 30 BC.

540
00:19:57,900 --> 00:20:01,259
And so Greece falls under the control of Rome

541
00:20:01,259 --> 00:20:05,759
and Rome is very heavily influenced by Greek culture.

542
00:20:05,759 --> 00:20:09,239
They themselves see the Greeks as a superior civilization,

543
00:20:09,240 --> 00:20:10,889
culturally more sophisticated,

544
00:20:10,890 --> 00:20:13,289
great art, great philosophy, all this.

545
00:20:13,289 --> 00:20:14,999
And another thing about the Romans

546
00:20:15,000 --> 00:20:17,640
is they're super competitive.

547
00:20:17,640 --> 00:20:18,750
So one of the things that,

548
00:20:18,750 --> 00:20:22,259
one of the engines that drives Romans

549
00:20:22,259 --> 00:20:24,479
is this public competitiveness,

550
00:20:24,480 --> 00:20:27,029
especially among the upper classes.

551
00:20:27,029 --> 00:20:29,368
They care more about their status

552
00:20:29,369 --> 00:20:31,288
and standing among their peers

553
00:20:31,289 --> 00:20:34,139
than they do about money or even their own life.

554
00:20:34,140 --> 00:20:36,059
So there's this intense competition.

555
00:20:36,059 --> 00:20:38,219
And when they conquer Greece,

556
00:20:38,220 --> 00:20:42,389
Greek culture just becomes one more arena of competition.

557
00:20:42,390 --> 00:20:44,700
So Romans will start to learn Greek,

558
00:20:44,700 --> 00:20:46,650
they'll start to memorize Homer,

559
00:20:46,650 --> 00:20:49,590
they'll start to see who can quote more passages of Homer

560
00:20:49,589 --> 00:20:51,389
in Greek, in their letters to one another

561
00:20:51,390 --> 00:20:53,789
because that increases their status.

562
00:20:53,789 --> 00:20:56,668
So Rome kind of absorbs Greek civilization,

563
00:20:56,670 --> 00:20:59,339
and then the two get fused together.

564
00:20:59,339 --> 00:21:01,289
The other thing I should mention in terms of influences

565
00:21:01,289 --> 00:21:04,199
that's really huge on Rome is the Etruscan.

566
00:21:04,200 --> 00:21:06,599
And this is one that comes along before the Greeks.

567
00:21:06,599 --> 00:21:08,788
So the Etruscans were this,

568
00:21:08,789 --> 00:21:11,128
eh, kind of mysterious culture

569
00:21:11,130 --> 00:21:12,809
that flourished in northern Italy

570
00:21:12,809 --> 00:21:16,142
before the Romans, so way back 800 BC.

571
00:21:16,143 --> 00:21:18,120
They were much more powerful than the Romans.

572
00:21:18,119 --> 00:21:20,639
They were kind a loose confederation of states.

573
00:21:20,640 --> 00:21:21,809
For awhile, the Romans even seemed

574
00:21:21,809 --> 00:21:23,759
to have been under Etruscan control,

575
00:21:23,759 --> 00:21:25,529
the last of the Roman kings

576
00:21:25,529 --> 00:21:27,691
was really an Etruscan guy, pretty clearly.

577
00:21:28,559 --> 00:21:32,789
But the Etruscans end up giving to Rome,

578
00:21:32,789 --> 00:21:34,918
or you could say Romans up stealing

579
00:21:34,920 --> 00:21:39,089
perhaps a lot of elements of Etruscan culture.

580
00:21:39,089 --> 00:21:40,978
And many of the things that we today

581
00:21:40,980 --> 00:21:43,350
think of as distinctively Roman,

582
00:21:43,349 --> 00:21:46,168
that, you know, it was our cliches of what a Roman is

583
00:21:46,170 --> 00:21:47,940
actually aren't truly Roman.

584
00:21:47,940 --> 00:21:50,100
They're stuff they stole from the Etruscans.

585
00:21:50,099 --> 00:21:52,529
So just a couple examples, the toga?

586
00:21:52,529 --> 00:21:53,549
What do you think of a Roman?

587
00:21:53,549 --> 00:21:54,748
It's a guy wearing a toga,

588
00:21:54,750 --> 00:21:56,550
and the toga's the mark of Roman citizen.

589
00:21:56,549 --> 00:21:59,368
Well, that's what Etruscan kings wore, probably.

590
00:21:59,369 --> 00:22:00,568
Gladiator games,

591
00:22:00,569 --> 00:22:03,328
we associate those very intensely with the Romans.

592
00:22:03,329 --> 00:22:05,728
Well, they probably stole that from the Etruscans.

593
00:22:05,730 --> 00:22:07,799
A lot of Roman religion.

594
00:22:07,799 --> 00:22:09,749
Jupiter is a thunder God,

595
00:22:09,750 --> 00:22:11,159
all sorts of divination.

596
00:22:11,160 --> 00:22:13,499
The Romans love to, you know, chop open animals

597
00:22:13,500 --> 00:22:16,290
and look at their livers and predict the future.

598
00:22:16,289 --> 00:22:18,269
That comes from the Etruscans.

599
00:22:18,269 --> 00:22:21,028
Watching the flight of birds to predict the future.

600
00:22:21,029 --> 00:22:22,739
That comes from the Etruscans.

601
00:22:22,740 --> 00:22:25,320
So there's a lot of central elements

602
00:22:25,319 --> 00:22:27,508
of what we think of is Roman civilization,

603
00:22:27,509 --> 00:22:30,209
which actually are borrowings, let's say,

604
00:22:30,210 --> 00:22:33,060
from the these older, slightly mysterious Etruscans.

605
00:22:33,059 --> 00:22:35,369
- I mean, that's a really powerful thing

606
00:22:35,369 --> 00:22:37,319
as a powerful aspect of a civilization

607
00:22:37,319 --> 00:22:39,208
to be able to, we can call it stealing,

608
00:22:39,210 --> 00:22:40,950
which is a negative connotation,

609
00:22:40,950 --> 00:22:43,349
but you can also see its integration, basically.

610
00:22:44,309 --> 00:22:48,059
Yes, steal the best stuff from the peoples you conquer

611
00:22:48,059 --> 00:22:53,039
or the people's that you interact with.

612
00:22:53,039 --> 00:22:55,559
Not every empire does that.

613
00:22:55,559 --> 00:23:00,559
There's a lot of nations and empires that when they conquer,

614
00:23:00,630 --> 00:23:02,790
they annihilate versus integrate.

615
00:23:02,789 --> 00:23:06,298
And so it's an interesting thing to be able to, culturally.

616
00:23:06,299 --> 00:23:09,868
Like the form that the competitiveness takes

617
00:23:09,869 --> 00:23:13,619
is that you want to compete in the realm of ideas in culture

618
00:23:13,619 --> 00:23:18,619
versus compete strictly in the realm of military conquest.

619
00:23:19,529 --> 00:23:21,718
- Yeah, and I think you've exactly put your finger

620
00:23:21,720 --> 00:23:25,349
on one of the, let's say, secrets of Rome's success,

621
00:23:25,349 --> 00:23:29,849
which is that they're very good at integrating non-Romans

622
00:23:29,849 --> 00:23:31,498
or non-Roman ideas

623
00:23:31,500 --> 00:23:33,389
and kind of absorbing them.

624
00:23:33,390 --> 00:23:36,419
So one of the things that's absolutely crucial

625
00:23:36,420 --> 00:23:37,750
early in Roman history

626
00:23:38,946 --> 00:23:41,909
when they're just one of these tiny little mud hut villages

627
00:23:41,910 --> 00:23:44,160
fighting dozens of other mud hut villages in Italy,

628
00:23:44,160 --> 00:23:46,499
why does Rome emerge as the dominant one?

629
00:23:46,500 --> 00:23:47,970
Well, one of the things they do

630
00:23:47,970 --> 00:23:51,150
is when they do finally succeed in conquering somebody else,

631
00:23:51,150 --> 00:23:53,940
let's say another Italianate people,

632
00:23:53,940 --> 00:23:55,379
they do something very unusual.

633
00:23:55,380 --> 00:23:57,210
Because the normal procedure in the ancient world

634
00:23:57,210 --> 00:23:58,140
is you conquer some,

635
00:23:58,140 --> 00:23:59,819
let's say you conquer another city,

636
00:23:59,819 --> 00:24:02,008
you often kill most of the men

637
00:24:02,009 --> 00:24:03,269
and slave the women and children,

638
00:24:03,269 --> 00:24:05,219
steal all the stuff, right?

639
00:24:05,220 --> 00:24:07,679
The Romans, at least with the Italians,

640
00:24:07,680 --> 00:24:08,940
conquer the other city,

641
00:24:08,940 --> 00:24:10,169
and sometimes they'll do that,

642
00:24:10,170 --> 00:24:11,797
but sometimes they'll also then say,

643
00:24:11,797 --> 00:24:14,130
"All right, we're gonna now leave you alone

644
00:24:14,130 --> 00:24:16,290
and we're going to share with you

645
00:24:16,289 --> 00:24:18,838
a degree of Roman citizenship."

646
00:24:18,839 --> 00:24:20,579
Sometimes that make them full citizens,

647
00:24:20,579 --> 00:24:23,369
more often that make them something we call half citizens,

648
00:24:23,369 --> 00:24:24,905
which is kind of what sounds like

649
00:24:24,905 --> 00:24:26,429
you get some of the privileges of citizenship,

650
00:24:26,430 --> 00:24:27,390
but not all of them.

651
00:24:27,390 --> 00:24:29,399
Sometimes they would just make them allies,

652
00:24:29,400 --> 00:24:30,930
but they would sort of incorporate them

653
00:24:30,930 --> 00:24:33,300
into the Roman project.

654
00:24:33,299 --> 00:24:36,328
And they wouldn't necessarily ask for money or taxes,

655
00:24:36,329 --> 00:24:37,738
which is weird too,

656
00:24:37,740 --> 00:24:42,299
but instead, the one thing they would always, always demand

657
00:24:42,299 --> 00:24:43,821
from the conquered cities in Italy

658
00:24:43,823 --> 00:24:46,923
is that they provide troops to the Roman army.

659
00:24:47,759 --> 00:24:51,778
So the army becomes this mechanism of Romanization

660
00:24:51,779 --> 00:24:53,759
where you pull in foreigners,

661
00:24:53,759 --> 00:24:55,319
you make them like you,

662
00:24:55,319 --> 00:24:58,019
and then they end up fighting for you.

663
00:24:58,019 --> 00:25:01,648
And early on, the secret to Rome's military success

664
00:25:01,650 --> 00:25:03,480
is not that they have better generals,

665
00:25:03,480 --> 00:25:04,800
it's not that they have better equipment,

666
00:25:04,799 --> 00:25:07,138
it's not that they have better strategy or tactics,

667
00:25:07,140 --> 00:25:11,340
it's that they have limitless manpower, relatively speaking.

668
00:25:11,339 --> 00:25:12,929
So they lose a war,

669
00:25:12,930 --> 00:25:14,460
and they just come back and fight again.

670
00:25:14,460 --> 00:25:15,659
And they lose again,

671
00:25:15,660 --> 00:25:17,610
and they come back and they fight again.

672
00:25:17,609 --> 00:25:20,249
And eventually, they just wear down their enemies

673
00:25:20,250 --> 00:25:22,410
because their key thing of their policy

674
00:25:22,410 --> 00:25:25,110
is we incorporate the conquered people.

675
00:25:25,109 --> 00:25:27,479
And the great moment that just exemplifies this

676
00:25:27,480 --> 00:25:29,159
is pretty late in this process.

677
00:25:29,160 --> 00:25:31,829
So they've been doing this for 250 years, just about.

678
00:25:31,829 --> 00:25:33,929
And they've gotten down to the toe of Italy,

679
00:25:33,930 --> 00:25:37,110
they're conquering the very last cities down there.

680
00:25:37,109 --> 00:25:39,028
And one of the last cities is actually a Greek city;

681
00:25:39,029 --> 00:25:40,438
it's a Greek colony.

682
00:25:40,440 --> 00:25:41,460
It's a wealthy city,

683
00:25:41,460 --> 00:25:43,410
and so when the Romans show up on the doorstep

684
00:25:43,410 --> 00:25:45,150
and are about to attack them,

685
00:25:45,150 --> 00:25:47,730
they do what any rich Greek colony or city does.

686
00:25:47,730 --> 00:25:50,220
They go out and hire the best mercenaries they can.

687
00:25:50,220 --> 00:25:52,260
And they hire this guy who thinks of himself

688
00:25:52,259 --> 00:25:54,388
as the new Alexander the Great,

689
00:25:54,390 --> 00:25:55,350
a man named Pyrrhus of Epirus.

690
00:25:55,349 --> 00:25:56,699
So he is a mercenary,

691
00:25:56,700 --> 00:25:59,880
he is actually related to Alexander, distantly.

692
00:25:59,880 --> 00:26:02,429
He has a terrific army, top-notch army.

693
00:26:02,430 --> 00:26:03,960
He's got elephants,

694
00:26:03,960 --> 00:26:06,690
you know, he's got all the latest military technology.

695
00:26:06,690 --> 00:26:08,819
The Romans come and fight a battle against him,

696
00:26:08,819 --> 00:26:10,258
and Pyrrhus knows what he's doing.

697
00:26:10,259 --> 00:26:12,388
He wipes out the Romans.

698
00:26:12,390 --> 00:26:14,789
He thinks, "Okay, now we'll have a peace treaty,

699
00:26:14,789 --> 00:26:16,139
we'll negotiate something,

700
00:26:16,140 --> 00:26:17,430
I can go home."

701
00:26:17,430 --> 00:26:19,439
But the Romans won't even talk.

702
00:26:19,440 --> 00:26:22,410
They go to their Italian allies and half citizens,

703
00:26:22,410 --> 00:26:23,670
they raise a second army,

704
00:26:23,670 --> 00:26:25,496
they send them against Pyrrhus.

705
00:26:25,496 --> 00:26:26,329
Pyrrhus says, "Okay,

706
00:26:26,328 --> 00:26:28,589
these guys are slow learners. Fine."

707
00:26:28,589 --> 00:26:30,988
He fights them again, wipes them out.

708
00:26:30,990 --> 00:26:33,269
Thinks now we'll have a peace treaty.

709
00:26:33,269 --> 00:26:35,188
But the Romans go back to the allies,

710
00:26:35,190 --> 00:26:36,210
raise a third army,

711
00:26:36,210 --> 00:26:38,279
and send it after Pyrrhus.

712
00:26:38,279 --> 00:26:41,405
And when he sees that third army coming, he says,

713
00:26:41,406 --> 00:26:44,878
"I can't afford to win another battle.

714
00:26:44,880 --> 00:26:45,960
I win these battles,

715
00:26:45,960 --> 00:26:48,210
but each time, I lose some of my troops

716
00:26:48,210 --> 00:26:49,680
and I can't replace them.

717
00:26:49,680 --> 00:26:53,010
And the Romans just keeps sprouting new armies."

718
00:26:53,009 --> 00:26:54,928
So he gives up and goes home.

719
00:26:54,930 --> 00:26:57,660
So Rome kind of loses every battle,

720
00:26:57,660 --> 00:26:59,280
but wins the war.

721
00:26:59,279 --> 00:27:01,408
And Pyrrhus, one of his,

722
00:27:01,410 --> 00:27:03,120
actually, his officers has a great line

723
00:27:03,119 --> 00:27:04,439
as they're kind of going back to Greece.

724
00:27:04,440 --> 00:27:08,819
He says, "Fighting the Romans is like fighting a hydra."

725
00:27:08,819 --> 00:27:11,459
And a hydra is this mythological monster

726
00:27:11,460 --> 00:27:13,349
that when you cut off one head,

727
00:27:13,349 --> 00:27:15,418
two more grow in its place.

728
00:27:15,420 --> 00:27:18,029
So you can just never win. - That's fascinating.

729
00:27:18,029 --> 00:27:20,412
- So that's the secret to Rome's early success.

730
00:27:20,413 --> 00:27:22,590
- That's not the military strategy.

731
00:27:22,589 --> 00:27:26,368
It's not some technological asymmetry of power.

732
00:27:26,369 --> 00:27:28,288
It's literally just manpower.

733
00:27:28,289 --> 00:27:30,296
- Uh-huh. Early on. - Early on.

734
00:27:30,297 --> 00:27:33,150
- And later, the Romans get very good when,

735
00:27:33,150 --> 00:27:34,650
we're into the empire phase now,

736
00:27:34,650 --> 00:27:37,380
so once they have emperors into the AD era,

737
00:27:37,380 --> 00:27:41,190
of kind of doing the same thing

738
00:27:41,190 --> 00:27:45,869
by drawing in the best and the brightest

739
00:27:45,869 --> 00:27:47,008
and the most ambitious

740
00:27:47,009 --> 00:27:50,489
and the most talented local leaders

741
00:27:50,490 --> 00:27:51,719
of the people they conquer.

742
00:27:51,720 --> 00:27:53,460
So when they go someplace,

743
00:27:53,460 --> 00:27:56,430
let say they conquer tribe of what to them as barbarians,

744
00:27:56,430 --> 00:27:59,490
they'll often take the sons of the barbarian chiefs,

745
00:27:59,490 --> 00:28:00,510
bring them to Rome,

746
00:28:00,509 --> 00:28:02,549
and raise them as Romans. - Damn.

747
00:28:02,549 --> 00:28:04,079
- And so it's that whole way

748
00:28:04,079 --> 00:28:07,529
of kind of turning your enemies into your own strength.

749
00:28:07,529 --> 00:28:10,979
And the Romans start giving citizenship

750
00:28:10,980 --> 00:28:12,090
to areas they conquer.

751
00:28:12,089 --> 00:28:13,649
So once they move out of Italy,

752
00:28:13,650 --> 00:28:15,329
they aren't as free with the citizenship,

753
00:28:15,329 --> 00:28:16,558
but eventually they do.

754
00:28:16,559 --> 00:28:18,061
So they make Spain,

755
00:28:18,900 --> 00:28:19,800
lost cities in Spain,

756
00:28:19,799 --> 00:28:20,819
they make all citizens,

757
00:28:20,819 --> 00:28:21,958
and other places.

758
00:28:21,960 --> 00:28:23,633
And soon enough, the Roman emperors

759
00:28:23,633 --> 00:28:27,120
and the Roman senators are not Italians.

760
00:28:27,119 --> 00:28:29,668
They're coming from Spain or North Africa

761
00:28:29,670 --> 00:28:31,679
or Germany or wherever.

762
00:28:31,680 --> 00:28:34,490
So, you know, as early as the second century AD

763
00:28:34,490 --> 00:28:36,119
of the Roman Empire,

764
00:28:36,119 --> 00:28:37,768
so the first set of emperors,

765
00:28:37,769 --> 00:28:39,958
the first hundred years were all Italians.

766
00:28:39,960 --> 00:28:42,330
But right away, at the beginning of the second century AD,

767
00:28:42,329 --> 00:28:44,398
you have Trajan, who's from Spain,

768
00:28:44,400 --> 00:28:46,140
and the next guy, Hadrian, is from Spain.

769
00:28:46,140 --> 00:28:48,120
And then a century later, you have Septimius Severus,

770
00:28:48,119 --> 00:28:50,188
who's from North Africa.

771
00:28:50,190 --> 00:28:52,020
You would later get guys from Syria.

772
00:28:52,019 --> 00:28:54,659
So I mean, the actual leaders of the Roman Empire

773
00:28:54,660 --> 00:28:56,700
are coming from the provinces.

774
00:28:56,700 --> 00:28:58,410
- That's brilliant. - And it's that openness

775
00:28:58,410 --> 00:29:00,840
to incorporating foreigners,

776
00:29:00,839 --> 00:29:01,978
making them work for you,

777
00:29:01,980 --> 00:29:04,980
making them want to be part of your empire

778
00:29:04,980 --> 00:29:07,290
that I think is one of the Rome strengths.

779
00:29:07,289 --> 00:29:09,929
- Yeah, taking the sons is a brilliant idea,

780
00:29:09,930 --> 00:29:11,627
and bringing them to Rome,

781
00:29:11,626 --> 00:29:15,029
'cause it's a kind of a generational integration.

782
00:29:15,029 --> 00:29:17,729
- And the Roman military later in the empire

783
00:29:17,730 --> 00:29:21,989
is this giant machine of half a million people

784
00:29:21,990 --> 00:29:25,380
that takes in foreigners and churns out Romans.

785
00:29:25,380 --> 00:29:27,630
So the army is composed of two groups.

786
00:29:27,630 --> 00:29:30,480
You have the Roman Legionaries, who are all citizens,

787
00:29:30,480 --> 00:29:33,359
but then you have another group that's just as large,

788
00:29:33,359 --> 00:29:35,121
about 250,000 of each,

789
00:29:35,123 --> 00:29:36,330
250,000 legionaries,

790
00:29:36,329 --> 00:29:40,079
250,000 of the second group called auxiliaries.

791
00:29:40,079 --> 00:29:44,248
And auxiliaries tend to be newly conquered, war-like people

792
00:29:44,250 --> 00:29:47,190
that the Romans enlist as auxiliaries

793
00:29:47,190 --> 00:29:48,660
to fight with them.

794
00:29:48,660 --> 00:29:51,930
And they serve side by side with the Roman legions

795
00:29:51,930 --> 00:29:54,240
for 25 years.

796
00:29:54,240 --> 00:29:55,409
And at the end of that time,

797
00:29:55,410 --> 00:29:57,720
when they're discharged, what do they get?

798
00:29:57,720 --> 00:30:00,090
They get Roman citizenship.

799
00:30:00,089 --> 00:30:04,228
And their kids then tend to become Roman legionaries.

800
00:30:04,230 --> 00:30:06,480
So again, you're taking the most war-like

