00:32:55,200 --> 00:32:57,900
So Carthage is on the coast of north Africa,

872
00:32:57,900 --> 00:32:59,279
Rome is in central Italy,

873
00:32:59,279 --> 00:33:00,418
what's right between them?

874
00:33:00,420 --> 00:33:01,920
The island of Sicily.

875
00:33:01,920 --> 00:33:05,880
So the first big war is fought purely dictated by geography,

876
00:33:05,880 --> 00:33:07,952
who gets Sicily, Rome or Carthage?

877
00:33:09,000 --> 00:33:12,299
And Rome wins. In the end, they get it.

878
00:33:12,299 --> 00:33:13,769
But Carthage is still strong,

879
00:33:13,769 --> 00:33:14,602
they're not weakened.

880
00:33:14,603 --> 00:33:16,530
So Carthage is now looking to expand.

881
00:33:16,529 --> 00:33:18,269
The next place to go is Spain,

882
00:33:18,269 --> 00:33:19,889
so they go and take Spain.

883
00:33:19,890 --> 00:33:21,720
Rome, meanwhile, is moving along the coast

884
00:33:21,720 --> 00:33:23,220
of what today is France.

885
00:33:23,220 --> 00:33:24,330
Where are they gonna meet up?

886
00:33:24,329 --> 00:33:26,279
On the border of Spain and France.

887
00:33:26,279 --> 00:33:30,149
And there's a city at this point in time called Saguntum.

888
00:33:30,150 --> 00:33:32,489
The second big war between Rome and Carthage

889
00:33:32,490 --> 00:33:34,379
is over who gets Saguntum.

890
00:33:34,380 --> 00:33:35,940
So I mean, you can just look at a map

891
00:33:35,940 --> 00:33:37,680
and see this stuff coming.

892
00:33:37,680 --> 00:33:40,289
Sometimes, geography is inevitability.

