and you have the short sword,

1320
00:49:19,590 --> 00:49:20,539
the Roman gladius.

1321
00:49:20,539 --> 00:49:23,700
And that's kind of the classic Roman legionnaire.

1322
00:49:23,699 --> 00:49:26,458
Later, more things develop.

1323
00:49:26,460 --> 00:49:29,520
My personal sort of relationship with armor

1324
00:49:29,519 --> 00:49:32,338
is I got, really, by accident,

1325
00:49:32,340 --> 00:49:33,930
involved in this project

1326
00:49:33,929 --> 00:49:38,098
to try to reconstruct this mysterious type of armor

1327
00:49:38,099 --> 00:49:40,438
that was used especially by the Greeks

1328
00:49:40,440 --> 00:49:41,700
and Alexander the Great

1329
00:49:41,699 --> 00:49:43,588
called the linothorax,

1330
00:49:43,590 --> 00:49:46,830
which, apparently, was made only out of linen and glue.

1331
00:49:46,829 --> 00:49:48,389
So this seems a little odd that, you know,

1332
00:49:48,389 --> 00:49:49,739
that's not the sort of material

1333
00:49:49,739 --> 00:49:52,267
once you want metal or something.

1334
00:49:52,268 --> 00:49:54,630
But we had clear literary references

1335
00:49:54,630 --> 00:49:55,946
that people, including Alexander,

1336
00:49:55,947 --> 00:49:57,959
and the most famous image of Alexander

1337
00:49:57,960 --> 00:50:01,319
is this Alexander Mosaic, found at Pompeii,

1338
00:50:01,320 --> 00:50:05,430
that shows him wearing one of these funny types of armor.

1339
00:50:05,429 --> 00:50:08,339
The catch is none survived.

1340
00:50:08,340 --> 00:50:10,229
It's organic materials.

1341
00:50:10,230 --> 00:50:12,450
So we don't have any of them.

1342
00:50:12,449 --> 00:50:16,078
And archeologists like to study things that survive.

1343
00:50:16,079 --> 00:50:19,559
So we have nice typologies of Greek armor made of bronze,

1344
00:50:19,559 --> 00:50:22,708
Roman armor made of steel or sort of proto steel,

1345
00:50:22,710 --> 00:50:24,989
but this thing, this linothorax,

1346
00:50:24,989 --> 00:50:26,489
was a mystery.

1347
00:50:26,489 --> 00:50:29,129
And of my undergraduate students,

1348
00:50:29,130 --> 00:50:30,359
a guy named Scott Bartel,

1349
00:50:30,360 --> 00:50:33,360
had a real, well, an Alexander obsession.

1350
00:50:33,360 --> 00:50:35,569
He really loved Alexander. - As one should.

1351
00:50:35,570 --> 00:50:38,790
- He had Alexandros tattooed on his arm in Greek.

1352
00:50:38,789 --> 00:50:41,248
And he was a smart student, he was really smart.

1353
00:50:41,250 --> 00:50:44,730
And so he, one summer, made himself an imitation

1354
00:50:44,730 --> 00:50:47,759
of this thing of Alexanders just for fun.

1355
00:50:47,760 --> 00:50:49,949
And he said, you know, "Can you give me some articles

1356
00:50:49,949 --> 00:50:51,269
so I could do a better job?"

1357
00:50:51,269 --> 00:50:53,818
So I used some scholarly articles about this armor.

1358
00:50:53,820 --> 00:50:55,680
And with typical sort of, you know, academic arrogance,

1359
00:50:55,679 --> 00:50:57,358
I said, "Why, Scott, of course I will.

1360
00:50:57,360 --> 00:50:58,890
I'll give you some references."

1361
00:50:58,889 --> 00:51:01,228
And I went and looked and there weren't any.

1362
00:51:01,230 --> 00:51:02,197
So at that point, I was like,

1363
00:51:02,197 --> 00:51:04,589
"Huh, tell you what,

1364
00:51:04,590 --> 00:51:07,049
why don't you and I look into this

1365
00:51:07,050 --> 00:51:09,929
and try to do a reconstruction

1366
00:51:09,929 --> 00:51:11,568
using only the materials they would've had

1367
00:51:11,570 --> 00:51:13,260
in the ancient world?"

1368
00:51:13,260 --> 00:51:14,863
And little did I know at the time,

1369
00:51:14,862 --> 00:51:16,271
I thought maybe I'll get an article out of this.

1370
00:51:16,273 --> 00:51:19,229
I mean, it ended up being a 10-year project

1371
00:51:19,230 --> 00:51:22,200
involving, you know, 150 students,

1372
00:51:22,199 --> 00:51:25,098
a couple dozen other faculty members,

1373
00:51:25,099 --> 00:51:26,819
you know, ended up having three documentaries

1374
00:51:26,820 --> 00:51:27,653
made out of it,

1375
00:51:27,652 --> 00:51:30,168
and Scott and I ended up writing a scholarly book on this.

1376
00:51:30,170 --> 00:51:31,619
So this is how, you know,

1377
00:51:31,619 --> 00:51:34,109
you never know where your next project's gonna come from.

1378
00:51:34,110 --> 00:51:35,670
So it started with this undergraduate

1379
00:51:35,670 --> 00:51:37,079
turned into this huge thing.

1380
00:51:37,079 --> 00:51:37,919
But it's what we did.

1381
00:51:37,920 --> 00:51:38,847
We first said, "All right,

1382
00:51:38,847 --> 00:51:41,730
what are all the sources for this armor?"

1383
00:51:41,730 --> 00:51:42,630
And in the end,

1384
00:51:42,630 --> 00:51:47,250
we found 65 accounts of it in ancient literature

1385
00:51:47,250 --> 00:51:48,780
by 40 different authors.

1386
00:51:48,780 --> 00:51:51,090
So we have literary descriptions.

1387
00:51:51,090 --> 00:51:53,130
And then we looked at ancient art

1388
00:51:53,130 --> 00:51:56,370
and we were able to identify about a thousand images

1389
00:51:56,369 --> 00:51:57,659
in ancient art.

1390
00:51:57,659 --> 00:52:01,319
In vase paintings, pottery,

1391
00:52:01,320 --> 00:52:03,420
bronze sculpture, tomb paintings,

1392
00:52:03,420 --> 00:52:05,940
all these different things showing this armor.

1393
00:52:05,940 --> 00:52:07,800
And then using those two things,

1394
00:52:07,800 --> 00:52:10,170
we tried to backwards engineer a pattern

1395
00:52:10,170 --> 00:52:12,359
to say, well, if this is what the end product look like,

1396
00:52:12,360 --> 00:52:14,249
what does it have to look like when you make it?

1397
00:52:14,250 --> 00:52:17,040
And then we tried to reconstruct one of these things

1398
00:52:17,039 --> 00:52:19,378
using only the glue and materials.

1399
00:52:19,380 --> 00:52:20,609
So we had to use, you know,

1400
00:52:20,610 --> 00:52:22,710
animal glues, rabbit glue.

1401
00:52:22,710 --> 00:52:26,250
We had to end up sort of making our own linen,

1402
00:52:26,250 --> 00:52:28,350
which comes from the flax plant.

1403
00:52:28,349 --> 00:52:30,538
So we had to grow flax,

1404
00:52:30,539 --> 00:52:33,029
harvest it using only techniques in the ancient world.

1405
00:52:33,030 --> 00:52:35,159
So modern flax goes through chemical processes.

1406
00:52:35,159 --> 00:52:37,139
No, we had to do this the old fashioned way.

1407
00:52:37,139 --> 00:52:38,399
Spin it into thread,

1408
00:52:38,400 --> 00:52:40,380
sew the thread into fabric,

1409
00:52:40,380 --> 00:52:41,730
glued all together.

1410
00:52:41,730 --> 00:52:43,169
And then the fun part was,

1411
00:52:43,170 --> 00:52:44,280
once we made these things,

1412
00:52:44,280 --> 00:52:46,739
we subjected them to ballistics testing.

1413
00:52:46,739 --> 00:52:48,989
So we shot them with arrows,

1414
00:52:48,989 --> 00:52:51,598
which, again, were wooden reconstruction arrows,

1415
00:52:51,599 --> 00:52:52,978
using bronze arrowheads

1416
00:52:52,980 --> 00:52:56,520
that were based on arrowheads found on ancient battlefields

1417
00:52:56,519 --> 00:52:59,999
to determine how good protection would this thing have been.

1418
00:53:00,000 --> 00:53:01,110
And of course,

1419
00:53:01,110 --> 00:53:02,940
the kind of fun one that everyone always likes

1420
00:53:02,940 --> 00:53:04,200
and that the documentaries always want

1421
00:53:04,199 --> 00:53:05,032
is, at one point, they're like,

1422
00:53:05,032 --> 00:53:07,169
"Well, can you put Scott in one of these and shoot him?"

1423
00:53:07,170 --> 00:53:09,929
- Yeah. - And we're like, "Okay."

1424
00:53:09,929 --> 00:53:10,762
I mean, at that point,

1425
00:53:10,762 --> 00:53:12,058
we'd done about a thousand test shots.

1426
00:53:12,059 --> 00:53:13,978
I grew up shooting bows and arrows,

1427
00:53:13,980 --> 00:53:16,230
I knew exactly how far that was gonna go.

1428
00:53:16,230 --> 00:53:19,140
So it's one of these "Don't do this at home, kids."

1429
00:53:19,139 --> 00:53:20,669
- So there's a million questions to ask here,

1430
00:53:20,670 --> 00:53:21,750
but, you know, in general,

1431
00:53:21,750 --> 00:53:23,790
how well, in terms of ballistics, does it work?

1432
00:53:23,789 --> 00:53:26,699
Like can it withstand arrows

1433
00:53:26,699 --> 00:53:28,739
or direct strikes from like swords

1434
00:53:28,739 --> 00:53:29,999
and axes and stuff like that?

1435
00:53:30,000 --> 00:53:34,169
- Bottom line is a one centimeter thick linothorax,

1436
00:53:34,170 --> 00:53:36,870
so laminated, or even sewn,

1437
00:53:36,869 --> 00:53:38,248
it doesn't have to be laminated,

1438
00:53:38,250 --> 00:53:40,139
layer of linen

1439
00:53:40,139 --> 00:53:41,999
is about as good protection

1440
00:53:42,000 --> 00:53:44,129
as two millimeters of bronze,

1441
00:53:44,130 --> 00:53:46,529
which was the thickest comparable

1442
00:53:46,530 --> 00:53:48,719
body armor of bronze at the time.

1443
00:53:48,719 --> 00:53:53,719
And we're talking fourth century, fifth century BC here.

1444
00:53:54,389 --> 00:53:57,089
So Classical and Hellenistic Greece.

1445
00:53:57,090 --> 00:53:58,950
And that would've protected you from,

1446
00:53:58,949 --> 00:54:01,889
let's say, random aero strikes on the battlefield.

1447
00:54:01,889 --> 00:54:04,529
So you could have gotten hit by arrows

1448
00:54:04,530 --> 00:54:06,510
and they simply wouldn't have gone through.

1449
00:54:06,510 --> 00:54:07,500
- What are the benefits?

1450
00:54:07,500 --> 00:54:09,480
So is there a major weight difference?

1451
00:54:09,480 --> 00:54:11,879
- Yes. So the benefits of this are,

1452
00:54:11,880 --> 00:54:14,370
it's much lighter than metal armor.

1453
00:54:14,369 --> 00:54:17,339
So the linothorax is about 11 pounds.

1454
00:54:17,340 --> 00:54:20,580
A bronze cuirass of comparable protection

1455
00:54:20,579 --> 00:54:23,938
would've been about 24 to six pounds.

1456
00:54:23,940 --> 00:54:27,569
A chain mail shirt would be about 28, 27 pounds.

1457
00:54:27,570 --> 00:54:28,440
It's cooler.

1458
00:54:28,440 --> 00:54:29,460
I mean, you know,

1459
00:54:29,460 --> 00:54:31,080
the Mediterranean is a hot place

1460
00:54:31,079 --> 00:54:32,609
with the hot sun.

1461
00:54:32,610 --> 00:54:34,019
Even today, you know, a linen shirt

1462
00:54:34,019 --> 00:54:35,759
is something you wear when you want to be cool.

1463
00:54:35,760 --> 00:54:37,020
So it's much lighter,

1464
00:54:37,019 --> 00:54:39,568
that gives you troops greater endurance on the battlefield.

1465
00:54:39,570 --> 00:54:42,210
They can run farther, fight longer.

1466
00:54:42,210 --> 00:54:43,290
It's cheaper.

1467
00:54:43,289 --> 00:54:44,639
You don't need a blacksmith,

1468
00:54:44,639 --> 00:54:46,379
who's a specialist, to make it.

1469
00:54:46,380 --> 00:54:48,059
In fact, probably, this is interesting,

1470
00:54:48,059 --> 00:54:50,338
any woman in the ancient world

1471
00:54:50,340 --> 00:54:51,779
could have made one of these

1472
00:54:51,780 --> 00:54:54,960
because they were the ones who spun thread

1473
00:54:54,960 --> 00:54:57,419
and sewed it into fabric.

1474
00:54:57,420 --> 00:55:00,060
So I can easily see, in a household,

1475
00:55:00,059 --> 00:55:01,919
a mother making this for her son,

1476
00:55:01,920 --> 00:55:04,080
a wife making it for her husband.

1477
00:55:04,079 --> 00:55:08,248
So it's a form of armor you could have made domestically.

1478
00:55:08,250 --> 00:55:09,090
That would've been, you know,

1479
00:55:09,090 --> 00:55:10,560
maybe not the greatest armor,

1480
00:55:10,559 --> 00:55:11,849
but pretty good,

1481
00:55:11,849 --> 00:55:13,978
pretty comparable to bronze armor.

1482
00:55:13,980 --> 00:55:15,240
- And it's amazing that you used

1483
00:55:15,239 --> 00:55:16,799
all the materials they had at the time

1484
00:55:16,800 --> 00:55:18,540
and none of the modern techniques.

1485
00:55:18,539 --> 00:55:19,706
But I should probably say,

1486
00:55:19,706 --> 00:55:21,269
and maybe you can speak to that,

1487
00:55:21,269 --> 00:55:23,429
they were probably much better at doing that

1488
00:55:23,429 --> 00:55:26,699
than you are, right, because like,

1489
00:55:26,699 --> 00:55:29,038
you know, again, generational, it's a skill,

1490
00:55:29,039 --> 00:55:31,259
and it's a skill that probably has practiced across decades,

1491
00:55:31,260 --> 00:55:32,512
across centuries with the...

1492
00:55:32,512 --> 00:55:35,129
- I mean, in terms of producing the fabric,

1493
00:55:35,130 --> 00:55:37,860
I'm sure they could do it 10 times faster than we could,

1494
00:55:37,860 --> 00:55:39,059
just that's a speed thing,

1495
00:55:39,059 --> 00:55:41,248
but it's still incredibly labor intensive.

1496
00:55:41,250 --> 00:55:42,720
Where I think there's a big difference

1497
00:55:42,719 --> 00:55:44,728
between our reconstruction and ancient ones

1498
00:55:44,730 --> 00:55:45,959
is in the glue.

1499
00:55:45,960 --> 00:55:47,010
So we ended up using

1500
00:55:47,010 --> 00:55:49,409
a kind of least common denominator glue.

1501
00:55:49,409 --> 00:55:50,879
We used rabbit glue

1502
00:55:50,880 --> 00:55:53,100
because it would've been available anywhere

1503
00:55:53,099 --> 00:55:53,932
and it's cheap.

1504
00:55:55,260 --> 00:55:56,250
But in the ancient world,

1505
00:55:56,250 --> 00:55:59,459
they did have basically the equivalent of super glues.

1506
00:55:59,460 --> 00:56:01,980
I mean, we found, for example,

1507
00:56:01,980 --> 00:56:04,350
helmets that were fished out of a river in Germany

1508
00:56:04,349 --> 00:56:07,319
that had metal parts glued together

1509
00:56:07,320 --> 00:56:09,420
that after 2000 years of immersion in water

1510
00:56:09,420 --> 00:56:10,859
were still glued together.

1511
00:56:10,860 --> 00:56:12,360
So they had some great glues,

1512
00:56:12,360 --> 00:56:14,850
we just don't know what the recipes for them were.

1513
00:56:14,849 --> 00:56:16,506
So we went the opposite tack and said,

1514
00:56:16,507 --> 00:56:17,850
"Well, we're just gonna make something

1515
00:56:17,849 --> 00:56:19,528
that we know they could have made."

1516
00:56:19,530 --> 00:56:22,889
So it was at least this good, you know what I'm saying?

1517
00:56:22,889 --> 00:56:25,829
- But actually, this is a materials thing,

1518
00:56:25,829 --> 00:56:27,302
but I think glue,

1519
00:56:29,639 --> 00:56:33,359
aside from helping glue things together,

1520
00:56:33,360 --> 00:56:36,210
it can also be a thing that serves as armor.

1521
00:56:36,210 --> 00:56:38,520
So like if you glue things correctly,

1522
00:56:38,519 --> 00:56:42,688
the way it permeates the material that is gluing

1523
00:56:42,690 --> 00:56:44,452
can strengthen the material,

1524
00:56:44,452 --> 00:56:45,629
the integrity of the material.

1525
00:56:45,630 --> 00:56:46,710
That's an art and a science

1526
00:56:46,710 --> 00:56:48,060
probably that they understood deeply.

1527
00:56:48,059 --> 00:56:50,279
- The process of lamination did add something.

1528
00:56:50,280 --> 00:56:52,889
So there's actually a huge debate among scholars

1529
00:56:52,889 --> 00:56:55,168
and actually a sort of amateur archeologist

1530
00:56:55,170 --> 00:56:58,500
that was this linothorax thing glued together

1531
00:56:58,500 --> 00:57:00,360
or was it simply sewn together?

1532
00:57:00,360 --> 00:57:02,310
Was it composite, partially linen,

1533
00:57:02,309 --> 00:57:04,349
partially leather, or other materials?

1534
00:57:04,349 --> 00:57:07,259
And my honest answer is, I think it's all of the above,

1535
00:57:07,260 --> 00:57:09,900
because, again, every piece of armor in the ancient world

1536
00:57:09,900 --> 00:57:11,789
was an individual creation.

1537
00:57:11,789 --> 00:57:13,619
So I think if you had some spare leather,

1538
00:57:13,619 --> 00:57:14,699
you put that in.

1539
00:57:14,699 --> 00:57:17,189
If you wanted to make one that was just sewn together,

1540
00:57:17,190 --> 00:57:19,680
even quilted stuffed with stuff, you do that.

1541
00:57:19,679 --> 00:57:21,868
Maybe you were good at gluing stuff, you used that.

1542
00:57:21,869 --> 00:57:23,639
So I think there's no one answer.

1543
00:57:23,639 --> 00:57:26,549
We investigated one possibility

1544
00:57:26,550 --> 00:57:28,500
because we just had limited time

1545
00:57:28,500 --> 00:57:30,120
and money and resources.

1546
00:57:30,119 --> 00:57:32,969
But I think all these other things existed at the same time

1547
00:57:32,969 --> 00:57:34,648
and were variants of it.

1548
00:57:34,650 --> 00:57:36,210
- Just as a small aside,

1549
00:57:36,210 --> 00:57:38,640
I just think this is a fascinating journey you went on.

1550
00:57:38,639 --> 00:57:40,129
I love it.

1551
00:57:40,130 --> 00:57:44,070
That sort of answering really important questions

1552
00:57:44,070 --> 00:57:47,369
about, in this case, armor,

1553
00:57:47,369 --> 00:57:50,668
about military equipment and technology

1554
00:57:50,670 --> 00:57:53,009
that archeologists can't answer

1555
00:57:53,010 --> 00:57:54,899
by using all the literate.

1556
00:57:54,900 --> 00:57:56,309
So all the sources you can

1557
00:57:56,309 --> 00:57:57,142
to understand what it looked like,

1558
00:57:57,143 --> 00:57:58,620
what were the materials,

1559
00:57:58,619 --> 00:58:00,145
using the materials at the time,

1560
00:58:00,146 --> 00:58:02,669
and actually doing ballistic testing.

1561
00:58:02,670 --> 00:58:03,630
It's really cool.

1562
00:58:03,630 --> 00:58:05,819
It's really cool that it's,

1563
00:58:05,820 --> 00:58:08,340
you see that there's a hole in the literature.

1564
00:58:08,340 --> 00:58:09,360
Nobody studied it

1565
00:58:09,360 --> 00:58:13,020
and going hard and doing it the right way

1566
00:58:13,019 --> 00:58:14,492
to sort of uncovered this.

1567
00:58:15,659 --> 00:58:16,499
I don't know.

1568
00:58:16,500 --> 00:58:18,810
I think it's an amazing mystery about the ancient world.

1569
00:58:18,809 --> 00:58:19,739
- I mean, shifting from

1570
00:58:19,739 --> 00:58:21,089
just sort of Roman history in general

1571
00:58:21,090 --> 00:58:23,549
to my research that I've done as a scholar,

1572
00:58:23,550 --> 00:58:25,380
the theme that runs throughout my scholarship

1573
00:58:25,380 --> 00:58:26,910
is practical stuff.

1574
00:58:26,909 --> 00:58:27,742
I'm interested,

1575
00:58:27,742 --> 00:58:28,709
how did this actually work

1576
00:58:28,710 --> 00:58:29,909
in the ancient world?

1577
00:58:29,909 --> 00:58:32,339
So there's people who are much more theoretical,

1578
00:58:32,340 --> 00:58:33,173
who look at, you know,

1579
00:58:33,172 --> 00:58:34,948
the symbolic meaning of something.

