01:08:15,449 --> 01:08:18,719
And the Twelve Tables is that it's a crude law code,

1840
01:08:18,720 --> 01:08:20,270
it has a lot of goofy stuff in it,

1841
01:08:20,270 --> 01:08:22,080
it has things about, you know,

1842
01:08:22,079 --> 01:08:25,259
if you use magic, this is the punishment,

1843
01:08:25,260 --> 01:08:28,590
but it's that basic agrarian society law code.

1844
01:08:28,590 --> 01:08:30,659
Now, that's typical in many societies.

1845
01:08:30,659 --> 01:08:33,899
Where the Romans are different is they keep going,

1846
01:08:33,899 --> 01:08:36,119
they keep developing their law code.

1847
01:08:36,119 --> 01:08:38,398
And by the late republic,

1848
01:08:38,399 --> 01:08:41,099
the Romans just get kind of really into legal stuff.

1849
01:08:41,100 --> 01:08:42,473
I don't know why, but...

1850
01:08:42,472 --> 01:08:45,539
And the Romans are very methodical, organized people,

1851
01:08:45,539 --> 01:08:47,668
so maybe this has something to do with it.

1852
01:08:47,670 --> 01:08:49,410
But their law code just keeps getting

1853
01:08:49,409 --> 01:08:51,239
more and more complicated

1854
01:08:51,239 --> 01:08:53,219
and keeps expanding to different areas.

1855
01:08:53,220 --> 01:08:54,510
And they start to get juris

1856
01:08:54,510 --> 01:08:57,692
who write sort of theoretical things about Roman law.

1857
01:08:58,560 --> 01:09:01,260
And eventually, it becomes this huge body,

1858
01:09:01,260 --> 01:09:04,679
both of cases and comments on those cases

1859
01:09:04,680 --> 01:09:06,780
and of actual laws.

1860
01:09:06,779 --> 01:09:10,742
And in the 6th century AD, so the 500s,

1861
01:09:11,640 --> 01:09:13,200
the Roman Emperor Justinian,

1862
01:09:13,199 --> 01:09:16,739
who is a emperor of the Eastern Roman Empire by this point,

1863
01:09:16,739 --> 01:09:17,938
the Byzantine Empire,

1864
01:09:17,939 --> 01:09:20,008
compiles all this together into something

1865
01:09:20,010 --> 01:09:21,720
that today we just kinda loosely called

1866
01:09:21,720 --> 01:09:23,820
Justinian's Code of Roman Law,

1867
01:09:23,819 --> 01:09:25,166
and that survives.

1868
01:09:25,167 --> 01:09:26,910
And so that becomes the basis

1869
01:09:26,909 --> 01:09:29,009
for almost all the legal systems around the world.

1870
01:09:29,010 --> 01:09:30,957
And it's very complicated.

1871
01:09:30,957 --> 01:09:32,880
And Roman law, I think, is really fun,

1872
01:09:32,880 --> 01:09:35,250
because on the one hand, it's really dry,

1873
01:09:35,250 --> 01:09:37,319
but it also preserves these wonderful,

1874
01:09:37,319 --> 01:09:39,718
little vignettes of daily life.

1875
01:09:39,720 --> 01:09:42,929
So you get these great just kind of entertaining law cases.

1876
01:09:42,930 --> 01:09:43,800
One of my favorite,

1877
01:09:43,800 --> 01:09:45,090
and this may not even be a real case,

1878
01:09:45,090 --> 01:09:46,259
this might be a hypothetical

1879
01:09:46,260 --> 01:09:47,429
that they would use like to train

1880
01:09:47,430 --> 01:09:49,530
Roman sort of, you know, law students,

1881
01:09:49,529 --> 01:09:52,109
is like one day a man sends a slave

1882
01:09:52,109 --> 01:09:54,118
to the barber to get a shave,

1883
01:09:54,119 --> 01:09:57,748
and the barbershop is adjacent to an athletic field.

1884
01:09:57,750 --> 01:09:59,520
And two guys are on the athletic field

1885
01:09:59,520 --> 01:10:00,959
throwing a ball back and forth.

1886
01:10:00,960 --> 01:10:03,450
And one of them throws the ball badly,

1887
01:10:03,449 --> 01:10:05,309
the other guy fails to catch it,

1888
01:10:05,310 --> 01:10:07,229
the ball flies into the barbershop,

1889
01:10:07,229 --> 01:10:08,549
hits the hand of the barber,

1890
01:10:08,550 --> 01:10:11,099
cuts the slave's throat, he dies.

1891
01:10:11,100 --> 01:10:13,439
Who's liable under Roman law?

1892
01:10:13,439 --> 01:10:16,318
Is it the athlete one who threw the ball badly,

1893
01:10:16,319 --> 01:10:18,439
is it athlete two who failed to catch it,

1894
01:10:18,439 --> 01:10:21,179
is the barber who actually cut the slave's throat,

1895
01:10:21,180 --> 01:10:23,130
is it the owner of the slave

1896
01:10:23,130 --> 01:10:26,009
for being stupid enough to send his slave

1897
01:10:26,010 --> 01:10:29,219
to get a shave in a place adjacent to a playing field,

1898
01:10:29,220 --> 01:10:30,599
or is it the Roman state

1899
01:10:30,600 --> 01:10:34,410
rezoning a barbershop next to an athletic field?

1900
01:10:34,409 --> 01:10:35,578
What do you think?

1901
01:10:35,579 --> 01:10:38,159
- Well, do they resolve the complexity of that

1902
01:10:38,159 --> 01:10:39,749
with the right answer?

1903
01:10:39,750 --> 01:10:41,614
- We don't have the answer. - We don't have the answer.

1904
01:10:41,613 --> 01:10:43,554
- It's a case without the answer.

1905
01:10:43,555 --> 01:10:47,430
So we have various juris commenting on this one,

1906
01:10:47,430 --> 01:10:49,619
but we don't have what was actually ruled.

1907
01:10:49,619 --> 01:10:52,949
But it's just a great little, you know, sort of vignette.

1908
01:10:52,949 --> 01:10:54,989
And that's how complicated Roman law got

1909
01:10:54,989 --> 01:10:58,589
that it was dealing with these weird, esoteric questions.

1910
01:10:58,590 --> 01:11:00,269
There's another one where, you know,

1911
01:11:00,270 --> 01:11:03,569
a cow gets loose and runs into an apartment building,

1912
01:11:03,569 --> 01:11:04,679
goes up onto the roof,

1913
01:11:04,680 --> 01:11:07,050
and crashes down three stories into a bar

1914
01:11:07,050 --> 01:11:08,310
on the ground floor,

1915
01:11:08,310 --> 01:11:11,339
and kicks open the taps to the wine jug,

1916
01:11:11,340 --> 01:11:12,930
and all the wine flows out,

1917
01:11:12,930 --> 01:11:14,309
who's at fault?

1918
01:11:14,310 --> 01:11:16,260
I mean, this seems to have happened

1919
01:11:16,260 --> 01:11:18,003
as crazy as it sounds.

1920
01:11:18,960 --> 01:11:20,940
And Roman testamentary law is great.

1921
01:11:20,939 --> 01:11:22,469
I mean, something like 20% of Roman law

1922
01:11:22,470 --> 01:11:23,699
has to do with wills

1923
01:11:23,699 --> 01:11:24,868
and what you do with the will

1924
01:11:24,869 --> 01:11:27,200
and what makes a will valid.

1925
01:11:27,202 --> 01:11:28,861
You know, you have to have seven witnesses,

1926
01:11:28,862 --> 01:11:29,695
and you have to have a guy named

1927
01:11:29,694 --> 01:11:31,439
the liber friends to witness it,

1928
01:11:31,439 --> 01:11:33,088
and the witnesses have to be adult men

1929
01:11:33,090 --> 01:11:34,319
who can't be blind

1930
01:11:34,319 --> 01:11:36,539
and all this other stuff.

1931
01:11:36,539 --> 01:11:37,372
So it's just great.

1932
01:11:37,372 --> 01:11:38,999
I mean, it's fun to mess around in this,

1933
01:11:39,000 --> 01:11:40,800
but it always contains these little nuggets

1934
01:11:40,800 --> 01:11:42,780
about what happens.

1935
01:11:42,779 --> 01:11:44,639
I mentioned, I wrote a book on floods.

1936
01:11:44,640 --> 01:11:46,500
And there were all these law cases about

1937
01:11:46,500 --> 01:11:48,270
if a flood strikes the city

1938
01:11:48,270 --> 01:11:51,870
and picks up my piece of furniture in my apartment building

1939
01:11:51,869 --> 01:11:53,129
and carries it out the door

1940
01:11:53,130 --> 01:11:55,110
and deposits it in another apartment building,

1941
01:11:55,109 --> 01:11:56,998
does that guy now own my furniture

1942
01:11:57,000 --> 01:11:59,730
because it's now legally within his apartment?

1943
01:11:59,729 --> 01:12:01,005
Or can I go in there and repossess it

1944
01:12:01,006 --> 01:12:03,898
'cause the flood took it out of my apartment?

1945
01:12:03,899 --> 01:12:05,699
You know, this is the stuff laws handled.

1946
01:12:05,699 --> 01:12:08,098
And that's how sophisticated Roman law got

1947
01:12:08,100 --> 01:12:11,970
- Did kind of corrupt, unfair things seep into the law?

1948
01:12:11,970 --> 01:12:12,803
- Oh, yeah.

1949
01:12:12,802 --> 01:12:15,599
I mean, it's biased in favor of the wealthy, obviously.

1950
01:12:15,600 --> 01:12:17,729
And, I mean, you know,

1951
01:12:17,729 --> 01:12:21,599
Roman law cases are interesting

1952
01:12:21,600 --> 01:12:24,780
because they became linked to politics.

1953
01:12:24,779 --> 01:12:26,609
So one of the way that politicians,

1954
01:12:26,609 --> 01:12:28,919
up and coming politicians, aspiring politicians

1955
01:12:28,920 --> 01:12:30,180
could sort of make their name

1956
01:12:30,180 --> 01:12:31,559
or become famous

1957
01:12:31,560 --> 01:12:33,510
was by either prosecuting

1958
01:12:33,510 --> 01:12:35,760
or defending people in Roman law courts.

1959
01:12:35,760 --> 01:12:39,002
And especially during the late Roman Republic,

1960
01:12:39,899 --> 01:12:41,999
you get a lot of really sensational,

1961
01:12:42,000 --> 01:12:44,430
what today we'd call celebrity law cases.

1962
01:12:44,430 --> 01:12:46,559
So this is where some of the biggest politicians

1963
01:12:46,560 --> 01:12:51,060
were accused of very melodramatic kinds of things.

1964
01:12:51,060 --> 01:12:54,269
And, I mean, the most famous Roman orator of all time,

1965
01:12:54,270 --> 01:12:55,409
Cicero,

1966
01:12:55,409 --> 01:12:57,989
is a guy who made his entire career

1967
01:12:57,989 --> 01:12:59,368
in the law courts,

1968
01:12:59,369 --> 01:13:00,959
and that's how he made his reputation,

1969
01:13:00,960 --> 01:13:03,690
was able to parlay that into political power,

1970
01:13:03,689 --> 01:13:05,669
and eventually was elected to the highest office

1971
01:13:05,670 --> 01:13:06,839
in the Roman government.

1972
01:13:06,840 --> 01:13:08,909
But it's purely because of his skill,

1973
01:13:08,909 --> 01:13:11,609
his facility at using words,

1974
01:13:11,609 --> 01:13:13,678
at giving speeches in public.

1975
01:13:13,680 --> 01:13:17,189
- So they loved the puzzle and the game of law,

1976
01:13:17,189 --> 01:13:22,189
the sort of untangling really complicated legal situations

1977
01:13:23,130 --> 01:13:24,269
and coming up with new laws

1978
01:13:24,270 --> 01:13:27,641
that help you tangle and untangle the situations?

1979
01:13:27,640 --> 01:13:29,759
- Yes, and law cases, again,

1980
01:13:29,760 --> 01:13:30,899
especially in the late republic,

1981
01:13:30,899 --> 01:13:33,599
also became a form of public spectacle.

1982
01:13:33,600 --> 01:13:38,519
So, Rome did not have law courts in a building locked away.

1983
01:13:38,520 --> 01:13:41,399
A lot of these cases were held in the Roman forum,

1984
01:13:41,399 --> 01:13:42,419
in the open,

1985
01:13:42,420 --> 01:13:45,810
and audiences would just come to be entertained.

1986
01:13:45,810 --> 01:13:47,939
And the people presenting the speeches there

1987
01:13:47,939 --> 01:13:50,159
were playing as much to this audience

1988
01:13:50,159 --> 01:13:53,099
as they were to, let's say, the jury or a judge.

1989
01:13:53,100 --> 01:13:55,050
And that became a big part of the cases.

1990
01:13:55,050 --> 01:13:57,329
So that's all tied up in Roman oratory too.

1991
01:13:57,329 --> 01:14:01,708
- So we're talking a bit about the details of the laws.

1992
01:14:01,710 --> 01:14:04,140
Is there some big picture laws

1993
01:14:04,140 --> 01:14:07,080
that are new innovations or like profound things

1994
01:14:07,079 --> 01:14:10,199
like all Roman citizens are equal before the law,

1995
01:14:10,199 --> 01:14:13,708
kind of founding fathers type of in the United States,

1996
01:14:13,710 --> 01:14:14,640
in the western world,

1997
01:14:14,640 --> 01:14:16,979
these big legal ideas?

1998
01:14:16,979 --> 01:14:19,289
- I think maybe one of the things

1999
01:14:19,289 --> 01:14:21,539
that was really stressed in Roman law early on,

2000
01:14:21,539 --> 01:14:23,039
even as early as the Twelve Tables,

2001
01:14:23,039 --> 01:14:25,716
is the notion of Roman citizenship.

2002
01:14:25,716 --> 01:14:27,958
So if you were a Roman citizen,

2003
01:14:27,960 --> 01:14:32,759
it came with a set of both privileges and obligations.

2004
01:14:32,760 --> 01:14:34,080
So the obligations were

2005
01:14:34,079 --> 01:14:35,488
you're supposed to fight in the army,

2006
01:14:35,489 --> 01:14:37,319
you were supposed to vote in elections.

2007
01:14:37,319 --> 01:14:40,379
The privileges were you had the protection of Roman law,

2008
01:14:40,380 --> 01:14:43,529
and at least in theory, if not in practice,

2009
01:14:43,529 --> 01:14:45,658
everybody was equal under that law.

2010
01:14:45,659 --> 01:14:47,399
Now, of course, keep in mind,

2011
01:14:47,399 --> 01:14:49,259
we're talking about men here.

2012
01:14:49,260 --> 01:14:51,809
And even at the height of the Roman Empire,

2013
01:14:51,810 --> 01:14:53,640
so let's say 2nd century AD,

2014
01:14:53,640 --> 01:14:56,999
there were about 50 million human beings

2015
01:14:57,000 --> 01:14:59,759
living within the boundaries of the Roman Empire.

2016
01:14:59,760 --> 01:15:04,200
Maybe 6 million were actual citizens.

2017
01:15:04,199 --> 01:15:06,066
So, you know, this is, we tend to go,

2018
01:15:06,067 --> 01:15:07,680
"Oh, it's so great if you're a citizen,

2019
01:15:07,680 --> 01:15:08,513
you have all these things."

2020
01:15:08,512 --> 01:15:12,269
Well, adult free men who are not slaves,

2021
01:15:12,270 --> 01:15:14,130
who are not resident foreigners,

2022
01:15:14,130 --> 01:15:15,900
they have this great stuff.

2023
01:15:15,899 --> 01:15:20,099
And that's always a tiny minority of all the human beings

2024
01:15:20,100 --> 01:15:21,960
who existed in this society.

2025
01:15:21,960 --> 01:15:23,790
But still, the notion,

2026
01:15:23,789 --> 01:15:26,398
the notion of citizenship is huge.

2027
01:15:26,399 --> 01:15:28,798
And citizens, for example, early on,

2028
01:15:28,800 --> 01:15:30,479
you had to be tried at Rome

2029
01:15:30,479 --> 01:15:32,309
if you were accused of something.

2030
01:15:32,310 --> 01:15:35,490
And there's this very famous moment in Sicily

2031
01:15:35,489 --> 01:15:39,449
where an abusive governor, who's corrupt,

2032
01:15:39,449 --> 01:15:43,049
is punishing a citizen arbitrarily.

2033
01:15:43,050 --> 01:15:46,230
And this person cries out "Civis Romanus sum,"

2034
01:15:46,229 --> 01:15:49,048
meaning "I am a Roman citizen."

2035
01:15:49,050 --> 01:15:52,500
And it really was this hugely loaded statement

2036
01:15:52,500 --> 01:15:54,270
that gives me protections.

2037
01:15:54,270 --> 01:15:56,490
It is wrong for you to do this to me.

2038
01:15:56,489 --> 01:15:58,079
It's wrong for you to beat me

2039
01:15:58,079 --> 01:15:59,639
because I am a citizen,

2040
01:15:59,640 --> 01:16:01,860
and that gives me certain protections.

2041
01:16:01,859 --> 01:16:05,339
So that notion of citizenship is something that I think

2042
01:16:05,340 --> 01:16:06,900
the Romans really emphasize

2043
01:16:06,899 --> 01:16:10,318
and becomes a legacy to a lot of civilizations today

2044
01:16:10,319 --> 01:16:12,059
where citizenship means something.

2045
01:16:12,060 --> 01:16:13,979
It's a special status.

2046
01:16:13,979 --> 01:16:17,128
- So you mentioned slaves, slavery,

2047
01:16:17,130 --> 01:16:21,240
that's something that is common throughout human history.

2048
01:16:21,239 --> 01:16:25,319
What do we know about their relationship with slavery?

2049
01:16:25,319 --> 01:16:26,728
- Well, Roman slavery,

2050
01:16:26,729 --> 01:16:28,439
a couple just reminders at the beginning,

2051
01:16:28,439 --> 01:16:31,229
first of all, it's not racial slavery.

2052
01:16:31,229 --> 01:16:33,329
So for people, you know, in the United States,

2053
01:16:33,329 --> 01:16:34,379
you tend to think of slavery

2054
01:16:34,380 --> 01:16:36,299
through this kind of racial lens.

2055
01:16:36,300 --> 01:16:38,880
So slaves in Ancient Roman society

2056
01:16:38,880 --> 01:16:41,759
could be any color, ethnicity, gender,

2057
01:16:41,760 --> 01:16:43,320
you know, origin, whatever.

2058
01:16:43,319 --> 01:16:45,778
It's an economic status.

2059
01:16:45,779 --> 01:16:47,099
Now, having said that,

2060
01:16:47,100 --> 01:16:51,810
slavery is fundamentally horrific to human dignity

2061
01:16:51,810 --> 01:16:56,010
because it is defining a human being as an object.

2062
01:16:56,010 --> 01:16:58,860
And very famously, a Roman agricultural writer,

2063
01:16:58,859 --> 01:17:02,076
who's writing about farms just as a kind of aside, says,

2064
01:17:02,077 --> 01:17:04,859
"You know, on your farm, you have three types of tools.

2065
01:17:04,859 --> 01:17:07,618
You have dumb tools,

2066
01:17:07,619 --> 01:17:09,119
and by dummy means can't speak.

2067
01:17:09,119 --> 01:17:10,318
So that's like shovels,

2068
01:17:10,319 --> 01:17:12,809
you know, picks things like this, wagons.

2069
01:17:12,810 --> 01:17:16,319
You have semi-articulate tools, which are animals,

2070
01:17:16,319 --> 01:17:18,899
and you have articulate tools,

2071
01:17:18,899 --> 01:17:21,119
which are human beings, slaves."

2072
01:17:21,119 --> 01:17:24,089
And for him, these are all just categories of tools.

2073
01:17:24,090 --> 01:17:27,199
You know, it's so intensely dehumanizing

2074
01:17:27,199 --> 01:17:29,489
to view people in that way.

2075
01:17:29,489 --> 01:17:31,819
So Roman slavery is odd in that

2076
01:17:31,819 --> 01:17:33,509
it doesn't have this racial component.

2077
01:17:33,510 --> 01:17:36,269
It's horrible in the way all slavery is horrible.

2078
01:17:36,270 --> 01:17:37,499
But the other thing about it is,

2079
01:17:37,500 --> 01:17:40,770
it's not a hard line.

2080
01:17:40,770 --> 01:17:42,510
It's a permeable membrane.

2081
01:17:42,510 --> 01:17:46,050
And many people move back and forth across it.

2082
01:17:46,050 --> 01:17:48,270
So you have many people in the Roman world

2083
01:17:48,270 --> 01:17:50,669
who were born a slave who gained their freedom

2084
01:17:50,670 --> 01:17:51,720
through one means or another.

2085
01:17:51,720 --> 01:17:53,369
And you have many others who were born free

2086
01:17:53,369 --> 01:17:54,629
and become slaves.

2087
01:17:54,630 --> 01:17:56,759
And you have some who go back and forth.

2088
01:17:56,760 --> 01:17:59,347
There's a great Roman tombstone of this guy who says,

2089
01:17:59,346 --> 01:18:01,559
"I was born a free man in Parthia,

2090
01:18:01,560 --> 01:18:02,969
I was enslaved,

2091
01:18:02,970 --> 01:18:04,349
then I gained my freedom

2092
01:18:04,350 --> 01:18:06,060
and I became a teacher or something,

2093
01:18:06,060 --> 01:18:06,893
and I had a life,

2094
01:18:06,893 --> 01:18:08,280
and now I'm a Roman citizen."

2095
01:18:08,279 --> 01:18:10,319
So it's this whole, like, back and forth

2096
01:18:10,319 --> 01:18:13,439
across all these boundaries multiple times.

2097
01:18:13,439 --> 01:18:15,269
- Oh, so there's probably a process,

2098
01:18:15,270 --> 01:18:17,1000
like an economic transaction.

2099
01:18:18,000 --> 01:18:19,439
- The most common source of slaves

2100
01:18:19,439 --> 01:18:21,568
in the Roman world was war.

2101
01:18:21,569 --> 01:18:24,209
So wherever the Roman army went,

2102
01:18:24,210 --> 01:18:28,679
in its wake would be literally a train of slave traders.

2103
01:18:28,680 --> 01:18:30,150
So you're in war,

2104
01:18:30,149 --> 01:18:31,528
you capture an enemy city,

2105
01:18:31,529 --> 01:18:32,968
you whack the people over the head,

2106
01:18:32,970 --> 01:18:34,349
and you turn around if you're a soldier,

2107
01:18:34,350 --> 01:18:36,060
and you sell them to one of these slave traders

2108
01:18:36,060 --> 01:18:38,519
that's following the army around, literally.

2109
01:18:38,520 --> 01:18:40,770
So that's probably the biggest source of slaves.

2110
01:18:40,770 --> 01:18:43,653
Another big source is just children of slave or slaves.

2111
01:18:45,869 --> 01:18:48,268
And some people could literally sell

2112
01:18:48,270 --> 01:18:51,330
either themselves or their children into slavery

2113
01:18:51,329 --> 01:18:54,569
due to economic, you know, necessity

2114
01:18:54,569 --> 01:18:56,488
or privation or something.

2115
01:18:56,489 --> 01:18:57,809
So as terrible as that sounds,

2116
01:18:57,810 --> 01:19:02,162
a father could sell a child if he needed money.

2117
01:19:04,050 --> 01:19:06,090
Once you were a slave though,

2118
01:19:06,090 --> 01:19:09,420
the experience of slavery varied a lot

2119
01:19:09,420 --> 01:19:13,830
because a lot of the slaves were agricultural slaves.

2120
01:19:13,829 --> 01:19:15,329
So they would work sort of,

2121
01:19:15,329 --> 01:19:18,628
like in the American south, big plantations,

2122
01:19:18,630 --> 01:19:19,799
they might be chained,

2123
01:19:19,800 --> 01:19:21,179
they were probably abused.

2124
01:19:21,180 --> 01:19:23,894
That's very similar to slavery as we think of it in,

2125
01:19:23,894 --> 01:19:25,019
you know, let's say the Caribbean,

2126
01:19:25,020 --> 01:19:25,920
South America,

2127
01:19:25,920 --> 01:19:27,809
or the United States prior to the Civil War,

2128
01:19:27,810 --> 01:19:29,430
that kind of slavery.

2129
01:19:29,430 --> 01:19:31,380
But a lot of Roman slaves

2130
01:19:31,380 --> 01:19:34,170
were also some of the more skilled people.

2131
01:19:34,170 --> 01:19:35,339
And this seems a little weird.

2132
01:19:35,340 --> 01:19:37,440
So if you're a rich person, you have slaves,

2133
01:19:37,439 --> 01:19:39,479
it's actually a good investment for you

2134
01:19:39,479 --> 01:19:41,999
to train your slaves in a profession.

2135
01:19:42,000 --> 01:19:46,919
So a lot of Roman doctors, scribes, accountants,

2136
01:19:46,920 --> 01:19:49,170
sort of all this sort of thing, barbers,

2137
01:19:49,170 --> 01:19:50,280
were slaves,

2138
01:19:50,279 --> 01:19:52,499
because if you train this person

2139
01:19:52,500 --> 01:19:54,899
and then they produce a lot of money for you,

2140
01:19:54,899 --> 01:19:56,042
you get that money.

2141
01:19:57,149 --> 01:20:00,119
And those slaves would sometimes be given an incentive

2142
01:20:00,119 --> 01:20:02,578
to work hard where they could...

2143
01:20:02,579 --> 01:20:03,778
And this is just sort of an agreement

2144
01:20:03,779 --> 01:20:05,008
between the master and the slave,

2145
01:20:05,010 --> 01:20:07,920
if they earned a certain amount of money,

2146
01:20:07,920 --> 01:20:09,390
X amount of money,

2147
01:20:09,390 --> 01:20:12,510
they could then buy their own freedom from the master.

2148
01:20:12,510 --> 01:20:14,370
So this was your incentive to work harder

2149
01:20:14,369 --> 01:20:16,258
if you were trained, let's say, as a doctor,

2150
01:20:16,260 --> 01:20:17,130
I worked really hard,

2151
01:20:17,130 --> 01:20:19,770
I can buy myself out of slavery.

2152
01:20:19,770 --> 01:20:23,103
Or a lot of masters would free their slaves in their wills.

2153
01:20:24,090 --> 01:20:25,297
So when they died, they would say,

2154
01:20:25,296 --> 01:20:28,438
"I manumit this slave and that slave."

2155
01:20:28,439 --> 01:20:31,588
So it was a weird institution in that it was,

2156
01:20:31,590 --> 01:20:33,290
elements were just as horrible

2157
01:20:33,289 --> 01:20:34,799
as what we think of as slavery,

2158
01:20:34,800 --> 01:20:36,360
and just as exploitative.

2159
01:20:36,359 --> 01:20:38,698
And it, like I say, the overall notion of slavery

2160
01:20:38,699 --> 01:20:41,848
is intensely dehumanizing.

2161
01:20:41,850 --> 01:20:45,240
But yet there was this wide range of types of slaves.

2162
01:20:45,239 --> 01:20:47,489
And the odd thing is, in the city of Rome,

2163
01:20:47,489 --> 01:20:49,768
many of the worst jobs,

2164
01:20:49,770 --> 01:20:51,179
so if you're, you know,

2165
01:20:51,180 --> 01:20:53,930
just a laborer hauling crap around,

2166
01:20:53,930 --> 01:20:54,840
you know, at the docks

2167
01:20:54,840 --> 01:20:56,340
or, you know, things like that,

2168
01:20:56,340 --> 01:20:58,770
you might well be a free person

2169
01:20:58,770 --> 01:21:01,979
and a slave would hold a skilled job.

2170
01:21:01,979 --> 01:21:04,858
And that seems a little strange or counterintuitive to us,

2171
01:21:04,859 --> 01:21:07,468
but you see how in the Roman economy,

2172
01:21:07,470 --> 01:21:08,820
it sort of works.

2173
01:21:08,819 --> 01:21:10,258
- And that could be one of the things

2174
01:21:10,260 --> 01:21:11,1000
that would be surprising to us

2175
01:21:12,000 --> 01:21:15,560
coming from the modern day to the ancient world

2176
01:21:15,560 --> 01:21:17,009
is just the number of slaves.

2177
01:21:17,010 --> 01:21:19,050
So you mentioned one of the things we don't think about

2178
01:21:19,050 --> 01:21:21,657
is that most of the people are farmers.

2179
01:21:21,657 --> 01:21:22,490
- Yeah. - And then the other thing

2180
01:21:22,489 --> 01:21:24,569
is just the number of slaves.

2181
01:21:24,569 --> 01:21:25,469
- And there's a big debate.

2182
01:21:25,470 --> 01:21:27,389
How many slaves were there?

2183
01:21:27,390 --> 01:21:29,069
You know, what percentage of the populace,

2184
01:21:29,069 --> 01:21:30,569
let's say, in the city of Rome were slaves?

2185
01:21:30,569 --> 01:21:33,899
And this is something historians like to argue about a lot.

2186
01:21:33,899 --> 01:21:35,759
And we keep coming back to this theme of, you know,

2187
01:21:35,760 --> 01:21:37,260
sometimes it's the little things

2188
01:21:37,260 --> 01:21:38,520
that illustrates stuff well.

2189
01:21:38,520 --> 01:21:41,580
And for slaves, the one that always gets me

2190
01:21:41,579 --> 01:21:42,929
is some slaves,

2191
01:21:42,930 --> 01:21:45,389
and these would be sort of the more abused slaves,

2192
01:21:45,390 --> 01:21:48,630
they would literally put little bronze collars on them

2193
01:21:48,630 --> 01:21:52,830
with a tag that said, you know, "Hi, my name is Felix.

2194
01:21:52,829 --> 01:21:54,569
I'm the slave of so-and-so.

2195
01:21:54,569 --> 01:21:55,619
I've run away.

2196
01:21:55,619 --> 01:21:56,519
If you catch me,

2197
01:21:56,520 --> 01:21:58,230
return me to the temple of so-and-so

2198
01:21:58,229 --> 01:21:59,428
and you'll get a reward."

2199
01:21:59,430 --> 01:22:01,170
So it's a dog tag, right?

2200
01:22:01,170 --> 01:22:02,640
Except this is a human being.

2201
01:22:02,640 --> 01:22:04,140
And you can see these in museums.

2202
01:22:04,140 --> 01:22:05,430
I mean, you can go to a museum today

2203
01:22:05,430 --> 01:22:08,550
and see this little bronze collar with a tag on it

2204
01:22:08,550 --> 01:22:10,199
that's talking about a human being

2205
01:22:10,199 --> 01:22:13,139
as if they're this kind of animal that's run away.

2206
01:22:13,140 --> 01:22:14,436
And this is very telling too,

2207
01:22:14,435 --> 01:22:15,539
we're talking about Roman law.

2208
01:22:15,539 --> 01:22:16,649
Under Roman law,

2209
01:22:16,649 --> 01:22:19,649
technically, when a slave runs away,

2210
01:22:19,649 --> 01:22:23,099
the crime that he's committing is theft

2211
01:22:23,100 --> 01:22:27,779
because he's stolen himself from his master.

2212
01:22:27,779 --> 01:22:30,569
So again, it's this very dehumanizing view of it.

2213
01:22:30,569 --> 01:22:32,429
- And just a reminder

2214
01:22:32,430 --> 01:22:34,650
to people in America thinking about this,

2215
01:22:34,649 --> 01:22:39,089
we have a certain view and picture to what slavery is,

2216
01:22:39,090 --> 01:22:42,719
a reminder that all of human history,

2217
01:22:42,720 --> 01:22:46,800
most of human history has had slaves

2218
01:22:46,800 --> 01:22:50,250
of all colors, of all religions.

2219
01:22:50,250 --> 01:22:54,509
That's within us to select a group of people,

2220
01:22:54,510 --> 01:22:56,070
calling the other,

2221
01:22:56,069 --> 01:22:59,669
use them as objects, abuse them.

2222
01:22:59,670 --> 01:23:00,503
And I would say,

2223
01:23:00,502 --> 01:23:03,538
as a person who believes the line between good and evil

2224
01:23:03,539 --> 01:23:05,759
runs to the heart of every man,

2225
01:23:05,760 --> 01:23:08,280
all of us, every person listening to this,

2226
01:23:08,279 --> 01:23:12,359
is capable of being owner of a slave

2227
01:23:12,359 --> 01:23:13,709
if they're put in the position.

2228
01:23:13,710 --> 01:23:15,510
Of capable of hating the other,

2229
01:23:15,510 --> 01:23:16,832
of forming the other,

2230
01:23:18,201 --> 01:23:19,917
of othering other people.

2231
01:23:19,917 --> 01:23:21,513
And we should be very careful,

2232
01:23:23,930 --> 01:23:24,958
to look ourselves in the mirror

2233
01:23:24,960 --> 01:23:26,670
and remind ourselves that we're human.

2234
01:23:26,670 --> 01:23:28,140
It's easy to kind of think, okay,

2235
01:23:28,140 --> 01:23:30,059
well, there's these slaves

2236
01:23:30,060 --> 01:23:31,106
and slave owners through history,

2237
01:23:31,106 --> 01:23:33,089
and I would've never been one of those.

2238
01:23:33,090 --> 01:23:38,090
But just like as we would be farmers,

2239
01:23:39,060 --> 01:23:39,900
we could be both.

2240
01:23:39,899 --> 01:23:41,358
If we went back into history,

2241
01:23:41,359 --> 01:23:43,439
we could be both slaves and slave owners,

2242
01:23:43,439 --> 01:23:45,809
and all of those are humans.

2243
01:23:45,810 --> 01:23:46,800
- I mean, just to build on that,

2244
01:23:46,800 --> 01:23:48,600
I'd say the othering of others

2245
01:23:48,600 --> 01:23:52,050
is a morally corrosive thing to do.

2246
01:23:52,050 --> 01:23:52,883
- Yeah.

2247
01:23:54,569 --> 01:23:56,698
So this fascinating transition

2248
01:23:56,699 --> 01:23:59,279
between the republic to the empire,

2249
01:23:59,279 --> 01:24:00,269
can we talk about that?

2250
01:24:00,270 --> 01:24:02,939
How does the republic fall?

2251
01:24:02,939 --> 01:24:04,066
- Oh, boy. (Gregory laughing)

2252
01:24:04,068 --> 01:24:04,901
Okay, so,

2253
01:24:06,720 --> 01:24:08,999
the Roman Republic, on the one hand,

2254
01:24:09,000 --> 01:24:11,609
is incredibly successful, right?

2255
01:24:11,609 --> 01:24:13,079
In a short period of time,

2256
01:24:13,079 --> 01:24:14,669
is it expanded wildly,

2257
01:24:14,670 --> 01:24:16,710
it's conquered the Mediterranean world,

2258
01:24:16,710 --> 01:24:19,049
it's gained tons of wealth.

2259
01:24:19,050 --> 01:24:23,800
The contradiction here is that Rome's very success

2260
01:24:24,659 --> 01:24:28,288
has made almost every group within Roman society

2261
01:24:28,289 --> 01:24:32,369
deeply unhappy and boiling with resentment.

2262
01:24:32,369 --> 01:24:33,808
So this is the contradiction.

2263
01:24:33,810 --> 01:24:35,819
Enormous success on the surface,

2264
01:24:35,819 --> 01:24:37,379
you end up with this boiling pot

2265
01:24:37,380 --> 01:24:39,269
of resentment and unhappiness.

2266
01:24:39,270 --> 01:24:40,499
So let's break this down.

2267
01:24:40,500 --> 01:24:42,030
Who's unhappy?

2268
01:24:42,029 --> 01:24:45,658
Well, the people fighting Rome's wars.

2269
01:24:45,659 --> 01:24:47,609
The common farmers who went off to fight.

2270
01:24:47,609 --> 01:24:48,659
They joined the army,

2271
01:24:48,659 --> 01:24:49,492
they went and fought,

2272
01:24:49,493 --> 01:24:50,490
they've come back,

2273
01:24:50,489 --> 01:24:51,989
they've seen Rome get wealthy,

2274
01:24:51,989 --> 01:24:54,029
they've seen their generals get wealthy,

2275
01:24:54,029 --> 01:24:55,349
they've conquered all these areas,

2276
01:24:55,350 --> 01:24:57,479
all this money and stuff is going back to Rome,

2277
01:24:57,479 --> 01:24:59,128
but when they're discharged from the army,

2278
01:24:59,130 --> 01:25:00,720
they don't get that much.

2279
01:25:00,720 --> 01:25:01,553
So they feel like,

2280
01:25:01,552 --> 01:25:03,058
"I spent the best years of my life

2281
01:25:03,060 --> 01:25:04,530
fighting for my country.

2282
01:25:04,529 --> 01:25:05,758
I deserve a reward.

2283
01:25:05,760 --> 01:25:06,989
I haven't gotten it."

2284
01:25:06,989 --> 01:25:08,158
So you have a lot of veterans

2285
01:25:08,159 --> 01:25:11,009
who are now unemployed or underemployed.

2286
01:25:11,010 --> 01:25:13,710
Many of them have sold their small family farms

2287
01:25:13,710 --> 01:25:15,149
when they went off to join the army,

2288
01:25:15,149 --> 01:25:16,739
and now they don't have them.

2289
01:25:16,739 --> 01:25:19,408
So that group's unhappy, the veterans.

2290
01:25:19,409 --> 01:25:23,489
You have the aristocrats,

2291
01:25:23,489 --> 01:25:24,359
who, on the surface,

2292
01:25:24,359 --> 01:25:25,192
the ones who are doing well.

2293
01:25:25,193 --> 01:25:28,020
They're the politicians and the generals.

2294
01:25:28,020 --> 01:25:29,399
But as time goes on,

2295
01:25:29,399 --> 01:25:31,754
the ones who get the plum appointments,

2296
01:25:31,755 --> 01:25:33,089
who get the good generalships,

2297
01:25:33,090 --> 01:25:35,730
starts coming from a smaller and smaller subset

2298
01:25:35,729 --> 01:25:36,928
of the aristocrats.

2299
01:25:36,930 --> 01:25:40,019
The Scipio and their friends start to dominate.

2300
01:25:40,020 --> 01:25:42,810
So you end up where most of the aristocratic class

2301
01:25:42,810 --> 01:25:44,580
is feeling, "Hey, I'm left out.

2302
01:25:44,579 --> 01:25:46,498
I didn't get what I deserved."

2303
01:25:46,500 --> 01:25:48,629
What about the half citizens and the allies?

2304
01:25:48,630 --> 01:25:50,940
The Italians who have fought for Rome, who stayed loyal.

2305
01:25:50,939 --> 01:25:51,899
When Hannibal invaded,

2306
01:25:51,899 --> 01:25:54,149
they didn't go over to his side.

2307
01:25:54,149 --> 01:25:56,129
Well, they feel, rightfully,

2308
01:25:56,130 --> 01:25:57,720
we stayed loyal to Rome,

2309
01:25:57,720 --> 01:25:58,560
we fought for them,

2310
01:25:58,560 --> 01:25:59,729
we deserve our reward,

2311
01:25:59,729 --> 01:26:01,199
we should be full citizens.

2312
01:26:01,199 --> 01:26:02,789
But the Romans are traditional,

2313
01:26:02,789 --> 01:26:03,779
they're conservative,

2314
01:26:03,779 --> 01:26:04,918
they don't like change,

2315
01:26:04,920 --> 01:26:06,452
they don't give them that.

2316
01:26:07,560 --> 01:26:09,120
What about all the slaves?

2317
01:26:09,119 --> 01:26:10,859
Well, they've conquered all these foreigners,

2318
01:26:10,859 --> 01:26:11,692
they've sold them,

2319
01:26:11,693 --> 01:26:14,339
now, many of them are working these plantations,

2320
01:26:14,340 --> 01:26:16,320
big plantations owned by rich people

2321
01:26:16,319 --> 01:26:18,539
that used to be little family farms,

2322
01:26:18,539 --> 01:26:20,759
the slaves are obviously unhappy.

2323
01:26:20,760 --> 01:26:22,290
So you end up with a society

2324
01:26:22,289 --> 01:26:25,979
where it's incredibly successful by about a hundred BC

2325
01:26:25,979 --> 01:26:28,438
but almost every group that composes it

2326
01:26:28,439 --> 01:26:30,809
feels like "I haven't shared

2327
01:26:30,810 --> 01:26:32,280
in the benefits of what's happened"

2328
01:26:32,279 --> 01:26:34,408
or "I've been exploited by it."

2329
01:26:34,409 --> 01:26:36,868
So they all end up intensely unhappy.

2330
01:26:36,869 --> 01:26:38,579
And the next a hundred year period,

2331
01:26:38,579 --> 01:26:40,918
from 133 to 31 BC,

2332
01:26:40,920 --> 01:26:42,390
is called the late Roman Republic,

2333
01:26:42,390 --> 01:26:46,409
and it's a time of nearly constant internal strife,

2334
01:26:46,409 --> 01:26:50,372
ultimately culminating in multiple rounds of civil war.

2335
01:26:51,210 --> 01:26:54,629
So Roman society literally breaks apart,

2336
01:26:54,630 --> 01:26:56,160
turns on itself,

2337
01:26:56,159 --> 01:26:58,109
and goes to war with itself

2338
01:26:58,109 --> 01:27:01,859
over not equitably sharing the benefits

2339
01:27:01,859 --> 01:27:03,868
of conquest and of empire.

2340
01:27:03,869 --> 01:27:06,418
So it's a lesson about not sharing

2341
01:27:06,420 --> 01:27:08,670
the benefits of something in a society,

2342
01:27:08,670 --> 01:27:11,190
but concentrating it in one little group.

2343
01:27:11,189 --> 01:27:12,868
And the other thing that happens is,

2344
01:27:12,869 --> 01:27:14,669
among the aristocrats,

2345
01:27:14,670 --> 01:27:17,520
they start to get more and more ambitious.

2346
01:27:17,520 --> 01:27:18,689
So in the past,

2347
01:27:18,689 --> 01:27:20,128
there was a lot of ideology

2348
01:27:20,130 --> 01:27:22,679
of the state is more important than the person.

2349
01:27:22,680 --> 01:27:24,119
If you were a little Roman kid,

2350
01:27:24,119 --> 01:27:26,609
you would've been told these stories of Roman heroes.

2351
01:27:26,609 --> 01:27:28,618
And they're all about self-sacrifice,

2352
01:27:28,619 --> 01:27:30,389
putting the state before you,

2353
01:27:30,390 --> 01:27:31,619
about modesty,

2354
01:27:31,619 --> 01:27:33,748
about these sort of, you know, values.

2355
01:27:33,750 --> 01:27:35,159
Well, by the late republic,

2356
01:27:35,159 --> 01:27:38,990
you have a succession of strong men.

2357
01:27:38,990 --> 01:27:40,139
And it is a chain.

2358
01:27:40,140 --> 01:27:43,769
So it goes, you know, Marius, Sulla, Pompey, Julius Caesar,

2359
01:27:43,770 --> 01:27:47,069
where each one pushes the boundaries

2360
01:27:47,069 --> 01:27:49,169
of the Roman Republic a little bit,

2361
01:27:49,170 --> 01:27:52,529
pushes at the structures of the institutions,

2362
01:27:52,529 --> 01:27:53,609
the republic,

2363
01:27:53,609 --> 01:27:56,068
and they're motivated by personal gain.

2364
01:27:56,069 --> 01:27:59,218
They're putting themselves above the state.

2365
01:27:59,220 --> 01:28:00,270
So at the same time,

2366
01:28:00,270 --> 01:28:03,089
you have lots of groups unhappy in society,

2367
01:28:03,090 --> 01:28:05,099
and you get these strong men

2368
01:28:05,100 --> 01:28:07,289
who are now undermining the institutions,

2369
01:28:07,289 --> 01:28:10,858
chipping away at the things that have been shared,

2370
01:28:10,859 --> 01:28:13,439
things holding the state together,

2371
01:28:13,439 --> 01:28:14,489
and in the end,

2372
01:28:14,489 --> 01:28:15,868
they just become so ambitious,

2373
01:28:15,869 --> 01:28:18,119
they're like, "I don't care about the state.

2374
01:28:18,119 --> 01:28:21,359
I'm gonna try and make myself ruler of Rome."

2375
01:28:21,359 --> 01:28:22,289
So I mean,

2376
01:28:22,289 --> 01:28:24,688
this is gonna culminate obviously in Julius Caesar

2377
01:28:24,689 --> 01:28:27,959
who does succeed in making himself dictator

2378
01:28:27,960 --> 01:28:30,359
for life of the Roman Republic,

2379
01:28:30,359 --> 01:28:32,579
which is tantamount to king,

2380
01:28:32,579 --> 01:28:34,559
and he gets assassinated for it.

2381
01:28:34,560 --> 01:28:37,859
But he's the end point of this progression of people

2382
01:28:37,859 --> 01:28:40,738
who really undermine the institutions,

2383
01:28:40,739 --> 01:28:41,572
the republic,

2384
01:28:41,573 --> 01:28:43,260
through their own personal greed.

2385
01:28:43,260 --> 01:28:45,840
- So the resentment boils and boils and boils,

2386
01:28:45,840 --> 01:28:47,1000
and there's this person that puts themselves above-

2387
01:28:48,000 --> 01:28:48,870
- And they exploit it.

2388
01:28:48,869 --> 01:28:50,819
They're demagogues. They exploit it.

2389
01:28:50,819 --> 01:28:53,048
- But Caesar puts himself above the state

2390
01:28:54,210 --> 01:28:58,320
and that, I guess, the Roman people also hate.

2391
01:28:58,319 --> 01:28:59,609
- Well, I mean, it's a love-hate

2392
01:28:59,609 --> 01:29:01,618
because Caesar is very successful

2393
01:29:01,619 --> 01:29:03,479
at playing to the Roman people.

2394
01:29:03,479 --> 01:29:06,306
So he becomes their hero where he says, you know,

2395
01:29:06,306 --> 01:29:08,999
"I'll be your champion against the state

2396
01:29:09,000 --> 01:29:10,237
who doesn't care about you."

2397
01:29:10,237 --> 01:29:12,240
You know? So Caesar will do things

2398
01:29:12,239 --> 01:29:15,058
where he'll put on big shows for the people.

2399
01:29:15,060 --> 01:29:16,259
And it's cynical.

2400
01:29:16,260 --> 01:29:19,769
I mean, he's doing this to further his own political power,

2401
01:29:19,770 --> 01:29:24,090
but he's presenting himself as a populist, in essence,

2402
01:29:24,090 --> 01:29:26,883
even though he aspires to be a dictator, right?

2403
01:29:27,899 --> 01:29:30,238
But it's a way of winning the people's support,

2404
01:29:30,239 --> 01:29:31,918
because that's a tool for him

2405
01:29:31,920 --> 01:29:34,080
in his struggle with other aristocrats.

2406
01:29:34,079 --> 01:29:37,199
- So a dictator in populist clothing.

2407
01:29:37,199 --> 01:29:38,032
- Yes.

2408
01:29:39,300 --> 01:29:41,040
- So, but he gets- - When convenient.

2409
01:29:41,039 --> 01:29:43,201
Other times, he'll play to the aristocracy.

2410
01:29:44,039 --> 01:29:47,068
- And when he gets assassinated,

2411
01:29:47,069 --> 01:29:50,609
another civil war explodes.

2412
01:29:50,609 --> 01:29:51,778
- That's an interesting moment

2413
01:29:51,779 --> 01:29:54,238
because all these things have been leading up to Caesar,

2414
01:29:54,239 --> 01:29:55,769
and it really is a chain of men.

2415
01:29:55,770 --> 01:29:57,540
So it starts with this guy, Marius,

2416
01:29:57,539 --> 01:30:01,469
who is one of the first to start making armies loyal to him

2417
01:30:01,470 --> 01:30:03,330
rather than to the state.

2418
01:30:03,329 --> 01:30:05,218
That's a step in the wrong direction, right?

2419
01:30:05,220 --> 01:30:07,229
The army should be loyal to the state,

2420
01:30:07,229 --> 01:30:08,519
not to an individual general.

2421
01:30:08,520 --> 01:30:10,110
They shouldn't look for him to rewards.

2422
01:30:10,109 --> 01:30:11,609
Mariuus kind of breaks that,

2423
01:30:11,609 --> 01:30:12,899
makes a precedent.

2424
01:30:12,899 --> 01:30:15,448
One of his proteges is a guy named Sulla.

2425
01:30:15,449 --> 01:30:16,648
Sulla comes along

2426
01:30:16,649 --> 01:30:19,499
and he ends up marching on Rome with his army

2427
01:30:19,500 --> 01:30:21,179
and taking it over.

2428
01:30:21,180 --> 01:30:22,500
And he says, "Well, I'm just doing it

2429
01:30:22,500 --> 01:30:23,580
for the good of the state."

2430
01:30:23,579 --> 01:30:24,839
But that's another precedent.

2431
01:30:24,840 --> 01:30:28,139
Now, you've had someone attacking their own capital city,

2432
01:30:28,140 --> 01:30:31,649
even if they say they're doing it for the right reasons.

2433
01:30:31,649 --> 01:30:33,239
Then Pompey comes along.

2434
01:30:33,239 --> 01:30:35,669
And Pompey just breaks all kinds of things.

2435
01:30:35,670 --> 01:30:39,390
He starts holding offices when he's too young to do so.

2436
01:30:39,390 --> 01:30:43,050
He raises personal armies from his own wealth.

2437
01:30:43,050 --> 01:30:44,489
He disobeys commands,

2438
01:30:44,489 --> 01:30:45,779
he manipulates commands,

2439
01:30:45,779 --> 01:30:47,218
he does all kinds of stuff.

2440
01:30:47,220 --> 01:30:48,120
But in the end,

2441
01:30:48,119 --> 01:30:51,779
he sides with the Senate, when sort of forced.

2442
01:30:51,779 --> 01:30:53,399
And finally, Caesar comes along,

2443
01:30:53,399 --> 01:30:56,189
and Caesar's just shamelessly, "No, it's about me.

2444
01:30:56,189 --> 01:30:57,388
I'm gonna push it."

2445
01:30:57,390 --> 01:30:59,939
And he is the one who wins a civil war

2446
01:30:59,939 --> 01:31:01,828
against the state and Pompey,

2447
01:31:01,829 --> 01:31:03,006
takes over Rome, and says,

2448
01:31:03,006 --> 01:31:05,308
"Now, I'm gonna be dictator."

2449
01:31:05,310 --> 01:31:08,250
And dictator is a traditional office in the Roman state,

2450
01:31:08,250 --> 01:31:09,540
but dictators were limited

2451
01:31:09,539 --> 01:31:11,759
to no more than six months in power.

2452
01:31:11,760 --> 01:31:14,909
And Caesar says, "Well, I'll be dictator for life,"

2453
01:31:14,909 --> 01:31:16,048
which, of course, is king,

2454
01:31:16,050 --> 01:31:17,429
he gets killed for it.

2455
01:31:17,430 --> 01:31:22,430
So Caesar succeeded in taking over the state as one man,

2456
01:31:23,369 --> 01:31:25,679
but he couldn't solve the problem:

2457
01:31:25,680 --> 01:31:28,829
how do you rule Rome as one person

2458
01:31:28,829 --> 01:31:32,759
and not get killed for looking like a king?

2459
01:31:32,760 --> 01:31:33,959
That's the dilemma,

2460
01:31:33,960 --> 01:31:36,239
the riddle that Caesar leaves behind him.

2461
01:31:36,239 --> 01:31:37,349
He did it.

2462
01:31:37,350 --> 01:31:39,390
He sees power as one guy,

2463
01:31:39,390 --> 01:31:41,279
but how do you stay alive?

2464
01:31:41,279 --> 01:31:42,448
How do you come up with something

2465
01:31:42,449 --> 01:31:43,979
that the people will accept?

2466
01:31:43,979 --> 01:31:45,959
And Caesar did some other things which were bad.

2467
01:31:45,960 --> 01:31:47,040
He was arrogant.

2468
01:31:47,039 --> 01:31:51,058
He didn't even pretend that the Senate were his equals.

2469
01:31:51,060 --> 01:31:53,280
He just kind of, you know, railroaded them around.

2470
01:31:53,279 --> 01:31:54,938
He didn't respect them.

2471
01:31:54,939 --> 01:31:56,639
You know, he named a month after himself.

2472
01:31:56,640 --> 01:31:58,649
July, Julius.

2473
01:31:58,649 --> 01:32:00,629
He did egotistical things.

2474
01:32:00,630 --> 01:32:02,580
So that pissed people off.

2475
01:32:02,579 --> 01:32:03,659
They didn't like it.

2476
01:32:03,659 --> 01:32:05,038
And when Caesar dies,

2477
01:32:05,039 --> 01:32:06,958
it's this interesting moment.

2478
01:32:06,960 --> 01:32:09,540
The Republic is sort of dead by then.

2479
01:32:09,539 --> 01:32:11,369
You're gonna have a hard time reviving it.

2480
01:32:11,369 --> 01:32:13,378
You've broken too many precedents.

2481
01:32:13,380 --> 01:32:14,940
But there's a power vacuum now.

2482
01:32:14,939 --> 01:32:17,999
Caesar's gone, what's gonna happen next?

2483
01:32:18,000 --> 01:32:19,649
And you have a whole group of people

2484
01:32:19,649 --> 01:32:21,239
who wanna be the next Caesar.

2485
01:32:21,239 --> 01:32:23,759
So the most obvious is Mark Antony,

2486
01:32:23,760 --> 01:32:25,350
who is Caesar's right-hand man,

2487
01:32:25,350 --> 01:32:26,183
his lieutenant.

2488
01:32:26,182 --> 01:32:28,738
He's a very good general, he's very charismatic.

2489
01:32:28,739 --> 01:32:30,418
Everybody kind of expects Mark Antony

2490
01:32:30,420 --> 01:32:32,670
to just become the next Caesar.

2491
01:32:32,670 --> 01:32:34,710
But there's also another of Caesar's lieutenants,

2492
01:32:34,710 --> 01:32:36,750
a guy named Lepidus, sort of like Antony,

2493
01:32:36,750 --> 01:32:38,490
but not quite as great as him.

2494
01:32:38,489 --> 01:32:39,989
There's the Senate itself,

2495
01:32:39,989 --> 01:32:41,638
which wants to reassert its power,

2496
01:32:41,640 --> 01:32:44,249
kind of become the dominant force in Rome again.

2497
01:32:44,250 --> 01:32:47,040
There's the assassins who killed Caesar.

2498
01:32:47,039 --> 01:32:49,349
Led by Brutus and another guy Cassius,

2499
01:32:49,350 --> 01:32:51,419
they now want to seize control.

2500
01:32:51,420 --> 01:32:54,299
And finally, there's a really weird dark horse candidate

2501
01:32:54,300 --> 01:32:55,800
to fill this power vacuum,

2502
01:32:55,800 --> 01:32:59,880
and that's Julius Caesar's grand nephew,

2503
01:32:59,880 --> 01:33:04,110
who, at the time, is a 17-year-old kid named Octavian.

2504
01:33:04,109 --> 01:33:05,699
Who cares? He's nobody.

2505
01:33:05,699 --> 01:33:07,348
Absolutely nobody.

2506
01:33:07,350 --> 01:33:10,800
But when Caesar's will is opened after his death,

2507
01:33:10,800 --> 01:33:13,079
so posthumously read,

2508
01:33:13,079 --> 01:33:16,139
in his will, Caesar posthumously,

2509
01:33:16,140 --> 01:33:17,549
and this is a little weird,

2510
01:33:17,550 --> 01:33:21,300
posthumously adopts Octavian as his son.

2511
01:33:21,300 --> 01:33:23,340
Now, again, who cares?

2512
01:33:23,340 --> 01:33:24,450
Antony gets the troops,

2513
01:33:24,449 --> 01:33:25,409
Antony gets the money,

2514
01:33:25,409 --> 01:33:26,788
the other people get everything.

2515
01:33:26,789 --> 01:33:28,289
What does Octavian get?

2516
01:33:28,289 --> 01:33:30,418
He gets to now rename himself

2517
01:33:30,420 --> 01:33:33,420
Gaius Julius Caesar Octavianus.

2518
01:33:33,420 --> 01:33:34,649
Who cares?

2519
01:33:34,649 --> 01:33:36,928
Well, around the Mediterranean,

2520
01:33:36,930 --> 01:33:40,860
there's about 12 legions full of hardened soldiers

2521
01:33:40,859 --> 01:33:42,868
who are just kind of used to following

2522
01:33:42,869 --> 01:33:46,018
a guy named Gaius Julius Caesar.

2523
01:33:46,020 --> 01:33:48,390
And even though it's not quite logical,

2524
01:33:48,390 --> 01:33:49,320
this 18-year-old,

2525
01:33:49,319 --> 01:33:50,728
he's now 18-year-old kid,

2526
01:33:50,729 --> 01:33:53,128
inherits an army overnight.

2527
01:33:53,130 --> 01:33:56,159
So he becomes a player in this game for power.

2528
01:33:56,159 --> 01:33:58,768
And the next 30, 40 years

2529
01:33:58,770 --> 01:34:01,859
is gonna be those groups all vying with one another.

2530
01:34:01,859 --> 01:34:03,839
There's another candidate too, Pompey's son.

2531
01:34:03,840 --> 01:34:05,729
Pompey was Caesar's great rival.

2532
01:34:05,729 --> 01:34:06,749
He has a couple sons,

2533
01:34:06,750 --> 01:34:09,240
and one of them, a guy named Sextus Pompey,

2534
01:34:09,239 --> 01:34:12,538
basically becomes a warlord who seizes control of Sicily,

2535
01:34:12,539 --> 01:34:14,218
one of the richest provinces,

2536
01:34:14,220 --> 01:34:15,449
has a whole navy.

2537
01:34:15,449 --> 01:34:18,719
He's vying to be one of these successors too.

2538
01:34:18,720 --> 01:34:19,710
So for the next 40 years,

2539
01:34:19,710 --> 01:34:22,680
it's, as you said, another civil war

2540
01:34:22,680 --> 01:34:24,840
to see which guy emerges.

2541
01:34:24,840 --> 01:34:25,740
Is it gonna be the Senate?

2542
01:34:25,739 --> 01:34:26,849
Is it gonna be the assassins?

2543
01:34:26,850 --> 01:34:27,960
Is it gonna be an Antony?

2544
01:34:27,960 --> 01:34:28,793
Is it gonna be Lepidus?

2545
01:34:28,792 --> 01:34:29,878
Is it gonna be Sextus Pompey?

2546
01:34:29,880 --> 01:34:31,319
Is it gonna be Octavian?

2547
01:34:31,319 --> 01:34:33,769
- So now, looking back at all that history,

2548
01:34:33,770 --> 01:34:35,970
it just feels like history turns on

2549
01:34:35,970 --> 01:34:37,889
so many interesting accidents

2550
01:34:37,890 --> 01:34:41,490
because Octavian, later in named Augustus,

2551
01:34:41,489 --> 01:34:43,202
has turned out to be actually,

2552
01:34:44,909 --> 01:34:46,288
depends how you define good,

2553
01:34:46,289 --> 01:34:49,949
but a good king/emperor,

2554
01:34:49,949 --> 01:34:52,799
different than Caesar in terms of humility,

2555
01:34:52,800 --> 01:34:54,273
at least being able to play.

2556
01:34:55,560 --> 01:34:57,483
Not to piss off everybody,

2557
01:34:58,710 --> 01:35:01,140
but like it could have been so many other people.

2558
01:35:01,140 --> 01:35:03,732
That could have been the fall of Rome.

2559
01:35:03,731 --> 01:35:06,299
So like, it's a fascinating little turn of history.

2560
01:35:06,300 --> 01:35:08,880
Maybe Caesar saw something in this individual.

2561
01:35:08,880 --> 01:35:11,279
It's not an accident that he was in the will.

2562
01:35:11,279 --> 01:35:12,658
- Yeah, it's, I mean,

2563
01:35:12,659 --> 01:35:15,359
Caesar clearly did see something in him.

2564
01:35:15,359 --> 01:35:18,359
And Octavian, I mean, to cut to the end,

2565
01:35:18,359 --> 01:35:20,638
is the one who emerges from all that as the victor.

2566
01:35:20,640 --> 01:35:21,960
We can talk about how he does it,

2567
01:35:21,960 --> 01:35:24,180
but he's the one who sort of ends up

2568
01:35:24,180 --> 01:35:26,040
in the same position as Caesar.

2569
01:35:26,039 --> 01:35:27,208
It takes him 30 years,

2570
01:35:27,210 --> 01:35:28,680
but he defeats all the foes.

2571
01:35:28,680 --> 01:35:29,1000
He's the sole guy,

2572
01:35:30,000 --> 01:35:32,220
he now faces Caesar's riddle:

2573
01:35:32,220 --> 01:35:34,050
How do you rule Rome as one guy

2574
01:35:34,050 --> 01:35:35,340
and not get killed?

2575
01:35:35,340 --> 01:35:37,830
And Octavian, what makes him stand out

2576
01:35:37,829 --> 01:35:40,409
and what makes him fascinating to me

2577
01:35:40,409 --> 01:35:43,139
is he wasn't a good general.

2578
01:35:43,140 --> 01:35:44,460
In fact, he was a terrible general.

2579
01:35:44,460 --> 01:35:47,219
He lost almost every battle he commanded.

2580
01:35:47,220 --> 01:35:50,910
But what he is is he's politically savvy

2581
01:35:50,909 --> 01:35:53,429
and he's very good at what today we would call

2582
01:35:53,430 --> 01:35:55,680
manipulation of your public image

2583
01:35:55,680 --> 01:35:57,390
and propaganda.

2584
01:35:57,390 --> 01:36:01,050
So he basically defeats Mark Antony, partially,

2585
01:36:01,050 --> 01:36:03,929
by waging a propaganda war against him.

2586
01:36:03,930 --> 01:36:07,260
I mean, Antony starts out as a legitimate rival,

2587
01:36:07,260 --> 01:36:09,570
and there are two Romans vying for power,

2588
01:36:09,569 --> 01:36:12,749
at the end of this war, propaganda war,

2589
01:36:12,750 --> 01:36:15,120
Octavian has managed to portray Antony

2590
01:36:15,119 --> 01:36:17,728
as a foreign aggressor

2591
01:36:17,729 --> 01:36:20,449
allied with an enemy king or queen,

2592
01:36:20,449 --> 01:36:22,229
in this case, Cleopatra,

2593
01:36:22,229 --> 01:36:24,659
and who is an official enemy of the Roman state,

2594
01:36:24,659 --> 01:36:26,429
and that's all propaganda.

2595
01:36:26,430 --> 01:36:28,559
So he takes what's a civil war

2596
01:36:28,560 --> 01:36:31,680
and makes it look like a war against a foreign enemy.

2597
01:36:31,680 --> 01:36:35,430
And when Octavian becomes the sole ruler,

2598
01:36:35,430 --> 01:36:37,410
he looks at what Caesar did wrong

2599
01:36:37,409 --> 01:36:41,069
and he very carefully avoids the same mistakes.

2600
01:36:41,069 --> 01:36:43,589
So the first thing is just how he lives his life.

2601
01:36:43,590 --> 01:36:44,729
He's very modest.

2602
01:36:44,729 --> 01:36:47,338
He lives in an ordinary house like other aristocrats.

2603
01:36:47,340 --> 01:36:49,830
He wears just a plain toga, nothing fancy.

2604
01:36:49,829 --> 01:36:51,478
He's respectful to the Senate.

2605
01:36:51,479 --> 01:36:52,858
He treats them with respect.

2606
01:36:52,859 --> 01:36:54,719
He eats simple foods.

2607
01:36:54,720 --> 01:36:58,349
I mean, he's someone who cared about the reality of power,

2608
01:36:58,350 --> 01:37:00,570
not the external trappings.

2609
01:37:00,569 --> 01:37:01,859
Clearly, there's some rulers

2610
01:37:01,859 --> 01:37:03,809
who love "I want to dress in fancy clothes.

2611
01:37:03,810 --> 01:37:05,819
I want to be surrounded by gold. Everything.

2612
01:37:05,819 --> 01:37:07,559
This is what makes me feel good."

2613
01:37:07,560 --> 01:37:08,640
Octavian is the opposite.

2614
01:37:08,640 --> 01:37:10,289
He doesn't care about any of that.

2615
01:37:10,289 --> 01:37:12,449
He wants real power.

2616
01:37:12,449 --> 01:37:13,588
And then the other thing is,

2617
01:37:13,590 --> 01:37:16,500
how is he gonna rule Rome without looking like a king?

2618
01:37:16,500 --> 01:37:18,689
And his solution to this is brilliant.

2619
01:37:18,689 --> 01:37:23,309
He basically pretends to resign from all his public offices.

2620
01:37:23,310 --> 01:37:24,630
And not pretends, he does.

2621
01:37:24,630 --> 01:37:27,150
So he holds no official office.

2622
01:37:27,149 --> 01:37:29,338
But what he does is he manipulates

2623
01:37:29,340 --> 01:37:32,130
so that the Roman Senate votes him

2624
01:37:32,130 --> 01:37:35,310
the powers of the key Roman offices,

2625
01:37:35,310 --> 01:37:37,530
but not the office itself.

2626
01:37:37,529 --> 01:37:40,259
So the highest office in the Roman state is the consul.

2627
01:37:40,260 --> 01:37:42,179
Consuls have the power to command armies,

2628
01:37:42,180 --> 01:37:43,530
do all sorts of things,

2629
01:37:43,529 --> 01:37:44,879
run meetings of the Senate.

2630
01:37:45,750 --> 01:37:48,770
Octavian gets voted the powers of a consul.

2631
01:37:48,770 --> 01:37:50,219
So he can command armies,

2632
01:37:50,220 --> 01:37:51,810
control meetings of the Senate, do all this,

2633
01:37:51,810 --> 01:37:55,290
but he's not one of the two consuls elected for every year.

2634
01:37:55,289 --> 01:37:56,819
So he's just kind of floating

2635
01:37:56,819 --> 01:38:01,049
or drifting off to the side of the Roman government.

2636
01:38:01,050 --> 01:38:02,610
He gets the power of a tribune,

2637
01:38:02,609 --> 01:38:04,109
which has all sorts of powers.

2638
01:38:04,109 --> 01:38:05,548
He can veto anything he wants,

2639
01:38:05,550 --> 01:38:08,759
but he's not one of the tribunes elected for any one year.

2640
01:38:08,760 --> 01:38:11,130
So the state, the republic,

2641
01:38:11,130 --> 01:38:12,930
appears to continue as it always has.

2642
01:38:12,930 --> 01:38:14,520
Each year, they hold the same elections,

2643
01:38:14,520 --> 01:38:16,020
they elect the same number of people,

2644
01:38:16,020 --> 01:38:18,450
notionally, those people are in charge.

2645
01:38:18,449 --> 01:38:20,039
But floating off to the side,

2646
01:38:20,039 --> 01:38:21,659
you have this guy, Octavian,

2647
01:38:21,659 --> 01:38:23,038
who has equivalent power,

2648
01:38:23,039 --> 01:38:26,219
not just to any one magistrate or official,

2649
01:38:26,220 --> 01:38:27,930
but to all of them.

2650
01:38:27,930 --> 01:38:30,216
So any moment, he can just sort of pop up and say,

2651
01:38:30,216 --> 01:38:31,649
"No, let's not do this.

2652
01:38:31,649 --> 01:38:33,209
Let's do something else."

2653
01:38:33,210 --> 01:38:36,390
And he also keeps the army under his personal control.

2654
01:38:36,390 --> 01:38:37,890
- Isn't this a fascinating story?

2655
01:38:37,890 --> 01:38:39,870
Like what do you think is the psychology

2656
01:38:39,869 --> 01:38:40,766
of Augustus, of Octavian?

2657
01:38:40,766 --> 01:38:43,258
- Yeah, and he later changed his name to Augustus

2658
01:38:43,260 --> 01:38:44,461
when he sort of becomes first emperor.

2659
01:38:44,461 --> 01:38:45,930
And the other thing he does is he hides his power

2660
01:38:45,930 --> 01:38:47,760
behind all these different names.

2661
01:38:47,760 --> 01:38:49,710
So, you know, Caesar called himself

2662
01:38:49,710 --> 01:38:50,820
dictator for life, right?

2663
01:38:50,819 --> 01:38:52,198
So everybody knew what he was.

2664
01:38:52,199 --> 01:38:54,019
Octavian, we even have a source that talks about it,

2665
01:38:54,020 --> 01:38:56,076
he says he wondered what to call himself.

2666
01:38:56,077 --> 01:38:57,750
"Do I call myself king? No, can't do that.

2667
01:38:57,750 --> 01:38:59,700
Dictator for life? No way.

2668
01:38:59,699 --> 01:39:01,319
Maybe I'll call myself Romulus?"

2669
01:39:01,319 --> 01:39:02,152
That was the founder of Rome.

2670
01:39:02,153 --> 01:39:03,990
"No, no. Romulus was a king."

2671
01:39:03,989 --> 01:39:05,759
And finally, his solution is,

2672
01:39:05,760 --> 01:39:08,610
he takes a bunch of titles,

2673
01:39:08,609 --> 01:39:10,681
which are all ambiguous,

2674
01:39:11,520 --> 01:39:14,760
and no one of them sounds that impressive,

2675
01:39:14,760 --> 01:39:16,560
but collectively, they are.

2676
01:39:16,560 --> 01:39:20,609
So for example, one of the titles he gets is Augustus,

2677
01:39:20,609 --> 01:39:22,498
which is something tied to Roman religion.

2678
01:39:22,500 --> 01:39:24,509
Something that is Augustus in Latin

2679
01:39:24,510 --> 01:39:26,429
has two possible meanings.

2680
01:39:26,430 --> 01:39:29,070
One is, someone who is Augustus

2681
01:39:29,069 --> 01:39:30,659
is very pious.

2682
01:39:30,659 --> 01:39:32,308
They respect the gods deeply.

2683
01:39:32,310 --> 01:39:34,199
Well, that sounds nice, doesn't it?

2684
01:39:34,199 --> 01:39:35,032
Well, on the other hand,

2685
01:39:35,033 --> 01:39:36,569
an alternative meaning for Augustus

2686
01:39:36,569 --> 01:39:38,581
is something that is itself divine.

2687
01:39:39,510 --> 01:39:42,900
So is he just a deeply religious pious person

2688
01:39:42,899 --> 01:39:44,968
or is he himself sacred?

2689
01:39:44,970 --> 01:39:46,262
There's that ambiguity.

2690
01:39:47,130 --> 01:39:49,110
He calls himself princeps,

2691
01:39:49,109 --> 01:39:51,778
which means first citizen.

2692
01:39:51,779 --> 01:39:54,359
Okay, what the hell does that mean?

2693
01:39:54,359 --> 01:39:56,459
Am I a citizen just like everybody else

2694
01:39:56,460 --> 01:39:58,500
or am I the first citizen,

2695
01:39:58,500 --> 01:40:01,049
which means I'm superior to all the others?

2696
01:40:01,050 --> 01:40:03,809
So every title he takes has this weird ambiguity.

2697
01:40:03,810 --> 01:40:06,120
He calls himself imperator,

2698
01:40:06,119 --> 01:40:07,829
which is traditionally something

2699
01:40:07,829 --> 01:40:10,679
that soldiers shout at a victorious general

2700
01:40:10,680 --> 01:40:11,730
who's won a battle.

2701
01:40:11,729 --> 01:40:14,068
And now he takes this as a permanent title,

2702
01:40:14,069 --> 01:40:16,678
so it implies he's a good general.

2703
01:40:16,680 --> 01:40:17,1000
And by the way, it's from imperator

2704
01:40:18,000 --> 01:40:21,270
that we get the word emperor, an empire.

2705
01:40:21,270 --> 01:40:23,609
So originally, it's a military title,

2706
01:40:23,609 --> 01:40:25,738
a spontaneous military acclimation.

2707
01:40:25,739 --> 01:40:28,319
- It's just fascinating that he figured out a way

2708
01:40:28,319 --> 01:40:31,138
through public image, through branding

2709
01:40:31,140 --> 01:40:36,140
to gain power, maintain power,

2710
01:40:36,569 --> 01:40:40,366
and still pacify the boiling turmoil

2711
01:40:42,359 --> 01:40:44,789
that led to the civil wars. - Yeah.

2712
01:40:44,789 --> 01:40:47,338
Well, two things, I think, work in his favor as well.

2713
01:40:47,340 --> 01:40:51,060
One is he brings peace and stability.

2714
01:40:51,060 --> 01:40:53,550
So by this point, the Romans have experienced

2715
01:40:53,550 --> 01:40:58,139
a hundred years, almost, of civil war and chaos.

2716
01:40:58,140 --> 01:41:00,660
So at that point, you know, your family,

2717
01:41:00,659 --> 01:41:02,998
maybe you've had family members die in these wars,

2718
01:41:03,000 --> 01:41:04,110
have been proscribed,

2719
01:41:04,109 --> 01:41:05,788
your property has been confiscated,

2720
01:41:05,789 --> 01:41:06,749
who knows what.

2721
01:41:06,750 --> 01:41:09,779
And here's a guy who brings peace and stability

2722
01:41:09,779 --> 01:41:12,269
and doesn't seem oppressive or cruel or whatever.

2723
01:41:12,270 --> 01:41:13,890
So you're like, "Okay, fine.

2724
01:41:13,890 --> 01:41:14,723
I don't care.

2725
01:41:14,722 --> 01:41:16,349
Maybe he's killed the republic,

2726
01:41:16,350 --> 01:41:19,320
but at least we're not dying in the streets anymore."

2727
01:41:19,319 --> 01:41:20,998
So that's a big thing he does.

2728
01:41:21,000 --> 01:41:22,889
And secondly,

2729
01:41:22,890 --> 01:41:24,930
even though Augustus always seemed kind of sickly,

2730
01:41:24,930 --> 01:41:28,349
his constitution, he lives forever.

2731
01:41:28,350 --> 01:41:30,570
He rules for like 50 years.

2732
01:41:30,569 --> 01:41:33,328
And by the time he dies,

2733
01:41:33,329 --> 01:41:36,148
there's no one, literally, almost left alive

2734
01:41:36,149 --> 01:41:37,649
who can remember the republic.

2735
01:41:38,550 --> 01:41:41,340
So at that point, by the time he dies,

2736
01:41:41,340 --> 01:41:43,739
this is the only system we know.

2737
01:41:43,739 --> 01:41:47,549
- That's another just fascinating accident of history,

2738
01:41:47,550 --> 01:41:50,759
'cause as we talked about with Alexander the Great,

2739
01:41:50,760 --> 01:41:54,482
who knows if he lived for another 40 years?

2740
01:41:56,503 --> 01:42:00,028
If over time, the people that hate the new thing die off

2741
01:42:00,029 --> 01:42:03,032
and then their sons come into power,

2742
01:42:04,319 --> 01:42:05,458
that could be a very different story

2743
01:42:05,460 --> 01:42:06,712
and maybe we would be talking about Greek Empire.

2744
01:42:06,712 --> 01:42:07,589
- Yeah, that's a fluke of fate,

2745
01:42:07,590 --> 01:42:09,960
but it's hugely influential on history.

2746
01:42:09,960 --> 01:42:11,928
- You mentioned Cleopatra.

2747
01:42:11,927 --> 01:42:12,929
If we go back to that,

2748
01:42:12,930 --> 01:42:14,910
what role did she play?

2749
01:42:14,909 --> 01:42:17,308
Another fascinating human being.

2750
01:42:17,310 --> 01:42:19,110
- Cleopatra is interesting.

2751
01:42:19,109 --> 01:42:22,318
I mean, she was a direct descendant

2752
01:42:22,319 --> 01:42:24,809
of one of Alexander the Great's generals,

2753
01:42:24,810 --> 01:42:25,890
Ptolemy.

2754
01:42:25,890 --> 01:42:28,019
When Alexander's empire had broken up,

2755
01:42:28,020 --> 01:42:29,159
Ptolemy, this general,

2756
01:42:29,159 --> 01:42:30,719
had seized control of Egypt,

2757
01:42:30,720 --> 01:42:32,129
made it his kingdom.

2758
01:42:32,130 --> 01:42:34,920
And she, 10 generations later,

2759
01:42:34,920 --> 01:42:38,100
is a descendant of this Macedonian general.

2760
01:42:38,100 --> 01:42:41,939
So Egypt had been ruled by, in essence, foreigners,

2761
01:42:41,939 --> 01:42:44,338
these Macedonian dynasty of kings,

2762
01:42:44,340 --> 01:42:47,610
and often, they literally were ruled by the same dynasty

2763
01:42:47,609 --> 01:42:50,789
'cause they had a habit of marrying brothers to sisters,

2764
01:42:50,789 --> 01:42:52,139
and Cleopatra is, in fact,

2765
01:42:52,140 --> 01:42:54,273
originally married to her younger brother.

2766
01:42:56,250 --> 01:42:57,780
But despite that,

2767
01:42:57,779 --> 01:43:01,801
she seems to have intensely identified with Egypt.

2768
01:43:02,670 --> 01:43:04,620
In fact, she seems to have been the first one

2769
01:43:04,619 --> 01:43:06,359
of all these Ptolemy kings

2770
01:43:06,359 --> 01:43:08,809
who actually bothered to learn to speak Egyptian.

2771
01:43:09,689 --> 01:43:13,799
So she seemed to really have cared about Egypt as well.

2772
01:43:13,800 --> 01:43:17,429
And she was clearly very smart, very clever.

2773
01:43:17,430 --> 01:43:20,639
And so she's living at a time

2774
01:43:20,640 --> 01:43:21,809
during the late republic,

2775
01:43:21,810 --> 01:43:23,790
when Rome is having all these civil wars,

2776
01:43:23,789 --> 01:43:27,989
and Egypt is really the last big, independent kingdom left

2777
01:43:27,989 --> 01:43:29,849
around the shores of the Mediterranean.

2778
01:43:29,850 --> 01:43:32,519
Everything else has been conquered by Rome.

2779
01:43:32,520 --> 01:43:35,520
So she is in this very precarious position

2780
01:43:35,520 --> 01:43:38,160
where clearly she wants to maintain Egyptian independence,

2781
01:43:38,159 --> 01:43:41,549
but Rome is this juggernaut that's rolling over everything.

2782
01:43:41,550 --> 01:43:44,040
And she ends up meeting Julius Caesar

2783
01:43:44,039 --> 01:43:47,219
when Caesar comes to Egypt chasing Pompey,

2784
01:43:47,220 --> 01:43:48,180
his great rival.

2785
01:43:48,180 --> 01:43:49,230
After he defeats Pompey,

2786
01:43:49,229 --> 01:43:50,458
Pompey runs to Egypt,

2787
01:43:50,460 --> 01:43:52,200
thinking he'll sanctuary there,

2788
01:43:52,199 --> 01:43:54,449
and the Egyptians kill him and chop off his head.

2789
01:43:54,449 --> 01:43:55,499
And when Caesar lands,

2790
01:43:55,500 --> 01:43:58,166
they hand it to him and say, "Here, have a present."

2791
01:43:59,909 --> 01:44:01,078
And she, of course, famously ends up

2792
01:44:01,079 --> 01:44:02,939
having a love affair with Caesar.

2793
01:44:02,939 --> 01:44:05,309
Was that a genuine love

2794
01:44:05,310 --> 01:44:06,719
or was she just sort of, you know,

2795
01:44:06,720 --> 01:44:07,580
using this as a way

2796
01:44:07,579 --> 01:44:09,478
to try and keep Egypt independent,

2797
01:44:09,479 --> 01:44:10,888
to give it some status?

2798
01:44:10,890 --> 01:44:12,510
We don't know.

2799
01:44:12,510 --> 01:44:14,853
After she does have several kids with Caesar,

2800
01:44:15,689 --> 01:44:17,608
after Caesar's assassinated,

2801
01:44:17,609 --> 01:44:20,459
and the Roman world is having another civil war

2802
01:44:20,460 --> 01:44:22,260
between Octavian and Mark Antony,

2803
01:44:22,260 --> 01:44:24,480
Mark Antony is basing himself in the east,

2804
01:44:24,479 --> 01:44:25,678
he meets Cleopatra

2805
01:44:25,680 --> 01:44:28,019
and he has a big love affair with her.

2806
01:44:28,020 --> 01:44:29,943
And this one seems pretty genuine.

2807
01:44:30,960 --> 01:44:32,670
I mean, Antony and Cleopatra,

2808
01:44:32,670 --> 01:44:34,170
there's a lot of stories about them

2809
01:44:34,170 --> 01:44:35,579
kind of partying together.

2810
01:44:35,579 --> 01:44:37,858
They like to sort of cosplay

2811
01:44:37,859 --> 01:44:40,379
and dress up as different gods.

2812
01:44:40,380 --> 01:44:43,529
So Cleopatra would dress up as the goddess Isis

2813
01:44:43,529 --> 01:44:44,999
and Antony would dress up

2814
01:44:45,000 --> 01:44:47,100
as the god Dionysus in a leopard skin,

2815
01:44:47,100 --> 01:44:49,289
and they have these big parties and stuff.

2816
01:44:49,289 --> 01:44:53,128
And they end up, together, fighting against Octavian.

2817
01:44:53,130 --> 01:44:56,670
And in the end, they're defeated by Octavian.

2818
01:44:56,670 --> 01:44:59,790
And Antony commits suicide,

2819
01:44:59,789 --> 01:45:03,269
Cleopatra, there's differing accounts of her death.

2820
01:45:03,270 --> 01:45:05,189
She may have also killed herself

2821
01:45:05,189 --> 01:45:08,039
or she may actually have been killed by Octavian

2822
01:45:08,039 --> 01:45:09,589
to just get her out of the way.

2823
01:45:10,439 --> 01:45:11,638
But she's an interesting figure

2824
01:45:11,640 --> 01:45:14,700
because she was clearly a very smart woman

2825
01:45:14,699 --> 01:45:18,659
who managed to keep Egypt alive as an independent state.

2826
01:45:18,659 --> 01:45:21,149
She seemed to have actually cared about Egypt,

2827
01:45:21,149 --> 01:45:23,038
and identified with it,

2828
01:45:23,039 --> 01:45:25,446
and succeeded at a time with all these famous people,

2829
01:45:25,447 --> 01:45:28,350
you know, in being a real kind of mover and shaker

2830
01:45:28,350 --> 01:45:30,359
and a force in events.

2831
01:45:30,359 --> 01:45:33,028
- I mean, she's probably one of the most influential women

2832
01:45:33,029 --> 01:45:34,321
in human history.

2833
01:45:35,279 --> 01:45:36,299
- She's certainly, again,

2834
01:45:36,300 --> 01:45:39,809
she's someone that her image is incredibly important.

2835
01:45:39,810 --> 01:45:40,979
- Yes.

2836
01:45:40,979 --> 01:45:42,216
- And I mean, one of the interesting things,

2837
01:45:42,216 --> 01:45:44,452
you know, the whole question of gender in the Roman world.

2838
01:45:44,453 --> 01:45:46,650
I mean, this gets into Roman sources,

2839
01:45:46,649 --> 01:45:49,919
but of course it's a heavily male dominated history.

2840
01:45:49,920 --> 01:45:52,170
And, I mean, men and women

2841
01:45:52,170 --> 01:45:53,643
did not have equality in Ancient Rome.

2842
01:45:53,643 --> 01:45:55,620
It's a male dominated society.

2843
01:45:55,619 --> 01:45:57,748
It's misogynist in many ways.

2844
01:45:57,750 --> 01:45:59,460
But what I'm constantly struck by

2845
01:45:59,460 --> 01:46:02,475
is when you start, again, delving into the sources,

2846
01:46:02,475 --> 01:46:04,709
you know, you always hear, okay, you know,

2847
01:46:04,710 --> 01:46:06,030
well, there was this one woman

2848
01:46:06,029 --> 01:46:07,349
who was a philosopher

2849
01:46:07,350 --> 01:46:09,600
and she's an exception to the rule.

2850
01:46:09,600 --> 01:46:11,340
And yeah, okay, she's fine.

2851
01:46:11,340 --> 01:46:12,180
And then you start looking into,

2852
01:46:12,180 --> 01:46:15,479
oh, and there's also 60 other female philosophers.

2853
01:46:15,479 --> 01:46:17,548
Well, is that so much an exception anymore?

2854
01:46:17,550 --> 01:46:19,889
Or, you know, Cleopatra is the one queen,

2855
01:46:19,890 --> 01:46:21,029
she's this strong queen.

2856
01:46:21,029 --> 01:46:21,862
And then you look and, well,

2857
01:46:21,863 --> 01:46:22,800
there was this other queen here,

2858
01:46:22,800 --> 01:46:23,670
there was this queen here,

2859
01:46:23,670 --> 01:46:25,200
there was this queen here who led armies,

2860
01:46:25,199 --> 01:46:26,729
and here's another one who led armies.

2861
01:46:26,729 --> 01:46:28,559
And again, it's like, well,

2862
01:46:28,560 --> 01:46:30,060
are they exceptions to the rule

2863
01:46:30,060 --> 01:46:31,920
or is just the history that was written,

2864
01:46:31,920 --> 01:46:33,480
which is written by men,

2865
01:46:33,479 --> 01:46:35,938
a little bit selective in how it portrays them

2866
01:46:35,939 --> 01:46:38,608
because the sources are all these male elites

2867
01:46:38,609 --> 01:46:40,948
who have very definite ideas about women?

2868
01:46:40,949 --> 01:46:43,742
You know, the conventional notion has always been that,

2869
01:46:44,729 --> 01:46:46,349
you know, business in the Roman Empire

2870
01:46:46,350 --> 01:46:48,029
was a male field.

2871
01:46:48,029 --> 01:46:50,609
Well, but then there's this woman, Eumachia, in Pompeii,

2872
01:46:50,609 --> 01:46:53,519
who actually had the largest building in Pompeii

2873
01:46:53,520 --> 01:46:55,350
right on the forum named after her

2874
01:46:55,350 --> 01:46:56,940
with a giant statue of her,

2875
01:46:56,939 --> 01:46:58,078
and she was a patron

2876
01:46:58,079 --> 01:47:00,599
to a bunch of the most important guilds in Pompeii.

2877
01:47:00,600 --> 01:47:02,249
Okay, she's the exception to the rule.

2878
01:47:02,250 --> 01:47:04,050
Oh, but then there's these other four women

2879
01:47:04,050 --> 01:47:05,489
we have from Pompeii

2880
01:47:05,489 --> 01:47:07,498
who also were patrons of guilds.

2881
01:47:07,500 --> 01:47:09,300
And then there's this woman, Plancia Magna,

2882
01:47:09,300 --> 01:47:10,290
in this other place,

2883
01:47:10,289 --> 01:47:12,809
and she was the most important patron in the town

2884
01:47:12,810 --> 01:47:14,520
and put up all these statues.

2885
01:47:14,520 --> 01:47:16,409
So at some point, when do you start to say,

2886
01:47:16,409 --> 01:47:19,438
well, maybe women did play more of a role,

2887
01:47:19,439 --> 01:47:22,379
but they just haven't been recorded in the sources

2888
01:47:22,380 --> 01:47:24,360
in the way that maybe they deserve to be?

2889
01:47:24,359 --> 01:47:25,619
- Yeah, that's a fascinating question.

2890
01:47:25,619 --> 01:47:28,018
Is it the bias of society

2891
01:47:28,020 --> 01:47:30,698
or is it the bias of the historian?

2892
01:47:30,698 --> 01:47:33,178
The bias of the society that the historian is writing about

2893
01:47:33,180 --> 01:47:34,167
or the bias of the actual historian?

2894
01:47:34,167 --> 01:47:35,699
- And the bias of the historians

2895
01:47:35,699 --> 01:47:37,828
who have written history up to this point.

2896
01:47:37,829 --> 01:47:38,669
- Yeah.

2897
01:47:38,670 --> 01:47:40,109
- I was just writing a lecture,

2898
01:47:40,109 --> 01:47:42,508
which was about this woman, Musa,

2899
01:47:42,510 --> 01:47:44,250
who is a crazy story.

2900
01:47:44,250 --> 01:47:46,980
And she ties into Augustus, actually.

2901
01:47:46,979 --> 01:47:50,608
Augustus, his biggest diplomatic triumph

2902
01:47:50,609 --> 01:47:52,798
that he boasted about constantly

2903
01:47:52,800 --> 01:47:55,860
was that about 50 years before him,

2904
01:47:55,859 --> 01:47:58,439
the Romans had sent an expedition into Parthia,

2905
01:47:58,439 --> 01:48:01,709
this neighboring kingdom led by Crassus,

2906
01:48:01,710 --> 01:48:03,420
and they'd gotten wiped out.

2907
01:48:03,420 --> 01:48:04,740
So it was this big disaster,

2908
01:48:04,739 --> 01:48:06,089
military disaster.

2909
01:48:06,090 --> 01:48:08,880
And the standards of the Roman legions,

2910
01:48:08,880 --> 01:48:11,429
the eagles that each Roman legion carried,

2911
01:48:11,430 --> 01:48:13,499
had been captured by the Parthians.

2912
01:48:13,500 --> 01:48:15,179
And this is the most humiliating thing

2913
01:48:15,180 --> 01:48:16,589
that can happen to a Roman legion,

2914
01:48:16,590 --> 01:48:18,989
to have its eagles captured.

2915
01:48:18,989 --> 01:48:20,729
And Augustus desperately wanted

2916
01:48:20,729 --> 01:48:22,138
to negotiate with the Parthians

2917
01:48:22,140 --> 01:48:23,1000
to get these eagles returned.

2918
01:48:24,000 --> 01:48:26,069
Okay, this was his big diplomatic thing.

2919
01:48:26,069 --> 01:48:29,218
So he was constantly sending these embassies to Parthia.

2920
01:48:29,220 --> 01:48:30,449
On one of these embassies,

2921
01:48:30,449 --> 01:48:33,118
he sent along as a gift to the Parthian king

2922
01:48:33,119 --> 01:48:35,191
a slave woman named Musa.

2923
01:48:36,659 --> 01:48:39,208
Musa seems to have pleased the king of Parthia

2924
01:48:39,210 --> 01:48:41,790
because she becomes one of his concubines.

2925
01:48:41,789 --> 01:48:44,309
And then she gives birth to a son by the king,

2926
01:48:44,310 --> 01:48:46,080
and eventually, she becomes,

2927
01:48:46,079 --> 01:48:48,182
upgraded to the level of wife.

2928
01:48:49,590 --> 01:48:54,590
And Musa eventually murders the Parthian King,

2929
01:48:56,100 --> 01:49:01,100
arranges it so that her son becomes the king of Parthia,

2930
01:49:01,680 --> 01:49:04,620
and she's really ruling the whole empire

2931
01:49:04,619 --> 01:49:06,688
behind the scenes as his mother.

2932
01:49:06,689 --> 01:49:10,979
So this is a literal rags to riches story of a slave,

2933
01:49:10,979 --> 01:49:12,449
someone who starts out a slave

2934
01:49:12,449 --> 01:49:15,689
and becomes the queen of an empire

2935
01:49:15,689 --> 01:49:18,419
almost as large and powerful as Rome.

2936
01:49:18,420 --> 01:49:21,573
Okay? But yet, how often do we hear about Musa?

2937
01:49:22,590 --> 01:49:25,080
And when you look in traditional histories

2938
01:49:25,079 --> 01:49:26,909
of Roman-Parthian relations,

2939
01:49:26,909 --> 01:49:27,779
and I went and looked at this

2940
01:49:27,779 --> 01:49:29,848
because I was just writing this lecture,

2941
01:49:29,850 --> 01:49:32,519
most of those histories didn't even mention her.

2942
01:49:32,520 --> 01:49:33,810
They just talked about her son.

2943
01:49:33,810 --> 01:49:35,189
Like he had just come out of nowhere

2944
01:49:35,189 --> 01:49:38,039
and become the new heir to the Parthian throne

2945
01:49:38,039 --> 01:49:40,139
when it was all her doing clearly.

2946
01:49:40,140 --> 01:49:44,699
Now, that's selective editing of history by historians

2947
01:49:44,699 --> 01:49:47,401
to downplay the role that this woman played.

2948
01:49:48,420 --> 01:49:51,270
And there's a lot of examples like that.

2949
01:49:51,270 --> 01:49:52,409
- That's fascinating.

2950
01:49:52,409 --> 01:49:53,999
- She got overthrown after a few years.

2951
01:49:54,000 --> 01:49:55,260
There was a revolution against her,

2952
01:49:55,260 --> 01:49:56,1000
and we don't know what happened to her then.

2953
01:49:57,000 --> 01:49:59,520
But she's a really interesting figure.

2954
01:49:59,520 --> 01:50:02,010
Oh, and by the way, Augustus did negotiate

2955
01:50:02,010 --> 01:50:03,570
the return of the Parthian standards

2956
01:50:03,569 --> 01:50:04,948
and got them back.

2957
01:50:04,949 --> 01:50:06,929
And he was so proud of this

2958
01:50:06,930 --> 01:50:08,910
that this is what he constantly boasted about.

2959
01:50:08,909 --> 01:50:11,009
And the most famous statue of Augustus,

2960
01:50:11,010 --> 01:50:12,330
the Augustus from Primaporta,

2961
01:50:12,329 --> 01:50:14,489
which is in the Vatican today,

2962
01:50:14,489 --> 01:50:16,408
he's wearing a breastplate,

2963
01:50:16,409 --> 01:50:17,369
and on the breastplate,

2964
01:50:17,369 --> 01:50:18,839
right in the middle of the stomach,

2965
01:50:18,840 --> 01:50:21,509
is a Parthian handing over a golden eagle,

2966
01:50:21,510 --> 01:50:23,399
legionnaire's standard to a Roman.

2967
01:50:23,399 --> 01:50:24,739
So this is what Augustus thought of

2968
01:50:24,739 --> 01:50:26,699
as his greatest achievement.

2969
01:50:26,699 --> 01:50:29,399
And that embassy that arranged that

2970
01:50:29,399 --> 01:50:31,772
was the one that sent Musa to Parthia.

2971
01:50:32,640 --> 01:50:37,439
- So Augustus marks the start of the Roman Empire.

2972
01:50:37,439 --> 01:50:38,272
- Yep.

2973
01:50:38,273 --> 01:50:39,870
- You've written that Octavian Augustus

2974
01:50:39,869 --> 01:50:41,459
would become Rome's first emperor,

2975
01:50:41,460 --> 01:50:44,370
and the political system that he created

2976
01:50:44,369 --> 01:50:48,569
would endure for the next half a millennium.

2977
01:50:48,569 --> 01:50:50,519
This system would become the template

2978
01:50:50,520 --> 01:50:52,620
for countless later empires

2979
01:50:52,619 --> 01:50:54,209
up through the present day,

2980
01:50:54,210 --> 01:50:56,370
and he would become the model emperor

2981
01:50:56,369 --> 01:50:58,169
against whom all subsequent ones

2982
01:50:58,170 --> 01:50:59,399
would be measured.

2983
01:50:59,399 --> 01:51:02,008
The culture and history of the Mediterranean basin,

2984
01:51:02,010 --> 01:51:02,940
the western world,

2985
01:51:02,939 --> 01:51:04,948
and even global history itself

2986
01:51:04,949 --> 01:51:07,228
were all profoundly shaped and influenced

2987
01:51:07,229 --> 01:51:09,838
by the actions and legacy of Octavian.

2988
01:51:09,840 --> 01:51:12,150
He was the founder of the Roman Empire,

2989
01:51:12,149 --> 01:51:16,048
and we still live today in the world that he created.

2990
01:51:16,050 --> 01:51:19,770
So what, on the political side of things,

2991
01:51:19,770 --> 01:51:21,240
and maybe beyond,

2992
01:51:21,239 --> 01:51:24,089
what is the political system that he created?

2993
01:51:24,090 --> 01:51:27,033
- Well, I mean, I think Octavian/Augustus,

2994
01:51:27,033 --> 01:51:28,440
it's the same guy,

2995
01:51:28,439 --> 01:51:30,628
is one of the most influential people in the history

2996
01:51:30,630 --> 01:51:32,730
because he did found the Roman Empire.

2997
01:51:32,729 --> 01:51:34,709
So he's the one who oversaw this transition

2998
01:51:34,710 --> 01:51:35,939
from republic to empire.

2999
01:51:35,939 --> 01:51:37,229
And he sets the template,

3000
01:51:37,229 --> 01:51:39,959
which every future emperor follows.

3001
01:51:39,960 --> 01:51:41,520
So just in the most obvious way,

3002
01:51:41,520 --> 01:51:44,279
for the next either 500 or 1500 years,

3003
01:51:44,279 --> 01:51:47,669
depending on how long you think the Roman Empire lasted for,

3004
01:51:47,670 --> 01:51:49,230
everyone is trying to be Augustus.

3005
01:51:49,229 --> 01:51:51,329
They all take on the same titles.

3006
01:51:51,329 --> 01:51:54,974
Every Roman emperor after him is Caesar Augustus,

3007
01:51:54,975 --> 01:51:57,359
you know, imperator or pater patriae.

3008
01:51:57,359 --> 01:51:59,908
All these titles he has, they take too.

3009
01:51:59,909 --> 01:52:02,699
And so he's hugely influential

3010
01:52:02,699 --> 01:52:05,158
for Western civilization, all this.

3011
01:52:05,159 --> 01:52:07,649
But beyond just that literal thing,

3012
01:52:07,649 --> 01:52:10,198
which is already 500 years, 1500 years,

3013
01:52:10,199 --> 01:52:13,649
he becomes the paradigm of the good ruler.

3014
01:52:13,649 --> 01:52:17,249
So an absolute ruler who is nevertheless

3015
01:52:17,250 --> 01:52:20,040
sort of just does good things,

3016
01:52:20,039 --> 01:52:22,648
builds public works as popular.

3017
01:52:22,649 --> 01:52:25,919
So if we jump ahead, let's say, to the Middle Ages,

3018
01:52:25,920 --> 01:52:28,560
the most significant ruler of the early Middle Ages

3019
01:52:28,560 --> 01:52:29,670
is Charlemagne, right?

3020
01:52:29,670 --> 01:52:31,859
He's the guy who unites most of Europe.

3021
01:52:31,859 --> 01:52:35,309
He becomes the paradigm for all medieval kings after him.

3022
01:52:35,310 --> 01:52:39,209
Well, what is the title that the Pope gives to Charlemagne?

3023
01:52:39,210 --> 01:52:40,409
'Cause there's this famous moment

3024
01:52:40,409 --> 01:52:42,328
when the Pope acknowledges Charlemagne

3025
01:52:42,329 --> 01:52:44,338
as the preeminent European king

3026
01:52:44,340 --> 01:52:47,369
and crowns him on Christmas day of the year 800.

3027
01:52:47,369 --> 01:52:50,518
And the title that the Pope gives to Charlemagne

3028
01:52:50,520 --> 01:52:54,960
is Charles, that's Charlemagne, Augustus,

3029
01:52:54,960 --> 01:52:57,093
emperor of the Romans.

3030
01:52:58,319 --> 01:53:00,388
He's giving him the title of Augustus,

3031
01:53:00,390 --> 01:53:03,390
because that's the nicest thing he can think of

3032
01:53:03,390 --> 01:53:04,950
to say to Charlemagne

3033
01:53:04,949 --> 01:53:06,689
is to say, "You're the new Augustus,

3034
01:53:06,689 --> 01:53:08,098
you're emperor of the Romans."

3035
01:53:08,100 --> 01:53:08,1000
- Yeah.

3036
01:53:09,000 --> 01:53:11,669
- So that image is hugely powerful,

3037
01:53:11,670 --> 01:53:13,620
and that persists on and on.

3038
01:53:13,619 --> 01:53:17,849
I mean, even the literal names of most rulers afterwards

3039
01:53:17,850 --> 01:53:18,840
come from this.

3040
01:53:18,840 --> 01:53:22,560
In Russia, the Czars are Caesars.

3041
01:53:22,560 --> 01:53:24,153
That's where Czar comes from.

3042
01:53:25,140 --> 01:53:26,1000
Prince comes from princeps,

3043
01:53:27,000 --> 01:53:29,069
first citizen, one of the titles.

3044
01:53:29,069 --> 01:53:31,109
Emperor comes from Imperator,

3045
01:53:31,109 --> 01:53:33,298
one of the titles of Augustus.

3046
01:53:33,300 --> 01:53:35,670
When Napoleon becomes emperor,

3047
01:53:35,670 --> 01:53:36,720
what does he call himself?

3048
01:53:36,720 --> 01:53:39,240
First Consul, which is kind of like princeps.

3049
01:53:39,239 --> 01:53:41,102
And then he calls himself emperor.

3050
01:53:42,362 --> 01:53:45,629
I mean, everybody wants to be this kind of ruler.

3051
01:53:45,630 --> 01:53:48,506
So he's the paradigm of this for the rest of history.

3052
01:53:48,506 --> 01:53:51,119
And you can see that as both a positive

3053
01:53:51,119 --> 01:53:52,498
and a negative legacy.

3054
01:53:52,500 --> 01:53:53,909
It's kinda like Alexander.

3055
01:53:53,909 --> 01:53:56,458
I mean, everybody wants to be the next Alexander.

3056
01:53:56,460 --> 01:53:59,100
Now, nobody does become the next Alexander.

3057
01:53:59,100 --> 01:54:00,390
Nobody's as successful as him,

3058
01:54:00,390 --> 01:54:02,250
but a lot of people try.

3059
01:54:02,250 --> 01:54:03,570
And you can see that either as,

3060
01:54:03,569 --> 01:54:06,209
oh, inspirational or awful,

3061
01:54:06,210 --> 01:54:09,600
because lots of people killed lots of other people

3062
01:54:09,600 --> 01:54:11,400
and started lots of wars

3063
01:54:11,399 --> 01:54:13,262
trying to be the next Alexander.

3064
01:54:14,399 --> 01:54:17,879
At least Augustus has this notion of good rulership.

3065
01:54:17,880 --> 01:54:20,279
That you're not just a great powerful person,

3066
01:54:20,279 --> 01:54:23,279
but you're a good ruler somehow.

3067
01:54:23,279 --> 01:54:25,649
- Can you speak to the kind of political system he created?

3068
01:54:25,649 --> 01:54:30,649
So how did he consolidate power

3069
01:54:30,659 --> 01:54:32,728
as you spoke to a bit already,

3070
01:54:32,729 --> 01:54:35,849
and what role did the Senate now play?

3071
01:54:35,850 --> 01:54:38,609
How were the laws,

3072
01:54:38,609 --> 01:54:39,689
who was the executive,

3073
01:54:39,689 --> 01:54:41,968
how was power allocated, and so on?

3074
01:54:41,970 --> 01:54:44,729
- Yeah, so once the empire begins,

3075
01:54:44,729 --> 01:54:46,108
let's say, 27 BC,

3076
01:54:46,109 --> 01:54:48,988
so in 31 BC,

3077
01:54:48,989 --> 01:54:52,198
Octavian defeats Antony at the Battle of Actium.

3078
01:54:52,199 --> 01:54:54,493
So that's kind of the moment he becomes the sole ruler.

3079
01:54:54,494 --> 01:54:57,059
And then in 27 BC, a couple years later,

3080
01:54:57,060 --> 01:54:58,877
he settles the Roman Republic,

3081
01:54:58,877 --> 01:55:00,060
is how it's referred to,

3082
01:55:00,060 --> 01:55:02,280
which basically sets up his system.

3083
01:55:02,279 --> 01:55:03,749
And in this system,

3084
01:55:03,750 --> 01:55:07,049
on the surface, it all looks the same.

3085
01:55:07,050 --> 01:55:08,640
You still have a Senate,

3086
01:55:08,640 --> 01:55:10,500
each year, there's elections,

3087
01:55:10,500 --> 01:55:11,970
all the Roman systems vote,

3088
01:55:11,970 --> 01:55:13,230
they elect magistrates

3089
01:55:13,229 --> 01:55:15,988
who, notionally, are in charge of Rome.

3090
01:55:15,989 --> 01:55:18,509
But as I mentioned, off to the side,

3091
01:55:18,510 --> 01:55:20,519
you now have this figure of Augustus

3092
01:55:20,520 --> 01:55:23,640
who sort of controls everything behind the scenes.

3093
01:55:23,640 --> 01:55:25,500
And that continues.

3094
01:55:25,500 --> 01:55:28,560
So this political system he establishes continues.

3095
01:55:28,560 --> 01:55:31,919
And in reality, I would say Augustus,

3096
01:55:31,920 --> 01:55:33,839
at that point, is, again, a king.

3097
01:55:33,840 --> 01:55:37,199
It really is one man controlling the state

3098
01:55:37,199 --> 01:55:41,279
even if, notionally, it's still continuing as a republic.

3099
01:55:41,279 --> 01:55:42,928
They are electing magistrates,

3100
01:55:42,930 --> 01:55:44,280
but the magistrates only do

3101
01:55:44,279 --> 01:55:47,009
what the emperor tells them, right?

3102
01:55:47,010 --> 01:55:49,829
But it's this sort of formal versus informal power.

3103
01:55:49,829 --> 01:55:51,958
The formal structure is a republic,

3104
01:55:51,960 --> 01:55:54,660
the way things really work informally

3105
01:55:54,659 --> 01:55:56,489
is it's a monarchy.

3106
01:55:56,489 --> 01:55:59,189
Now, if you asked Augustus, what did he do?

3107
01:55:59,189 --> 01:56:00,719
Did you become a king?

3108
01:56:00,720 --> 01:56:02,437
He said, and he says this explicitly,

3109
01:56:02,436 --> 01:56:03,508
"No, no, no.

3110
01:56:03,510 --> 01:56:08,279
What I did is I refounded the Roman Republic."

3111
01:56:08,279 --> 01:56:09,369
That's how he phrases it.

3112
01:56:09,369 --> 01:56:11,788
- Yeah, this guy is good at framing.

3113
01:56:11,789 --> 01:56:13,319
- He's so good at propaganda.

3114
01:56:13,319 --> 01:56:15,149
I'll give you one more example that I love.

3115
01:56:15,149 --> 01:56:17,729
Augustus actually writes his own autobiography,

3116
01:56:17,729 --> 01:56:19,289
which is very rare, and survives.

3117
01:56:19,289 --> 01:56:21,119
So here we have the autobiography

3118
01:56:21,119 --> 01:56:22,979
of one of the pivotal figures in history.

3119
01:56:22,979 --> 01:56:25,349
And if you had conquered the world, let's say,

3120
01:56:25,350 --> 01:56:27,990
starting at the age of 18,

3121
01:56:27,989 --> 01:56:29,729
what would you call your autobiography?

3122
01:56:29,729 --> 01:56:30,562
It'd be something like, you know,

3123
01:56:30,563 --> 01:56:32,520
"How I Conquered The World," right?

3124
01:56:32,520 --> 01:56:35,910
Augustus calls his the "Res Gestae,"

3125
01:56:35,909 --> 01:56:40,319
which the best sort of literal translation is "stuff I did."

3126
01:56:40,319 --> 01:56:42,119
I mean, it's the most modest title

3127
01:56:42,119 --> 01:56:45,389
for someone who could have given the most grandiose title.

3128
01:56:45,390 --> 01:56:47,397
And the first line of it is, you know,

3129
01:56:47,396 --> 01:56:48,779
"At the age of 18,

3130
01:56:48,779 --> 01:56:50,939
when the liberty of the Republic

3131
01:56:50,939 --> 01:56:53,159
was oppressed by a faction,

3132
01:56:53,159 --> 01:56:55,078
I defended it."

3133
01:56:55,079 --> 01:56:57,296
Now, the way I might phrase that sense is,

3134
01:56:57,296 --> 01:56:58,439
"At the age of 18,

3135
01:56:58,439 --> 01:57:00,689
I fought a civil war against another Roman

3136
01:57:00,689 --> 01:57:02,489
and conquered the Roman state."

3137
01:57:02,489 --> 01:57:05,009
But no, he defended the liberty of the Republic

3138
01:57:05,010 --> 01:57:08,010
when it was oppressed by the tyranny of a faction.

3139
01:57:08,010 --> 01:57:11,099
That's propaganda. And it works.

3140
01:57:11,100 --> 01:57:12,420
- It is propaganda,

3141
01:57:12,420 --> 01:57:15,870
but is there a degree to which he also lived it,

3142
01:57:15,869 --> 01:57:18,179
that kind of humility?

3143
01:57:18,180 --> 01:57:19,500
Establishing that humility

3144
01:57:19,500 --> 01:57:22,080
is a standard of the way government operates.

3145
01:57:22,079 --> 01:57:23,099
So it's not an,

3146
01:57:23,100 --> 01:57:25,709
like a literal direct balance of power,

3147
01:57:25,710 --> 01:57:28,049
but it's sort of a cultural balance of power,

3148
01:57:28,050 --> 01:57:29,699
where the emperor is not supposed to be

3149
01:57:29,699 --> 01:57:31,319
a bully and a dictator.

3150
01:57:31,319 --> 01:57:33,598
- I would really like to know

3151
01:57:33,600 --> 01:57:36,180
what Romans of his time thought.

3152
01:57:36,180 --> 01:57:38,670
Like if you were alive at that moment,

3153
01:57:38,670 --> 01:57:41,137
would you honestly believe,

3154
01:57:41,136 --> 01:57:43,469
"Oh, okay, we've got this guy Augustus,

3155
01:57:43,470 --> 01:57:44,430
but he's brought peace,

3156
01:57:44,430 --> 01:57:46,232
he's just kind of keeping in charge for a while

3157
01:57:46,233 --> 01:57:47,489
'til things settle down.

3158
01:57:47,489 --> 01:57:49,589
We've just had a hundred years of civil war.

3159
01:57:49,590 --> 01:57:51,390
I think we still have a republic.

3160
01:57:51,390 --> 01:57:54,300
Or would you say, "Nah, we have a king now."

3161
01:57:54,300 --> 01:57:56,460
And I don't know what the answer to that is.

3162
01:57:56,460 --> 01:58:00,780
I will tell you that it takes 200 years

3163
01:58:00,779 --> 01:58:03,868
before we have the first Roman source

3164
01:58:03,869 --> 01:58:07,460
that bluntly calls Augustus a king.

3165
01:58:07,461 --> 01:58:08,670
So 200 years,

3166
01:58:08,670 --> 01:58:11,1000
it takes the Romans 200 years to admit to themselves.

3167
01:58:12,000 --> 01:58:15,757
And that's a guy who comes along 200 years later and says,

3168
01:58:15,756 --> 01:58:18,719
"Hey, Augustus, he looks like a king,

3169
01:58:18,720 --> 01:58:19,859
he acts like a king,

3170
01:58:19,859 --> 01:58:21,209
let's just call him a king,

3171
01:58:21,210 --> 01:58:23,489
because he had every aspect of a king

3172
01:58:23,489 --> 01:58:25,349
except the poultry title."

3173
01:58:25,350 --> 01:58:26,850
- Maybe I'm buying his propaganda,

3174
01:58:26,850 --> 01:58:28,440
and maybe I'm a sucker for humility,

3175
01:58:28,439 --> 01:58:31,619
but I suspect that the Romans bought it.

3176
01:58:31,619 --> 01:58:35,128
And I also suspect he himself believed it.

3177
01:58:35,130 --> 01:58:38,820
I mean, there is such thing as good kings, right?

3178
01:58:38,819 --> 01:58:42,868
There's kings that understand the downside,

3179
01:58:42,869 --> 01:58:45,151
the dark side of absolute power,

3180
01:58:46,020 --> 01:58:48,089
and can wield that power properly.

3181
01:58:48,090 --> 01:58:50,099
- And, you know, to give sort of both sides here,

3182
01:58:50,100 --> 01:58:51,420
Augustus wasn't all nice.

3183
01:58:51,420 --> 01:58:54,089
I mean, there were moments where he was extremely cruel.

3184
01:58:54,090 --> 01:58:55,350
So early in his career,

3185
01:58:55,350 --> 01:58:57,629
when he's still fighting for power,

3186
01:58:57,630 --> 01:59:00,120
he goes all in on proscriptions,

3187
01:59:00,119 --> 01:59:02,998
which is where he and Antony and other people

3188
01:59:03,000 --> 01:59:06,396
basically post lists of their enemies and say,

3189
01:59:06,396 --> 01:59:09,448
"It's legal for anyone to kill these people."

3190
01:59:09,449 --> 01:59:11,249
And so hundreds are massacred there,

3191
01:59:11,250 --> 01:59:13,740
including Cicero, the great orator,

3192
01:59:13,739 --> 01:59:15,569
is proscribed and killed.

3193
01:59:15,569 --> 01:59:16,889
There's moments when he is really cruel.

3194
01:59:16,890 --> 01:59:18,480
One slave once gets him angry

3195
01:59:18,479 --> 01:59:19,829
and he has him tortured

3196
01:59:19,829 --> 01:59:21,599
in particularly sort of cruel manner.

3197
01:59:21,600 --> 01:59:23,190
So, I mean, on the one hand,

3198
01:59:23,189 --> 01:59:24,209
he had this clemency,

3199
01:59:24,210 --> 01:59:25,043
on the other hand,

3200
01:59:25,042 --> 01:59:26,879
he could be really hard-nosed

3201
01:59:26,880 --> 01:59:27,713
and hard-edged.

3202
01:59:27,712 --> 01:59:29,759
And I think he was a very calculating person.

3203
01:59:29,760 --> 01:59:32,309
- Yeah. So the thing I would love to know

3204
01:59:32,310 --> 01:59:36,060
is what he was actually like behind the mask.

3205
01:59:36,060 --> 01:59:36,893
- Yes. Yes, I mean,

3206
01:59:36,893 --> 01:59:37,949
that to me is one of those, you know,

3207
01:59:37,949 --> 01:59:39,749
like if you could invite a historical person

3208
01:59:39,750 --> 01:59:40,919
to dinner or whatever,

3209
01:59:40,920 --> 01:59:42,750
I wanna know what the real Augustus was,

3210
01:59:42,750 --> 01:59:44,129
what he really thought he was doing,

3211
01:59:44,130 --> 01:59:45,543
'cause he's an enigma.

3212
01:59:46,409 --> 01:59:48,779
And he has this great moment when he dies, right?

3213
01:59:48,779 --> 01:59:51,448
What's his dying lines on his deathbed?

3214
01:59:51,449 --> 01:59:54,598
He says, "If I've played my part well,

3215
01:59:54,600 --> 01:59:57,180
dismiss me from the stage with applause."

3216
01:59:57,180 --> 01:59:59,789
So he's seeing himself as an actor.

3217
01:59:59,789 --> 02:00:02,699
That his whole life was acting this role.

3218
02:00:02,699 --> 02:00:05,609
Which is, again, all that manipulation and public image,

3219
02:00:05,609 --> 02:00:06,778
he was brilliant at that,

3220
02:00:06,779 --> 02:00:08,309
but who's the real guy?

3221
02:00:08,310 --> 02:00:09,780
What was behind that image?

3222
02:00:09,779 --> 02:00:10,712
- And by the way,

3223
02:00:11,640 --> 02:00:13,769
as long as we're talking about brutality,

3224
02:00:13,770 --> 02:00:17,549
I think you've mentioned in a few places that

3225
02:00:17,550 --> 02:00:20,429
there's a lot of brutality going on at the time,

3226
02:00:20,430 --> 02:00:23,309
with Caesar just killing

3227
02:00:23,310 --> 02:00:28,310
very large numbers of people brutally.

3228
02:00:28,649 --> 02:00:30,028
- I mean, Caesar,

3229
02:00:30,029 --> 02:00:32,308
his campaigns in Gaul are interesting

3230
02:00:32,310 --> 02:00:34,319
because, for a long time,

3231
02:00:34,319 --> 02:00:37,049
they were held up as, oh, genius general,

3232
02:00:37,050 --> 02:00:38,429
look at the amazing things he did.

3233
02:00:38,430 --> 02:00:41,099
But another way to view it is he provoked,

3234
02:00:41,100 --> 02:00:43,140
and he truly provoked a war with people

3235
02:00:43,140 --> 02:00:45,329
who were not that interested in fighting Rome

3236
02:00:45,329 --> 02:00:48,059
and just repeatedly attacked different tribes

3237
02:00:48,060 --> 02:00:52,649
for the sole purpose of building up his career,

3238
02:00:52,649 --> 02:00:54,928
his prestige, his status,

3239
02:00:54,930 --> 02:00:55,860
gaining territory,

3240
02:00:55,859 --> 02:00:57,629
making himself wealthier.

3241
02:00:57,630 --> 02:01:00,960
And he basically conquers all of modern France

3242
02:01:00,960 --> 02:01:02,670
and Belgium and some of Switzerland.

3243
02:01:02,670 --> 02:01:06,870
So this is, you know, a big chunk of Europe gets conquered.

3244
02:01:06,869 --> 02:01:08,518
Hundreds of thousands of people killed,

3245
02:01:08,520 --> 02:01:10,409
hundreds of thousands of people enslaved

3246
02:01:10,409 --> 02:01:12,449
to further one guy's career.

3247
02:01:12,449 --> 02:01:14,098
I mean, you, if you wanted,

3248
02:01:14,100 --> 02:01:16,200
could call Caesar a war criminal,

3249
02:01:16,199 --> 02:01:18,602
and I think that wouldn't be unfair.

3250
02:01:19,649 --> 02:01:20,549
But on the other hand,

3251
02:01:20,550 --> 02:01:22,980
some people see him as a great hero.

3252
02:01:22,979 --> 02:01:25,438
I mean, to talk about history and its reception,

3253
02:01:25,439 --> 02:01:29,129
it's quite interesting to see how Caesar has been viewed

3254
02:01:29,130 --> 02:01:31,199
by different generations.

3255
02:01:31,199 --> 02:01:33,029
So at different points in time,

3256
02:01:33,029 --> 02:01:34,079
the sort of, you know,

3257
02:01:34,079 --> 02:01:37,108
received wisdom on Caesar is very different.

3258
02:01:37,109 --> 02:01:40,559
So back in the, you know, let's say the 1920s or '30s,

3259
02:01:40,560 --> 02:01:42,540
there were a number of scholarly things written,

3260
02:01:42,539 --> 02:01:47,069
which kind of looked at Caesar as an admirable figure.

3261
02:01:47,069 --> 02:01:49,678
He's a strong man who knows what Rome needed

3262
02:01:49,680 --> 02:01:51,747
and, you know, was going to give it to them.

3263
02:01:51,747 --> 02:01:53,400
And of course, that's the era

3264
02:01:53,399 --> 02:01:55,379
when Fascism was kind of trendy

3265
02:01:55,380 --> 02:01:57,120
and was seen as a positive thing.

3266
02:01:57,119 --> 02:01:58,451
And then you get, you know, Hitler and World War II

3267
02:01:58,453 --> 02:02:02,310
and all of a sudden, Fascism is not so favored anymore.

3268
02:02:02,310 --> 02:02:03,870
And then in that post-war generation,

3269
02:02:03,869 --> 02:02:05,159
all of a sudden, Caesar is terrible.

3270
02:02:05,159 --> 02:02:06,409
You know, he's a dictator.

3271
02:02:06,409 --> 02:02:08,338
He is destroying the republic.

3272
02:02:08,340 --> 02:02:10,619
So it, you know, often,

3273
02:02:10,619 --> 02:02:11,818
histories that are written

3274
02:02:11,819 --> 02:02:14,158
tell you a lot more about the time they're written

3275
02:02:14,159 --> 02:02:17,069
than they do about the subject they're written about.

3276
02:02:17,069 --> 02:02:19,979
- Do we know, what did Hitler

3277
02:02:19,979 --> 02:02:22,318
or Stalin think about the Roman Empire?

3278
02:02:22,319 --> 02:02:25,109
- I mean, certainly, they borrow a lot of the trappings.

3279
02:02:25,109 --> 02:02:26,998
I mean, you know, Nazi Germany

3280
02:02:27,000 --> 02:02:29,819
borrows a lot of iconography from Ancient Rome.

3281
02:02:29,819 --> 02:02:31,319
You know, I mean, they carried around

3282
02:02:31,319 --> 02:02:33,658
little military standards with eagles on them

3283
02:02:33,659 --> 02:02:35,548
just like the Romans.

3284
02:02:35,550 --> 02:02:36,383
But then everybody does that.

3285
02:02:36,382 --> 02:02:38,849
I mean, the US has eagles as their standards.

3286
02:02:38,850 --> 02:02:39,989
Mussolini had them.

3287
02:02:39,989 --> 02:02:44,969
Napoleon had eagle standards for his, you know, military.

3288
02:02:44,970 --> 02:02:47,913
So a lot of people like that imagery.

3289
02:02:48,989 --> 02:02:50,128
- You mentioned Cicero.

3290
02:02:50,130 --> 02:02:51,509
He's a fascinating figure.

3291
02:02:51,510 --> 02:02:54,059
On the topic of Roman oratory,

3292
02:02:54,060 --> 02:02:55,053
who is Cicero?

3293
02:02:56,159 --> 02:02:58,319
- Cicero was a new man.

3294
02:02:58,319 --> 02:03:01,468
So he's someone who didn't have famous ancestors.

3295
02:03:01,470 --> 02:03:03,389
So he was at a disadvantage.

3296
02:03:03,390 --> 02:03:06,240
And I think Cicero is really interesting

3297
02:03:06,239 --> 02:03:07,079
for a couple reasons.

3298
02:03:07,079 --> 02:03:09,869
One is he wrote an incredible amount.

3299
02:03:09,869 --> 02:03:12,029
I think we have almost more words from Cicero

3300
02:03:12,029 --> 02:03:13,829
than any other author that survive.

3301
02:03:13,829 --> 02:03:14,998
And it's all kinds of stuff.

3302
02:03:15,000 --> 02:03:16,620
It's philosophical treatises,

3303
02:03:16,619 --> 02:03:18,958
it's books about how to be a good public speaker.

3304
02:03:18,960 --> 02:03:21,960
He published, you know, volume after volume

3305
02:03:21,960 --> 02:03:24,060
of his personal letters to his friends.

3306
02:03:24,060 --> 02:03:26,140
He published these things.

3307
02:03:26,140 --> 02:03:28,229
So there's tons of stuff from him.

3308
02:03:28,229 --> 02:03:31,528
And secondly, he's interesting because he lived at this

3309
02:03:31,529 --> 02:03:33,868
incredibly important time in the late Republic

3310
02:03:33,869 --> 02:03:35,938
when things were falling apart.

3311
02:03:35,939 --> 02:03:37,378
But he seems to have been born

3312
02:03:37,380 --> 02:03:39,389
with none of the natural advantages

3313
02:03:39,390 --> 02:03:41,100
that all these other people had.

3314
02:03:41,100 --> 02:03:43,680
So he was a lousy general,

3315
02:03:43,680 --> 02:03:45,749
he didn't come from a wealthy family,

3316
02:03:45,750 --> 02:03:48,573
he didn't come from a famous aristocratic family,

3317
02:03:49,500 --> 02:03:51,689
you know, he didn't have a lot of these advantages,

3318
02:03:51,689 --> 02:03:54,568
but yet he ended up being right at the center of things,

3319
02:03:54,569 --> 02:03:57,539
rose to the highest elected office in the Roman state

3320
02:03:57,539 --> 02:03:59,579
on the basis of one skill,

3321
02:03:59,579 --> 02:04:01,858
and that was his ability with words.

3322
02:04:01,859 --> 02:04:04,258
His ability to get up in front of a crowd

3323
02:04:04,260 --> 02:04:07,889
and persuade them of what he wanted them to believe.

3324
02:04:07,890 --> 02:04:09,720
And oratory, public speaking,

3325
02:04:09,720 --> 02:04:13,170
was absolutely central to life at Rome.

3326
02:04:13,170 --> 02:04:14,520
There were just all these events

3327
02:04:14,520 --> 02:04:17,729
where people had to get up and give speeches.

3328
02:04:17,729 --> 02:04:20,159
So in courtrooms, at funerals,

3329
02:04:20,159 --> 02:04:21,749
you know, in the Senate,

3330
02:04:21,750 --> 02:04:24,750
to the people of Rome, at games.

3331
02:04:24,750 --> 02:04:25,710
I mean, just constantly,

3332
02:04:25,710 --> 02:04:27,870
there were these opportunities for giving speeches.

3333
02:04:27,869 --> 02:04:29,548
So if you are good at this,

3334
02:04:29,550 --> 02:04:33,780
that was a huge advantage in your political career.

3335
02:04:33,779 --> 02:04:35,759
And Cicero was the best.

3336
02:04:35,760 --> 02:04:40,170
He was, arguably, the best public speaker of all time,

3337
02:04:40,170 --> 02:04:41,103
some people claim.

3338
02:04:42,390 --> 02:04:43,890
And he lived right in this era,

3339
02:04:43,890 --> 02:04:45,930
and he parlayed that skill with words

3340
02:04:45,930 --> 02:04:48,059
into this very successful political career.

3341
02:04:48,060 --> 02:04:49,499
He was one of the guys involved

3342
02:04:49,500 --> 02:04:51,330
with all this stuff with Caesar and Pompey

3343
02:04:51,329 --> 02:04:52,679
and all the other things going on.

3344
02:04:52,680 --> 02:04:54,359
Octavian and Mark Antony.

3345
02:04:54,359 --> 02:04:57,118
- And you've written, which is fascinating.

3346
02:04:57,119 --> 02:04:59,969
It's fascinating when the echoes of people

3347
02:04:59,970 --> 02:05:03,444
from a distant past are seen today.

3348
02:05:03,444 --> 02:05:04,647
The same stuff is seen today.

3349
02:05:04,646 --> 02:05:07,589
Not just like some of the beautiful legal stuff

3350
02:05:07,590 --> 02:05:08,460
that we've been talking about,

3351
02:05:08,460 --> 02:05:09,903
but the tricks,

3352
02:05:10,944 --> 02:05:12,718
the, you know, let's say,

3353
02:05:12,720 --> 02:05:14,369
the shitty stuff we see in politics.

3354
02:05:14,369 --> 02:05:17,429
So many of the rhetorical tricks you wrote,

3355
02:05:17,430 --> 02:05:19,559
such as mud slinging, exaggeration,

3356
02:05:19,560 --> 02:05:21,689
guilt by association, ad hominem attacks,

3357
02:05:21,689 --> 02:05:23,159
name calling, fear mongering,

3358
02:05:23,159 --> 02:05:25,379
us versus them, rhyme, and so on and so forth.

3359
02:05:25,380 --> 02:05:27,330
So I'm guessing it worked

3360
02:05:27,329 --> 02:05:28,738
given that we still have those today?

3361
02:05:28,739 --> 02:05:30,599
- Yeah, I mean, one of the things Cicero did

3362
02:05:30,600 --> 02:05:33,899
is he wrote at least three of these sort of handbooks

3363
02:05:33,899 --> 02:05:35,489
about how to be a good public speaker.

3364
02:05:35,489 --> 02:05:37,408
So we know a lot about that,

3365
02:05:37,409 --> 02:05:39,298
we have his own speeches that survive,

3366
02:05:39,300 --> 02:05:41,280
and then we have later people after Cicero

3367
02:05:41,279 --> 02:05:42,599
who wrote about what Cicero did too.

3368
02:05:42,600 --> 02:05:45,030
So we know a lot about what he did.

3369
02:05:45,029 --> 02:05:49,288
And the key to Cicero's whole enterprise

3370
02:05:49,289 --> 02:05:50,579
about persuading an audience,

3371
02:05:50,579 --> 02:05:52,978
let's say either in a speech to the people

3372
02:05:52,979 --> 02:05:54,599
or in the courtroom,

3373
02:05:54,600 --> 02:05:56,400
is Cicero believed that people

3374
02:05:56,399 --> 02:05:58,802
are fundamentally ruled by emotion.

3375
02:05:59,789 --> 02:06:02,729
So if you can touch their emotions,

3376
02:06:02,729 --> 02:06:06,119
all sorts of other things become less important.

3377
02:06:06,119 --> 02:06:09,239
If you can get a jury emotionally worked up,

3378
02:06:09,239 --> 02:06:12,929
and fear, anger are particularly powerful there,

3379
02:06:12,930 --> 02:06:15,329
then the facts might not matter,

3380
02:06:15,329 --> 02:06:17,099
the truth might not matter,

3381
02:06:17,100 --> 02:06:19,620
evidence might not matter,

3382
02:06:19,619 --> 02:06:21,569
reason might not matter.

3383
02:06:21,569 --> 02:06:24,209
Emotion is the key to everything.

3384
02:06:24,210 --> 02:06:29,040
So Cicero used what I would arguably call a lot of tricks

3385
02:06:29,039 --> 02:06:32,309
to get his audiences emotionally riled up.

3386
02:06:32,310 --> 02:06:33,870
And you can just go through these,

3387
02:06:33,869 --> 02:06:34,979
and they're all the stuff you were saying.

3388
02:06:34,979 --> 02:06:37,289
You know, name calling,

3389
02:06:37,289 --> 02:06:39,029
you know, mud slinging,

3390
02:06:39,029 --> 02:06:41,459
us versus them arguments,

3391
02:06:41,460 --> 02:06:44,069
you know, ad hominem attacks.

3392
02:06:44,069 --> 02:06:45,718
I mean, incredibly sophisticated.

