3650
02:15:56,850 --> 02:15:59,220
evil, really, purposes.

3651
02:15:59,220 --> 02:16:00,053
But oratory is like that.

3652
02:16:00,052 --> 02:16:01,828
You know, it's...

3653
02:16:01,829 --> 02:16:04,199
The question I always end up asking my students is,

3654
02:16:04,199 --> 02:16:06,449
after studying Cicero and all these techniques,

3655
02:16:06,449 --> 02:16:08,879
I say, "Okay, this is great oratory,

3656
02:16:08,880 --> 02:16:10,230
but do you like this?

3657
02:16:10,229 --> 02:16:13,469
Is this good that this works on human beings?"

3658
02:16:13,470 --> 02:16:16,236
- I remember Noam Chomsky once was asked,

3659
02:16:16,237 --> 02:16:17,787
"Why do you speak in such a monotone way?"

3660
02:16:17,787 --> 02:16:22,200
And he said, "Well, I want the truth of my statement,

3661
02:16:22,199 --> 02:16:24,208
the contents of my statements to speak,

3662
02:16:24,210 --> 02:16:27,960
that I don't want you to get diluted by me

3663
02:16:27,960 --> 02:16:31,319
because I'm such a charismatic and eloquent speaker.

3664
02:16:31,319 --> 02:16:32,609
The more monotone I speak,

3665
02:16:32,610 --> 02:16:34,499
the more you will listen to the content of the words."

3666
02:16:34,500 --> 02:16:36,629
- Right, I want you just focusing on the content

3667
02:16:36,629 --> 02:16:38,219
and not being distracted.

3668
02:16:38,219 --> 02:16:39,779
I'll tell you also, with Cicero,

3669
02:16:39,780 --> 02:16:42,720
one of the things that he and other people

3670
02:16:42,719 --> 02:16:44,795
who write about Roman oratory do is to say,

3671
02:16:44,797 --> 02:16:46,860
"And you can do this stuff badly,

3672
02:16:46,860 --> 02:16:49,619
in which case it backfires horribly."

3673
02:16:49,620 --> 02:16:52,140
So you can have people who attempt to gesticulate,

3674
02:16:52,139 --> 02:16:54,449
and again, modern politicians, you'll see this sometime

3675
02:16:54,450 --> 02:16:55,283
where they feel like

3676
02:16:55,282 --> 02:16:57,389
"I'm supposed to be making hand gestures,"

3677
02:16:57,389 --> 02:16:58,236
and they're terrible at it-

3678
02:16:58,236 --> 02:17:00,509
- Yeah. - and it undercuts it.

3679
02:17:00,510 --> 02:17:01,870
And Cicero and Quintilian

3680
02:17:01,870 --> 02:17:04,649
gives some very amusing examples from Ancient Rome.

3681
02:17:04,649 --> 02:17:06,629
So like he says there was this one guy,

3682
02:17:06,629 --> 02:17:07,462
who, when he spoke,

3683
02:17:07,462 --> 02:17:10,079
looked like he was trying to swat away flies, you know,

3684
02:17:10,079 --> 02:17:11,968
'cause there were just these awkward gestures,

3685
02:17:11,969 --> 02:17:12,929
or another who looked like

3686
02:17:12,930 --> 02:17:14,609
he was trying to balance in a boat,

3687
02:17:14,610 --> 02:17:17,219
like in, you know, choppy seas.

3688
02:17:17,219 --> 02:17:19,288
And my favorite is there was one orator

3689
02:17:19,290 --> 02:17:21,720
who supposedly was prone to making,

3690
02:17:21,719 --> 02:17:24,989
I guess, kind of languid supple motions.

3691
02:17:24,989 --> 02:17:28,739
And so they actually named a dance after this guy.

3692
02:17:28,739 --> 02:17:30,607
And his name was Titius.

3693
02:17:30,608 --> 02:17:32,910
And so Romans could do the Titius,

3694
02:17:32,909 --> 02:17:35,969
which is this dance that was imitating this orator

3695
02:17:35,969 --> 02:17:36,869
who had these, you know,

3696
02:17:36,870 --> 02:17:40,560
kind of comically bad gesticulation.

3697
02:17:40,559 --> 02:17:43,438
So not enough gesticulation is a problem.

3698
02:17:43,440 --> 02:17:45,719
Too much gesticulation is a problem.

3699
02:17:45,719 --> 02:17:47,398
You have to hit the sweet spot.

3700
02:17:47,399 --> 02:17:50,519
It has to seem natural, it has to seem varied.

3701
02:17:50,520 --> 02:17:52,916
It has to conform to the meaning of the words

3702
02:17:52,916 --> 02:17:54,389
and not distract from it.

3703
02:17:54,389 --> 02:17:55,469
- Yeah, natural to your,

3704
02:17:55,469 --> 02:17:57,062
like authentic to who you are- - Yeah, authentic.

3705
02:17:57,063 --> 02:17:59,220
- which is when people try to copy

3706
02:17:59,219 --> 02:18:00,839
the gesture of another person,

3707
02:18:00,840 --> 02:18:02,100
it usually doesn't go well.

3708
02:18:02,100 --> 02:18:03,600
- Right. - You have to kind of,

3709
02:18:03,600 --> 02:18:04,739
yeah, you have to interpret,

3710
02:18:04,739 --> 02:18:06,806
integrate into your own personality and so on.

3711
02:18:06,807 --> 02:18:08,640
- But gestures is really fun.

3712
02:18:08,639 --> 02:18:09,778
- It's fascinating.

3713
02:18:09,780 --> 02:18:13,799
- I enjoyed my dissertation a lot doing that.

3714
02:18:13,799 --> 02:18:14,639
'Cause what I was trying to do there

3715
02:18:14,639 --> 02:18:16,799
was to literally reconstruct them, so to say.

3716
02:18:16,799 --> 02:18:18,258
What were the actual gestures?

3717
02:18:18,259 --> 02:18:20,009
And I did that by comparing

3718
02:18:20,010 --> 02:18:21,630
the literary accounts of the handbooks

3719
02:18:21,629 --> 02:18:22,828
with, again, Roman art.

3720
02:18:22,829 --> 02:18:24,838
Looking at statues of Romans and things,

3721
02:18:24,840 --> 02:18:26,219
and just trying to say, "Okay,

3722
02:18:26,219 --> 02:18:28,558
what were some of the gestures they actually used here?"

3723
02:18:28,559 --> 02:18:31,205
- And in that way,

3724
02:18:31,207 --> 02:18:32,999
the people from that time come to life

3725
02:18:33,000 --> 02:18:34,439
in your mind, in your work,

3726
02:18:34,440 --> 02:18:35,530
which is this fascinating.

3727
02:18:35,531 --> 02:18:36,625
- Well, again, this pragmatic thing.

3728
02:18:36,626 --> 02:18:38,453
I want to know, okay, how does this work?

3729
02:18:39,989 --> 02:18:43,239
- Could we talk about the role of religion

3730
02:18:44,250 --> 02:18:45,813
in the Roman Empire?

3731
02:18:46,889 --> 02:18:48,122
What's the story there?

3732
02:18:49,200 --> 02:18:50,339
- I mean, religion is interesting

3733
02:18:50,340 --> 02:18:53,219
because, in my mind,

3734
02:18:53,219 --> 02:18:58,079
the rise to dominance in a lot of the world

3735
02:18:58,079 --> 02:18:59,728
of monotheistic religions

3736
02:18:59,729 --> 02:19:02,699
is one of the huge sort of turning points,

3737
02:19:02,700 --> 02:19:05,099
'cause it's just such a different mentality.

3738
02:19:05,100 --> 02:19:08,257
I mean, it's very, very different where you say,

3739
02:19:08,256 --> 02:19:10,978
"There's one God, and it's my God,"

3740
02:19:10,979 --> 02:19:13,168
versus, "Okay, I believe in this God,

3741
02:19:13,170 --> 02:19:16,379
but there's an infinite number of legitimate gods."

3742
02:19:16,379 --> 02:19:18,388
And nowadays, particularly in the West,

3743
02:19:18,389 --> 02:19:22,922
we tend to view the monotheistic perspective as the norm.

3744
02:19:23,819 --> 02:19:24,958
But for, you know,

3745
02:19:24,959 --> 02:19:26,429
more than half of human history,

3746
02:19:26,430 --> 02:19:28,107
it was not.

3747
02:19:28,106 --> 02:19:31,679
You know, it used to be the notion in a lot of Roman history

3748
02:19:31,680 --> 02:19:34,349
up until about 300 AD.

3749
02:19:34,350 --> 02:19:35,640
The idea was, well,

3750
02:19:35,639 --> 02:19:37,918
there's just a ton of gods floating around

3751
02:19:37,920 --> 02:19:39,750
and, you know, maybe you worship that one,

3752
02:19:39,750 --> 02:19:41,333
and I worship these two that I like,

3753
02:19:41,333 --> 02:19:42,810
and the guy across the street

3754
02:19:42,809 --> 02:19:44,549
worships the oak tree in his backyard,

3755
02:19:44,549 --> 02:19:45,449
and it's all good.

3756
02:19:46,350 --> 02:19:48,120
They're all legitimate things.

3757
02:19:48,120 --> 02:19:49,590
Versus, "Oh, no, no, no.

3758
02:19:49,590 --> 02:19:51,090
Now, there is one God

3759
02:19:51,090 --> 02:19:54,270
and only one God that's the correct answer."

3760
02:19:54,270 --> 02:19:55,469
And as soon as you do that,

3761
02:19:55,469 --> 02:19:57,959
religion becomes foregrounded

3762
02:19:57,959 --> 02:20:00,479
in your decision-making much more.

3763
02:20:00,479 --> 02:20:02,488
I mean, the Romans had religion,

3764
02:20:02,489 --> 02:20:04,498
but it wasn't really driving anything,

3765
02:20:04,500 --> 02:20:05,699
if you know what I mean.

3766
02:20:05,700 --> 02:20:09,450
It was auxiliary to things rather than a central force.

3767
02:20:09,450 --> 02:20:11,490
So for a lot of Roman history,

3768
02:20:11,489 --> 02:20:14,189
you had a standard kind of, you know,

3769
02:20:14,190 --> 02:20:15,900
I guess, pagan polytheism

3770
02:20:15,899 --> 02:20:17,699
where there's a bunch of gods,

3771
02:20:17,700 --> 02:20:18,533
there's certain gods

3772
02:20:18,532 --> 02:20:20,449
who are associated with the Roman state,

3773
02:20:21,389 --> 02:20:24,268
and there would be prayers said to those gods

3774
02:20:24,270 --> 02:20:26,279
on behalf of the Roman state,

3775
02:20:26,280 --> 02:20:28,260
but it wasn't really, you know,

3776
02:20:28,260 --> 02:20:31,349
you weren't trying to execute the will of Zeus or something,

3777
02:20:31,350 --> 02:20:34,050
or of Jupiter, or Mars, or anybody else.

3778
02:20:34,049 --> 02:20:36,089
And in your private life, it was the same thing.

3779
02:20:36,090 --> 02:20:37,950
You might ask certain gods for help,

3780
02:20:37,950 --> 02:20:40,619
but it wasn't as much of a dominant thing

3781
02:20:40,620 --> 02:20:42,570
in your own existence.

3782
02:20:42,569 --> 02:20:45,059
So I think that's a real transition point

3783
02:20:45,059 --> 02:20:48,148
where religion started to become so foregrounded.

3784
02:20:48,149 --> 02:20:51,358
And as soon as you get the monotheistic religions,

3785
02:20:51,360 --> 02:20:52,470
Judaism, Christianity,

3786
02:20:52,469 --> 02:20:54,118
and Islam, in particular,

3787
02:20:54,120 --> 02:20:57,030
it really shifts how people start to think about themselves

3788
02:20:57,030 --> 02:20:59,610
in relationship to the world around them.

3789
02:20:59,610 --> 02:21:03,720
- So Jesus was born during the rule of Emperor Augustus.

3790
02:21:03,719 --> 02:21:06,089
- Yep. And which is kind of neat that, you know,

3791
02:21:06,090 --> 02:21:09,270
really influential people in the realm of political events

3792
02:21:09,270 --> 02:21:11,842
and religious events coexisted.

3793
02:21:11,842 --> 02:21:13,743
- Or... - What are the odds?

3794
02:21:14,579 --> 02:21:16,829
- I mean, yeah, there's certain moments in history

3795
02:21:16,829 --> 02:21:19,319
where just a lot of interesting, powerful people

3796
02:21:19,319 --> 02:21:21,362
come together and make history.

3797
02:21:22,200 --> 02:21:25,320
So, and he was crucified under Emperor Tiberius rule.

3798
02:21:25,319 --> 02:21:26,789
- [Gregory] Yep.

3799
02:21:26,790 --> 02:21:28,859
- [Lex] Why were the ideas of Jesus

3800
02:21:28,860 --> 02:21:31,263
seen as a threat by the emperor?

3801
02:21:32,129 --> 02:21:36,359
- The thing that causes conflicts

3802
02:21:36,360 --> 02:21:38,790
between the Romans and Christians

3803
02:21:38,790 --> 02:21:40,199
is a little bit strange.

3804
02:21:40,200 --> 02:21:41,643
It's all with this,

3805
02:21:42,840 --> 02:21:45,299
where the Romans had a tradition of,

3806
02:21:45,299 --> 02:21:47,009
on the emperor's birthday,

3807
02:21:47,010 --> 02:21:48,300
sort of saying a prayer,

3808
02:21:48,299 --> 02:21:50,729
basically, wishing him good luck, okay?

3809
02:21:50,729 --> 02:21:52,079
But technically, it's in the form

3810
02:21:52,079 --> 02:21:55,199
of sacrificing to that part of the emperor

3811
02:21:55,200 --> 02:21:57,659
that might become divine after his death.

3812
02:21:57,659 --> 02:21:58,709
So to the Romans,

3813
02:21:58,709 --> 02:22:02,159
this is the equivalent of a patriotism act,

3814
02:22:02,159 --> 02:22:03,479
saying, you know, the pledge of allegiance

3815
02:22:03,479 --> 02:22:04,949
or something to the country.

3816
02:22:04,950 --> 02:22:06,240
But of course, to Christians,

3817
02:22:06,239 --> 02:22:08,489
this is worshiping another God.

3818
02:22:08,489 --> 02:22:11,279
And I think there's almost a failure of communication here.

3819
02:22:11,280 --> 02:22:13,289
That the Romans just, at least initially,

3820
02:22:13,290 --> 02:22:14,459
didn't quite understand

3821
02:22:14,459 --> 02:22:16,648
this is really problematic for these people,

3822
02:22:16,649 --> 02:22:19,499
because they're coming from a polytheistic perspective

3823
02:22:19,500 --> 02:22:21,839
where, yeah, everybody has different gods, so what?

3824
02:22:21,840 --> 02:22:24,360
This isn't a religious problem,

3825
02:22:24,360 --> 02:22:26,759
this is a political one

3826
02:22:26,760 --> 02:22:28,800
that why won't you wish, you know,

3827
02:22:28,799 --> 02:22:30,059
send good wishes to the emperor?

3828
02:22:30,059 --> 02:22:31,379
If you're a loyal Roman,

3829
02:22:31,379 --> 02:22:33,928
this is something you should want to do.

3830
02:22:33,930 --> 02:22:35,520
And many of the early Christians, I think,

3831
02:22:35,520 --> 02:22:36,959
would've been fine with that,

3832
02:22:36,959 --> 02:22:40,139
but it took the form of what they were asked to be do

3833
02:22:40,139 --> 02:22:44,249
was to basically worship another God.

3834
02:22:44,250 --> 02:22:46,410
And that was the sticking point.

3835
02:22:46,409 --> 02:22:48,359
And this is where I think movies

3836
02:22:48,360 --> 02:22:49,559
have kind of warped

3837
02:22:49,559 --> 02:22:51,958
some of our images of Roman history.

3838
02:22:51,959 --> 02:22:56,338
That Hollywood loves to depict very early Christians,

3839
02:22:56,340 --> 02:22:58,200
and I'm talking like first 200 years

3840
02:22:58,200 --> 02:23:00,959
hereafter the ministry of Christ,

3841
02:23:00,959 --> 02:23:03,358
as, you know, a group

3842
02:23:03,360 --> 02:23:05,190
that all the Romans were obsessed with,

3843
02:23:05,190 --> 02:23:07,830
that they were constantly trying to persecute, and all this.

3844
02:23:07,829 --> 02:23:09,898
And honestly, I think the Romans at that point

3845
02:23:09,899 --> 02:23:11,699
were more just sort of indifferent

3846
02:23:11,700 --> 02:23:13,470
or didn't know what was going on.

3847
02:23:13,469 --> 02:23:16,199
And if you look at some of the primary sources at that time,

3848
02:23:16,200 --> 02:23:18,060
I mean, there's this very famous letter

3849
02:23:18,059 --> 02:23:19,948
by a guy named Pliny,

3850
02:23:19,950 --> 02:23:24,030
who was a Roman governor of a province in the east.

3851
02:23:24,030 --> 02:23:25,980
And he has the habit of writing letters

3852
02:23:25,979 --> 02:23:27,329
to the Roman emperor at the time,

3853
02:23:27,329 --> 02:23:28,169
who was Trajan,

3854
02:23:28,170 --> 02:23:31,500
every time he had a problem with being governor.

3855
02:23:31,500 --> 02:23:32,729
And so this is great.

3856
02:23:32,729 --> 02:23:35,459
This is the two highest governmental officials

3857
02:23:35,459 --> 02:23:36,688
in the Roman world

3858
02:23:36,690 --> 02:23:38,910
sort of hammering out policy between them, right?

3859
02:23:38,909 --> 02:23:40,889
The emperor and one of his governors.

3860
02:23:40,889 --> 02:23:42,359
And so this is about a hundred years,

3861
02:23:42,360 --> 02:23:43,860
a hundred AD about,

3862
02:23:43,860 --> 02:23:46,500
and Pliny says, "Hey, emperor,

3863
02:23:46,500 --> 02:23:47,550
I had this issue,

3864
02:23:47,549 --> 02:23:50,098
I had these people come before me called Christians.

3865
02:23:50,100 --> 02:23:51,749
I don't quite know what to do with them.

3866
02:23:51,750 --> 02:23:53,730
What should my policy be?

3867
02:23:53,729 --> 02:23:55,138
And here's what I know about them."

3868
02:23:55,139 --> 02:23:56,669
And what he knows is almost nothing.

3869
02:23:56,670 --> 02:23:58,230
I mean, it's this

3870
02:23:58,229 --> 02:23:59,796
almost comic, like, garbling.

3871
02:23:59,797 --> 02:24:01,319
"And, you know, they have this weird thing

3872
02:24:01,319 --> 02:24:03,388
where they get together on some day of the week

3873
02:24:03,389 --> 02:24:05,848
and they sort of swear oaths to one another

3874
02:24:05,850 --> 02:24:07,380
not to do bad stuff,"

3875
02:24:07,379 --> 02:24:09,268
which is, of course, his garbled understanding

3876
02:24:09,270 --> 02:24:10,919
of the 10 Commandments, you know.

3877
02:24:12,037 --> 02:24:13,620
"And then they have breakfast together,

3878
02:24:13,620 --> 02:24:14,670
and they eat food."

3879
02:24:14,670 --> 02:24:15,869
And this is communion,

3880
02:24:15,870 --> 02:24:19,079
but he doesn't get that that's what's going on.

3881
02:24:19,079 --> 02:24:21,599
And so he's really ignorant.

3882
02:24:21,600 --> 02:24:23,400
But I think that the broader point is,

3883
02:24:23,399 --> 02:24:26,789
okay, this is one of the best educated,

3884
02:24:26,790 --> 02:24:28,979
best traveled Romans

3885
02:24:28,979 --> 02:24:31,139
who has the most experience in the empire,

3886
02:24:31,139 --> 02:24:33,389
has been all over the empire,

3887
02:24:33,389 --> 02:24:35,308
and what does he know about Christianity?

3888
02:24:35,309 --> 02:24:37,259
Basically, nothing.

3889
02:24:37,260 --> 02:24:41,429
So if one of the best educated, most widely traveled guys

3890
02:24:41,430 --> 02:24:44,340
really doesn't know much about them,

3891
02:24:44,340 --> 02:24:45,779
that kind of suggests

3892
02:24:45,780 --> 02:24:48,329
that not many people did at this point in time.

3893
02:24:48,329 --> 02:24:50,069
- At this time, it was a fringe movement

3894
02:24:50,069 --> 02:24:51,357
that really did- - Yeah, very fringe.

3895
02:24:51,359 --> 02:24:52,889
I mean, it was one of, you know,

3896
02:24:52,889 --> 02:24:54,989
hundreds of little mystery religions,

3897
02:24:54,989 --> 02:24:56,333
the Romans sort of thought on this.

3898
02:24:56,334 --> 02:24:57,167
And these are, you know,

3899
02:24:57,166 --> 02:24:59,488
religions that have some sort of revealed knowledge

3900
02:24:59,489 --> 02:25:03,179
and that make more personal appeals to people.

3901
02:25:03,180 --> 02:25:06,599
Now, stepping back from this in a broad way,

3902
02:25:06,600 --> 02:25:08,130
I think you can say that Christianity

3903
02:25:08,129 --> 02:25:10,468
really was different in some ways

3904
02:25:10,469 --> 02:25:12,629
and had some things that maybe the Romans

3905
02:25:12,629 --> 02:25:14,698
should rightfully have viewed as a threat.

3906
02:25:14,700 --> 02:25:16,740
I mean, you know, the Romans are people

3907
02:25:16,739 --> 02:25:18,899
very focused on this world, right?

3908
02:25:18,899 --> 02:25:20,609
Citizenship, what you do.

3909
02:25:20,610 --> 02:25:24,210
Christianity, in essence, has a focus on the next world.

3910
02:25:24,209 --> 02:25:25,529
So this world isn't as important

3911
02:25:25,530 --> 02:25:27,599
as what you're setting yourself up for.

3912
02:25:27,600 --> 02:25:29,939
And even worse, from a Roman perspective,

3913
02:25:29,940 --> 02:25:32,399
I'm kind of saying, okay, if I were a Roman,

3914
02:25:32,399 --> 02:25:36,149
Romans are all about making distinctions between people.

3915
02:25:36,149 --> 02:25:38,428
Citizen, non-citizen.

3916
02:25:38,430 --> 02:25:39,659
Man, woman.

3917
02:25:39,659 --> 02:25:41,788
Free, slave.

3918
02:25:41,790 --> 02:25:43,747
Christianity comes along and says,

3919
02:25:43,746 --> 02:25:47,008
"In God's eyes, you're all equal."

3920
02:25:47,010 --> 02:25:50,219
Now, that's a pretty problematic idea

3921
02:25:50,219 --> 02:25:53,638
if you're deeply invested in Roman hierarchy.

3922
02:25:53,639 --> 02:25:55,949
And I think it is no surprise

3923
02:25:55,950 --> 02:26:00,119
that among the earliest converts to Christianity

3924
02:26:00,120 --> 02:26:02,850
are women and slaves,

3925
02:26:02,850 --> 02:26:05,609
and in particular female slaves.

3926
02:26:05,610 --> 02:26:06,660
Now, who are they?

3927
02:26:06,659 --> 02:26:08,848
They're the people at the rock bottom

3928
02:26:08,850 --> 02:26:11,580
of the Roman hierarchy of status, right?

3929
02:26:11,579 --> 02:26:13,619
Which the Romans are obsessed with status,

3930
02:26:13,620 --> 02:26:16,439
but here's a religion that says that doesn't matter.

3931
02:26:16,440 --> 02:26:18,870
And in that same letter to Pliny,

3932
02:26:18,870 --> 02:26:20,820
Pliny says, "Okay, in this group of Christians

3933
02:26:20,819 --> 02:26:21,652
I've heard about,

3934
02:26:21,653 --> 02:26:23,879
their leaders are two female slaves

3935
02:26:23,879 --> 02:26:25,829
they call deaconess."

3936
02:26:25,829 --> 02:26:27,419
Now, this is really early.

3937
02:26:27,420 --> 02:26:30,330
This is before the church exists, right?

3938
02:26:30,329 --> 02:26:32,579
There's no church structure yet.

3939
02:26:32,579 --> 02:26:35,938
And who is leading the local congregation of Christians?

3940
02:26:35,940 --> 02:26:37,232
Two slave women.

3941
02:26:39,180 --> 02:26:41,130
So that's an interesting moment, you know.

3942
02:26:41,129 --> 02:26:43,048
And that's not necessarily the image

3943
02:26:43,049 --> 02:26:45,089
we get of early Christianity,

3944
02:26:45,090 --> 02:26:47,159
but you can see how,

3945
02:26:47,159 --> 02:26:49,529
for people in this social structure,

3946
02:26:49,530 --> 02:26:51,270
that would be very appealing to them.

3947
02:26:51,270 --> 02:26:52,649
And in some ways, yeah,

3948
02:26:52,649 --> 02:26:54,689
it is sort of a threat to the Roman system

3949
02:26:54,690 --> 02:26:56,400
because they're challenging it.

3950
02:26:56,399 --> 02:26:57,931
Now, the irony is, of course,

3951
02:26:57,933 --> 02:27:00,929
300 years after the life of Christ,

3952
02:27:00,930 --> 02:27:03,840
the emperor converts to Christianity,

3953
02:27:03,840 --> 02:27:05,100
and another hundred years later,

3954
02:27:05,100 --> 02:27:05,933
under Theodosius,

3955
02:27:05,933 --> 02:27:09,389
it becomes the official religion of the Roman Empire.

3956
02:27:09,389 --> 02:27:11,038
So all of a sudden, you have this flip flop,

3957
02:27:11,040 --> 02:27:13,290
where now the state itself

3958
02:27:13,290 --> 02:27:15,660
is not just converted to Christianity,

3959
02:27:15,659 --> 02:27:17,938
but actively promoting it

3960
02:27:17,940 --> 02:27:20,162
and now persecuting pagans.

3961
02:27:21,239 --> 02:27:24,239
And the reason the emperors do that

3962
02:27:24,239 --> 02:27:26,669
is one of the biggest problems for emperors

3963
02:27:26,670 --> 02:27:29,069
at that point in time is legitimacy.

3964
02:27:29,069 --> 02:27:30,718
That there's tons of civil wars

3965
02:27:30,719 --> 02:27:32,885
where you have lots of different people saying,

3966
02:27:32,887 --> 02:27:34,169
"I'm emperor."

3967
02:27:34,170 --> 02:27:37,230
So lots of generals declaring themselves emperor.

3968
02:27:37,229 --> 02:27:41,701
Now, under a polytheistic religion,

3969
02:27:42,629 --> 02:27:44,099
that's just, you're all just fighting.

3970
02:27:44,100 --> 02:27:45,329
It doesn't matter.

3971
02:27:45,329 --> 02:27:48,869
But if you say there is only one God,

3972
02:27:48,870 --> 02:27:52,680
then if that God picks someone to be his emperor,

3973
02:27:52,680 --> 02:27:56,910
they're the only legitimate emperor, right?

3974
02:27:56,909 --> 02:27:59,009
So there is a real advantage

3975
02:27:59,010 --> 02:28:01,650
to emperors now becoming Christian,

3976
02:28:01,649 --> 02:28:03,906
because if they can say,

3977
02:28:03,906 --> 02:28:06,088
"We're now a Christian Empire,

3978
02:28:06,090 --> 02:28:07,650
and there's only one God,

3979
02:28:07,649 --> 02:28:09,928
and I'm the guy that God picked to be emperor,"

3980
02:28:09,930 --> 02:28:11,520
that means all these other people

3981
02:28:11,520 --> 02:28:14,100
claiming to be emperors are illegitimate.

3982
02:28:14,100 --> 02:28:15,430
- Do you think that,

3983
02:28:15,430 --> 02:28:17,400
or is there other factors that explain

3984
02:28:17,399 --> 02:28:20,309
why Christianity was able to spread?

3985
02:28:20,309 --> 02:28:22,469
- Well, I mean, that's why it's appealing to the emperors.

3986
02:28:22,469 --> 02:28:24,569
And we're talking here, you know...

3987
02:28:24,569 --> 02:28:26,939
I mean, the religious answer is

3988
02:28:26,940 --> 02:28:28,319
people see the light, right?

3989
02:28:28,319 --> 02:28:29,879
It's a faith-based thing.

3990
02:28:29,879 --> 02:28:32,008
I'm looking at this as a historian.

3991
02:28:32,010 --> 02:28:33,960
So putting aside, you know,

3992
02:28:33,959 --> 02:28:34,866
religious feeling and saying,

3993
02:28:34,867 --> 02:28:37,080
"Okay, if I'm doing an analysis of this

3994
02:28:37,079 --> 02:28:38,518
as a social phenomenon,

3995
02:28:38,520 --> 02:28:40,140
what would be appealing to people?"

3996
02:28:40,139 --> 02:28:42,239
And there is that very compelling reason

3997
02:28:42,239 --> 02:28:44,848
for emperors to want to go to Christianity

3998
02:28:44,850 --> 02:28:46,890
because it helps 'em with their biggest problem,

3999
02:28:46,889 --> 02:28:48,179
which is legitimacy.

4000
02:28:48,180 --> 02:28:50,430
Now, if you're an ordinary person,

4001
02:28:50,430 --> 02:28:52,140
what is the appeal of Christianity?

4002
02:28:52,139 --> 02:28:54,239
Well, we already looked at a couple of 'em.

4003
02:28:54,239 --> 02:28:55,349
One of 'em is that, you know,

4004
02:28:55,350 --> 02:28:57,663
it promises you a reward in the afterlife.

4005
02:28:58,799 --> 02:29:01,289
I mean, the Roman and Greek notions of the afterlife

4006
02:29:01,290 --> 02:29:02,939
aren't that appealing.

4007
02:29:02,940 --> 02:29:04,920
Either you just sort of turn into dust,

4008
02:29:04,920 --> 02:29:07,560
or, at best, you turn into this kind of ghost thing

4009
02:29:07,559 --> 02:29:08,879
that floats around something

4010
02:29:08,879 --> 02:29:10,469
that looks like a Greek gymnasium,

4011
02:29:10,469 --> 02:29:12,569
which is like a bunch of grassy fields.

4012
02:29:12,569 --> 02:29:13,831
It's not so hot.

4013
02:29:14,909 --> 02:29:16,356
So here, you're offered the idea of like,

4014
02:29:16,356 --> 02:29:18,089
"Oh, you go to paradise forever."

4015
02:29:18,090 --> 02:29:19,529
That sounds really good.

4016
02:29:19,530 --> 02:29:22,409
And secondly, for a lot of people in Roman society,

4017
02:29:22,409 --> 02:29:24,845
that notion of, here's something that says

4018
02:29:24,846 --> 02:29:26,999
"I'm valuable as a human being.

4019
02:29:27,000 --> 02:29:29,100
It doesn't matter whether I'm free or slave,

4020
02:29:29,100 --> 02:29:31,680
it doesn't matter whether I'm Roman or non-Roman,

4021
02:29:31,680 --> 02:29:33,420
it doesn't matter if I'm man or woman,

4022
02:29:33,420 --> 02:29:35,670
here's something that says I have equal value,"

4023
02:29:35,670 --> 02:29:37,410
that's enormously appealing.

4024
02:29:37,409 --> 02:29:38,578
And finally, early Christians,

4025
02:29:38,579 --> 02:29:39,412
I mean, they honestly,

4026
02:29:39,413 --> 02:29:40,679
a lot of them do good works.

4027
02:29:40,680 --> 02:29:42,420
They take care of the sick,

4028
02:29:42,420 --> 02:29:43,890
they feed the poor.

4029
02:29:43,889 --> 02:29:45,209
I mean, if you look at Jesus

4030
02:29:45,209 --> 02:29:46,319
and the Sermon on the Mount,

4031
02:29:46,319 --> 02:29:48,479
that's the stuff he really hammers.

4032
02:29:48,479 --> 02:29:50,158
If we look at, you know, the words of Jesus

4033
02:29:50,159 --> 02:29:51,749
when he says, "What do you do to be a Christian?"

4034
02:29:51,750 --> 02:29:54,363
A lot of it is take care of the unfortunate,

4035
02:29:55,200 --> 02:29:57,780
you know, take care of people who are sick,

4036
02:29:57,780 --> 02:30:00,420
take care of people who are starving.

4037
02:30:00,420 --> 02:30:01,859
And a lot of the early Christians

4038
02:30:01,860 --> 02:30:03,450
really take that seriously.

4039
02:30:03,450 --> 02:30:05,729
So they are helping people out,

4040
02:30:05,729 --> 02:30:07,679
so that's appealing.

4041
02:30:07,680 --> 02:30:10,110
- They're are the good kind of populist,

4042
02:30:10,110 --> 02:30:11,943
and populist messages spread.

4043
02:30:14,700 --> 02:30:16,498
Let me ask you about gladiators.

4044
02:30:16,498 --> 02:30:19,349
- (laughs) Switch of pace here.

4045
02:30:19,350 --> 02:30:22,713
- What role did they play in Roman society?

4046
02:30:23,940 --> 02:30:25,589
- I mean, okay, gladiator games

4047
02:30:25,590 --> 02:30:28,259
has obviously become a popular form of entertainment,

4048
02:30:28,260 --> 02:30:29,340
and they're one of the ones

4049
02:30:29,340 --> 02:30:31,320
that's captured people's imaginations

4050
02:30:31,319 --> 02:30:32,309
for all sorts of reasons.

4051
02:30:32,309 --> 02:30:33,748
I mean, it's dramatic,

4052
02:30:33,750 --> 02:30:36,299
but also I think it's that apparent contradiction

4053
02:30:36,299 --> 02:30:37,259
that in so many ways,

4054
02:30:37,260 --> 02:30:40,679
Roman society seems familiar to us,

4055
02:30:40,680 --> 02:30:41,520
in so many ways,

4056
02:30:41,520 --> 02:30:44,580
it seems sophisticated and appealing,

4057
02:30:44,579 --> 02:30:46,409
law is wonderful, all this,

4058
02:30:46,409 --> 02:30:48,538
but yet, for fun,

4059
02:30:48,540 --> 02:30:50,819
they watched people fight to the death.

4060
02:30:50,819 --> 02:30:52,669
So how do you reconcile these things?

4061
02:30:53,909 --> 02:30:56,009
Gladiators, I find very interesting

4062
02:30:56,010 --> 02:30:58,619
because they're an example

4063
02:30:58,620 --> 02:31:02,519
of what historians call status dissonance.

4064
02:31:02,520 --> 02:31:04,983
So it's someone who, in society,

4065
02:31:06,600 --> 02:31:08,879
has high status in some ways

4066
02:31:08,879 --> 02:31:12,149
and very low or despise status in another.

4067
02:31:12,149 --> 02:31:15,539
So gladiators, most of them were slaves.

4068
02:31:15,540 --> 02:31:18,932
The lowest of the low in Roman society, right?

4069
02:31:20,069 --> 02:31:22,769
Also, they're fighting for other people's pleasure,

4070
02:31:22,770 --> 02:31:25,410
and dying sometimes for other people's pleasure.

4071
02:31:25,409 --> 02:31:27,418
And the Romans had a real thing about this,

4072
02:31:27,420 --> 02:31:30,690
like your body being used for others' pleasure.

4073
02:31:30,690 --> 02:31:32,579
Even a humble working person

4074
02:31:32,579 --> 02:31:35,038
who hired themself out for labor,

4075
02:31:35,040 --> 02:31:37,379
the Romans thought that was innately demeaning

4076
02:31:37,379 --> 02:31:39,568
because you're using your body

4077
02:31:39,569 --> 02:31:41,488
for someone else's benefit or pleasure.

4078
02:31:41,489 --> 02:31:43,979
So they didn't have this notion of, you know,

4079
02:31:43,979 --> 02:31:46,079
the dignity of hard labor or something.

4080
02:31:46,079 --> 02:31:48,688
They thought the only noble profession was farming, okay?

4081
02:31:48,690 --> 02:31:50,609
'Cause there, you generate something

4082
02:31:50,610 --> 02:31:52,080
and you're producing it for yourself,

4083
02:31:52,079 --> 02:31:53,639
but if you work for someone else,

4084
02:31:53,639 --> 02:31:55,169
you're demeaning yourself.

4085
02:31:55,170 --> 02:31:57,299
And gladiators are the worst of the worst, right?

4086
02:31:57,299 --> 02:31:59,968
You're performing for someone else's pleasure.

4087
02:31:59,969 --> 02:32:02,339
So on the one hand, they're very low status,

4088
02:32:02,340 --> 02:32:03,810
but on the other hand,

4089
02:32:03,809 --> 02:32:06,268
successful gladiators get famous.

4090
02:32:06,270 --> 02:32:08,100
People admire them,

4091
02:32:08,100 --> 02:32:09,933
women find them attractive,

4092
02:32:10,770 --> 02:32:12,659
you know, they're celebrities.

4093
02:32:12,659 --> 02:32:15,359
And so this is the status dissonance, right?

4094
02:32:15,360 --> 02:32:17,580
You have these people who, on the one hand,

4095
02:32:17,579 --> 02:32:20,759
formally, are very low status in society,

4096
02:32:20,760 --> 02:32:23,550
but yet are very popular, on the other hand.

4097
02:32:23,549 --> 02:32:25,438
Another kind of myth about gladiators

4098
02:32:25,440 --> 02:32:28,170
is that they were just dying all the time.

4099
02:32:28,170 --> 02:32:30,089
I mean, you watch, you know, movies

4100
02:32:30,090 --> 02:32:32,009
and, again, they'll always throw a bunch of gladiators

4101
02:32:32,010 --> 02:32:33,270
and they all die.

4102
02:32:33,270 --> 02:32:35,430
I think some scholar did study of,

4103
02:32:35,430 --> 02:32:38,189
there's like a hundred fights we know of

4104
02:32:38,190 --> 02:32:40,050
where we know some details,

4105
02:32:40,049 --> 02:32:42,328
and I think 10% of those

4106
02:32:42,329 --> 02:32:44,338
ended in the death of one of the people.

4107
02:32:44,340 --> 02:32:48,780
So gladiators are a lot more like boxing matches

4108
02:32:48,780 --> 02:32:51,510
where you're watching a display of skill

4109
02:32:51,510 --> 02:32:52,739
between two people

4110
02:32:52,739 --> 02:32:54,719
who are more or less evenly matched

4111
02:32:54,719 --> 02:32:56,638
in terms of their abilities.

4112
02:32:56,639 --> 02:32:58,799
And probably they'll survive,

4113
02:32:58,799 --> 02:33:01,138
though there's a chance that one of them might get injured,

4114
02:33:01,139 --> 02:33:02,492
in fact, one might die.

4115
02:33:04,409 --> 02:33:06,449
Having said all that, in the end,

4116
02:33:06,450 --> 02:33:08,760
you really are having people fight

4117
02:33:08,760 --> 02:33:09,750
and potentially die

4118
02:33:09,750 --> 02:33:11,550
for the pleasure of an audience.

4119
02:33:11,549 --> 02:33:13,828
And anthropologists and Roman historians

4120
02:33:13,829 --> 02:33:16,741
like to speculate why did the Romans do this.

4121
02:33:17,670 --> 02:33:19,170
The Romans address it.

4122
02:33:19,170 --> 02:33:22,566
I mean, there's a famous thing where a Roman says,

4123
02:33:22,566 --> 02:33:24,929
"We, Romans, were a violent people,

4124
02:33:24,930 --> 02:33:26,339
we're a warlike people,

4125
02:33:26,340 --> 02:33:28,889
and so it's fitting that we should be accustomed

4126
02:33:28,889 --> 02:33:30,776
to the sight of death and violence."

4127
02:33:32,010 --> 02:33:32,943
Kind of works.

4128
02:33:33,989 --> 02:33:37,558
There's a more symbolic interpretation that says

4129
02:33:37,559 --> 02:33:41,608
the amphitheater is an expression of Roman dominance,

4130
02:33:41,610 --> 02:33:43,529
a symbolic expression,

4131
02:33:43,530 --> 02:33:44,520
because what you have

4132
02:33:44,520 --> 02:33:47,580
are all segments of Roman society gathered together

4133
02:33:47,579 --> 02:33:50,458
to control the fate of others.

4134
02:33:50,459 --> 02:33:51,959
So you have foreigners,

4135
02:33:51,959 --> 02:33:53,219
you have wild animals,

4136
02:33:53,219 --> 02:33:54,839
you have criminals,

4137
02:33:54,840 --> 02:33:56,489
you have other people.

4138
02:33:56,489 --> 02:33:59,819
And we are symbolically asserting our dominance

4139
02:33:59,819 --> 02:34:00,929
over those groups

4140
02:34:00,930 --> 02:34:03,809
by determining do you live or do you die?

4141
02:34:03,809 --> 02:34:06,059
And that kind works too.

4142
02:34:06,059 --> 02:34:09,418
And the cynical one is humans like violence.

4143
02:34:09,420 --> 02:34:11,879
I mean, when people watch a hockey game,

4144
02:34:11,879 --> 02:34:13,469
what gets the most excited?

4145
02:34:13,469 --> 02:34:14,309
The fight.

4146
02:34:14,309 --> 02:34:16,799
When people watch car racing,

4147
02:34:16,799 --> 02:34:17,819
there's a crash,

4148
02:34:17,819 --> 02:34:19,228
what's gonna be shown on the news?

4149
02:34:19,229 --> 02:34:20,638
It's the crash.

4150
02:34:20,639 --> 02:34:23,909
So there's something dark in human nature sometimes

4151
02:34:23,909 --> 02:34:24,959
that likes violence

4152
02:34:24,959 --> 02:34:25,792
and maybe the Romans

4153
02:34:25,792 --> 02:34:28,828
are just being more honest about it than we are.

4154
02:34:28,829 --> 02:34:29,968
- I think Dan Carlin

4155
02:34:29,969 --> 02:34:31,926
has a really great episode called

4156
02:34:31,926 --> 02:34:34,429
"Painfotainment." - Uh-huh.

4157
02:34:34,430 --> 02:34:36,630
- And I think in that episode,

4158
02:34:36,629 --> 02:34:38,038
he suggests a hypothetical

4159
02:34:38,040 --> 02:34:40,620
that if we did something like a gladiator games today

4160
02:34:40,620 --> 02:34:41,453
to the death,

4161
02:34:42,299 --> 02:34:44,159
that like the whole world would tune in.

4162
02:34:44,159 --> 02:34:45,009
- [Gregory] Yeah.

4163
02:34:45,930 --> 02:34:47,700
- Especially if it was anonymous, right?

4164
02:34:47,700 --> 02:34:51,030
We have a kind of like thin veil of civility,

4165
02:34:51,030 --> 02:34:53,159
underneath which we probably would still be,

4166
02:34:53,159 --> 02:34:54,239
something deep within us

4167
02:34:54,239 --> 02:34:56,586
would be attracted to that violence.

4168
02:34:56,587 --> 02:34:57,479
- Yeah. I mean, yeah,

4169
02:34:57,479 --> 02:35:00,059
there always, is it human nature?

4170
02:35:00,059 --> 02:35:02,369
You know, why do people slow down when there's a car wreck

4171
02:35:02,370 --> 02:35:04,320
and try and see what's happening?

4172
02:35:04,319 --> 02:35:05,488
On the other hand, to be fair,

4173
02:35:05,489 --> 02:35:07,469
I mean, there were Romans at the time

4174
02:35:07,469 --> 02:35:09,118
who morally objected to them

4175
02:35:09,120 --> 02:35:10,680
and said this is, you know,

4176
02:35:10,680 --> 02:35:13,439
morally degenerate to take pleasure in this

4177
02:35:13,440 --> 02:35:14,550
and that's wrong.

4178
02:35:14,549 --> 02:35:16,499
So I think in all eras,

4179
02:35:16,500 --> 02:35:18,060
you have a diversity of opinions.

4180
02:35:18,059 --> 02:35:20,549
There's no unanimous, you know, take on

4181
02:35:20,549 --> 02:35:22,499
on what this is or what this means.

4182
02:35:22,500 --> 02:35:25,020
- So who usually were the gladiators?

4183
02:35:25,020 --> 02:35:26,370
Was it slaves? Was it...

4184
02:35:26,370 --> 02:35:27,630
- Well, the most common source, again,

4185
02:35:27,629 --> 02:35:29,099
is prisoners of war. - Prisoners.

4186
02:35:29,100 --> 02:35:31,530
- So if you conquer some people

4187
02:35:31,530 --> 02:35:33,630
and they seem to be warlike,

4188
02:35:33,629 --> 02:35:36,689
you might well consign some of them to fight in the arena.

4189
02:35:36,690 --> 02:35:38,129
And the other thing about gladiators

4190
02:35:38,129 --> 02:35:41,415
is they were highly trained professionals.

4191
02:35:41,416 --> 02:35:44,729
So, you know, the gladiator schools who train them

4192
02:35:44,729 --> 02:35:47,398
were spending a lot of money to train these people.

4193
02:35:47,399 --> 02:35:49,169
And it wasn't just we take some guy

4194
02:35:49,170 --> 02:35:50,490
and throw 'em into the arena

4195
02:35:50,489 --> 02:35:53,339
like you see in movies all the time.

4196
02:35:53,340 --> 02:35:55,560
These were people that you'd invested a lot of money in,

4197
02:35:55,559 --> 02:35:58,529
that's why you don't really want to see them killed.

4198
02:35:58,530 --> 02:36:01,530
But yeah, mostly, they're prisoners of war.

4199
02:36:01,530 --> 02:36:03,360
I mean, in very rare instances,

4200
02:36:03,360 --> 02:36:05,699
you might have a free person volunteering

4201
02:36:05,700 --> 02:36:08,610
or even selling themself to fight as gladiators,

4202
02:36:08,610 --> 02:36:11,069
but much more common was that.

4203
02:36:11,069 --> 02:36:14,759
And what's interesting is some people wouldn't do it.

4204
02:36:14,760 --> 02:36:16,860
I mean, there's a lot of instances of gladiators

4205
02:36:16,860 --> 02:36:19,259
refusing to fight and committing suicide,

4206
02:36:19,260 --> 02:36:20,790
which you don't hear.

4207
02:36:20,790 --> 02:36:22,709
So like there was one German

4208
02:36:22,709 --> 02:36:24,809
who was supposed to fight as a gladiator

4209
02:36:24,809 --> 02:36:26,488
and instead he stuck his head

4210
02:36:26,489 --> 02:36:29,038
between the spokes of a wagon that was spinning

4211
02:36:29,040 --> 02:36:31,140
and snapped his own neck.

4212
02:36:31,139 --> 02:36:32,879
There were a group of 29 Germans

4213
02:36:32,879 --> 02:36:33,786
who all sort of said,

4214
02:36:33,787 --> 02:36:35,879
"We're not gonna fight for the Romans pleasure,"

4215
02:36:35,879 --> 02:36:37,379
and they strangled one another

4216
02:36:37,379 --> 02:36:40,258
the night before they were supposed to fight.

4217
02:36:40,260 --> 02:36:42,809
So I mean, you have people sort of objecting

4218
02:36:42,809 --> 02:36:47,156
to being complicit in this kind of performance as well.

4219
02:36:47,156 --> 02:36:50,369
- And they also had interest in animals.

4220
02:36:50,370 --> 02:36:51,203
- Yes.

4221
02:36:51,202 --> 02:36:53,609
- So humans fought animals.

4222
02:36:53,610 --> 02:36:54,510
Exotic animals.

4223
02:36:54,510 --> 02:36:56,429
- And animals fought animals. - Animals fought animals.

4224
02:36:56,430 --> 02:36:58,140
- Yeah, the Romans were a little weird

4225
02:36:58,139 --> 02:36:58,972
with their animal thing.

4226
02:36:58,972 --> 02:37:00,599
They loved exotic animals,

4227
02:37:00,600 --> 02:37:03,809
but mostly they liked to see the exotic animals die.

4228
02:37:03,809 --> 02:37:07,318
So I mean, there was an enormous industry

4229
02:37:07,319 --> 02:37:09,629
collecting wild beasts,

4230
02:37:09,629 --> 02:37:11,249
transporting them to Rome,

4231
02:37:11,250 --> 02:37:12,540
which is no easy matter

4232
02:37:12,540 --> 02:37:14,490
to transport elephants

4233
02:37:14,489 --> 02:37:16,349
and giraffes and rhinos,

4234
02:37:16,350 --> 02:37:18,689
particularly in, you know, this era of technology.

4235
02:37:18,690 --> 02:37:21,660
But they were like draining Africa

4236
02:37:21,659 --> 02:37:23,548
and bringing lions and all these things

4237
02:37:23,549 --> 02:37:25,198
and sacrificing them.

4238
02:37:25,200 --> 02:37:26,670
- And what about the different venues?

4239
02:37:26,670 --> 02:37:28,858
I mean, there's the legendary Colosseum.

4240
02:37:28,858 --> 02:37:32,490
What is the importance of this place?

4241
02:37:32,489 --> 02:37:33,628
- Well, the Colosseum,

4242
02:37:33,629 --> 02:37:35,999
it's real name is the Flavian Amphitheater,

4243
02:37:36,000 --> 02:37:38,330
is interesting because, for a long time,

4244
02:37:38,331 --> 02:37:40,560
Rome always had a chariot racing arena,

4245
02:37:40,559 --> 02:37:41,579
the Circus Maximus,

4246
02:37:41,579 --> 02:37:44,668
but it didn't have a permanent gladiatorial venue

4247
02:37:44,670 --> 02:37:48,449
until relatively late, 'til about 80 AD.

4248
02:37:48,450 --> 02:37:51,840
So during the reign of the Emperor Vespasian.

4249
02:37:51,840 --> 02:37:53,880
And he built this thing.

4250
02:37:53,879 --> 02:37:55,528
So he built the Flavian Amphitheater,

4251
02:37:55,530 --> 02:37:57,480
he was from the Flavian family of emperors,

4252
02:37:57,479 --> 02:38:02,248
and he did it as a deliberate act of propaganda.

4253
02:38:02,250 --> 02:38:05,310
So before him had been Nero,

4254
02:38:05,309 --> 02:38:07,858
who was, sources are saying,

4255
02:38:07,860 --> 02:38:10,170
crazy or bad emperor.

4256
02:38:10,170 --> 02:38:12,390
And one of Nero's indulgences

4257
02:38:12,389 --> 02:38:15,089
is he had built this enormous palace for himself

4258
02:38:15,090 --> 02:38:16,890
called the Golden House.

4259
02:38:16,889 --> 02:38:18,778
So it was kind of this pleasure palace

4260
02:38:18,780 --> 02:38:21,510
with 50 dining rooms and all this stuff.

4261
02:38:21,510 --> 02:38:25,349
And it was basically wasting a ton of money on him, right?

4262
02:38:25,350 --> 02:38:29,519
So right on the site where Nero had his Golden House,

4263
02:38:29,520 --> 02:38:33,450
Vespasian says, "I'm gonna erect a new building on top of it

4264
02:38:33,450 --> 02:38:35,940
that's gonna be for the pleasure of the people."

4265
02:38:35,940 --> 02:38:37,740
So it was very much a political statement

4266
02:38:37,739 --> 02:38:41,308
that my dynasty is gonna be about serving Romans,

4267
02:38:41,309 --> 02:38:43,349
not serving ourselves.

4268
02:38:43,350 --> 02:38:46,830
And so that's why he builds the Flavian Amphitheater.

4269
02:38:46,829 --> 02:38:48,599
And the funds he uses from it

4270
02:38:48,600 --> 02:38:51,419
is basically from looting Jerusalem.

4271
02:38:51,420 --> 02:38:53,400
Because the other thing he had done just before this

4272
02:38:53,399 --> 02:38:54,929
is he had sacked Jerusalem

4273
02:38:54,930 --> 02:38:57,479
and destroyed the temple there, in fact.

4274
02:38:57,479 --> 02:38:59,608
He and his son Titus.

4275
02:38:59,610 --> 02:39:02,250
And so this is what he now builds in Rome

4276
02:39:02,250 --> 02:39:04,890
is his gift to the people of Rome.

4277
02:39:04,889 --> 02:39:07,648
- But it's interesting to think about that place,

4278
02:39:07,649 --> 02:39:09,704
to think about their relationship with violence

4279
02:39:09,704 --> 02:39:12,838
across centuries

4280
02:39:12,840 --> 02:39:15,210
for spectacle, watching people fight.

4281
02:39:15,209 --> 02:39:17,069
And like you said, you know,

4282
02:39:17,069 --> 02:39:20,129
only like 10% of the time it led to the death,

4283
02:39:20,129 --> 02:39:25,129
but I read that still a lot of people died,

4284
02:39:25,170 --> 02:39:26,940
a lot of gladiators were killed.

4285
02:39:26,940 --> 02:39:28,089
- Oh yeah. - There's numbers are...

4286
02:39:28,090 --> 02:39:29,160
It is crazy, I mean.

4287
02:39:29,159 --> 02:39:33,119
I read a 400,000 dead.

4288
02:39:33,120 --> 02:39:34,740
So this includes gladiators, slaves,

4289
02:39:34,739 --> 02:39:37,888
convicts, prisoners, and so on.

4290
02:39:37,889 --> 02:39:39,118
That's a lot of people.

4291
02:39:39,120 --> 02:39:41,220
- The Flavian Amphitheater is really interesting too

4292
02:39:41,219 --> 02:39:42,929
just as a piece of technology

4293
02:39:42,930 --> 02:39:45,300
and as influence on later world.

4294
02:39:45,299 --> 02:39:48,209
I mean, almost every sporting arena today

4295
02:39:48,209 --> 02:39:50,249
owes something to the Flavian Amphitheater,

4296
02:39:50,250 --> 02:39:52,680
Colosseum, in terms of construction.

4297
02:39:52,680 --> 02:39:55,229
And it was amazingly sophisticated building.

4298
02:39:55,229 --> 02:39:57,418
I mean, it had, you know, retractable awnings

4299
02:39:57,420 --> 02:39:59,040
and elevators and ramps

4300
02:39:59,040 --> 02:40:02,339
that things could just pop up into the arena from below.

4301
02:40:02,340 --> 02:40:06,210
And, you know, it had very well designed passages

4302
02:40:06,209 --> 02:40:09,059
where everybody could file in and file out very efficiently,

4303
02:40:09,059 --> 02:40:10,529
and they were all numbered.

4304
02:40:10,530 --> 02:40:11,969
So, I mean, it's one of, I think,

4305
02:40:11,969 --> 02:40:14,998
the most influential buildings in history

4306
02:40:15,000 --> 02:40:16,830
just because of the way that, you know,

4307
02:40:16,829 --> 02:40:18,329
all these buildings we go to today,

4308
02:40:18,329 --> 02:40:19,829
they're all kind of variants on it

4309
02:40:19,829 --> 02:40:22,349
and using some of the ideas from it.

4310
02:40:22,350 --> 02:40:25,499
- And the Romans took their construction seriously.

4311
02:40:25,500 --> 02:40:26,333
- Oh yeah, they were good at that.

4312
02:40:26,333 --> 02:40:28,502
So they were excellent engineers.

4313
02:40:29,399 --> 02:40:31,229
And the Romans were excellent engineers,

4314
02:40:31,229 --> 02:40:32,398
especially when it came to

4315
02:40:32,399 --> 02:40:34,528
what you might think of as humble stuff.

4316
02:40:34,530 --> 02:40:35,850
I mean, today we tend to think of,

4317
02:40:35,850 --> 02:40:38,879
oh, a Roman building is shining white marble, right?

4318
02:40:38,879 --> 02:40:41,519
Well, the core of that building was probably concrete

4319
02:40:41,520 --> 02:40:44,189
and the marble is just a superficial facade.

4320
02:40:44,190 --> 02:40:47,009
And if you think about the Colosseum in Rome today,

4321
02:40:47,010 --> 02:40:49,349
all the marble has been stripped off that building

4322
02:40:49,350 --> 02:40:51,419
and what you see is the concrete core,

4323
02:40:51,420 --> 02:40:53,730
the structural core that's left.

4324
02:40:53,729 --> 02:40:56,639
And the Romans, I mean, they didn't invent concrete,

4325
02:40:56,639 --> 02:40:58,708
but they just used it more creatively

4326
02:40:58,709 --> 02:41:00,209
than anyone had before.

4327
02:41:00,209 --> 02:41:02,309
And if you look at buildings like the Greeks built,

4328
02:41:02,309 --> 02:41:03,448
they're all rectilinear,

4329
02:41:03,450 --> 02:41:05,430
they're all rectangles or squares,

4330
02:41:05,430 --> 02:41:07,559
and they always have a lot of columns

4331
02:41:07,559 --> 02:41:09,509
because you need to hold the roof up.

4332
02:41:09,510 --> 02:41:12,510
The Romans, because of their use of concrete,

4333
02:41:12,510 --> 02:41:14,250
could build wooden frames,

4334
02:41:14,250 --> 02:41:15,240
they could have curves,

4335
02:41:15,239 --> 02:41:16,139
they could have domes,

4336
02:41:16,139 --> 02:41:17,759
they could have all kinds of stuff.

4337
02:41:17,760 --> 02:41:21,809
And it just explodes the architectural possibilities.

4338
02:41:21,809 --> 02:41:24,268
They also made a lot of use of the vault.

4339
02:41:24,270 --> 02:41:26,490
So if you cut rocks and arrange them

4340
02:41:26,489 --> 02:41:27,599
so they form a curve,

4341
02:41:27,600 --> 02:41:29,669
you could have big vaulted spaces.

4342
02:41:29,670 --> 02:41:31,523
And they were just brilliant with their mix of things.

4343
02:41:31,522 --> 02:41:35,009
I mean, the Pantheon is the best preserved Roman building,

4344
02:41:35,010 --> 02:41:36,750
and it's another brilliant building,

4345
02:41:36,750 --> 02:41:38,250
incredibly influential.

4346
02:41:38,250 --> 02:41:41,009
I mean, every capitol building in the world

4347
02:41:41,010 --> 02:41:44,070
or museum is an imitation of the Pantheon.

4348
02:41:44,069 --> 02:41:46,528
You know, the capitol in Washington, D.C.,

4349
02:41:46,530 --> 02:41:48,480
the capitol in Madison, I'm from Wisconsin,

4350
02:41:48,479 --> 02:41:49,708
Austin, where we are now,

4351
02:41:49,709 --> 02:41:51,056
they're all Pantheons.

4352
02:41:52,040 --> 02:41:53,128
You know, it's a big dome

4353
02:41:53,129 --> 02:41:54,568
with a triangular pediment

4354
02:41:54,569 --> 02:41:56,069
and some columns on the front.

4355
02:41:57,059 --> 02:41:59,128
So it's just amazingly influential building,

4356
02:41:59,129 --> 02:42:00,358
but it's brilliant,

4357
02:42:00,360 --> 02:42:01,747
because the way it's constructed is,

4358
02:42:01,746 --> 02:42:04,319
you know, the concrete at the bottom of the dome

4359
02:42:04,319 --> 02:42:07,859
is both thicker and has a denser formulation.

4360
02:42:07,860 --> 02:42:10,380
So it's heavier where it needs to bear the weight.

4361
02:42:10,379 --> 02:42:12,179
And then as you get further up the dome,

4362
02:42:12,180 --> 02:42:13,680
it gets narrower and narrower

4363
02:42:13,680 --> 02:42:16,439
and they mix in different types of rock.

4364
02:42:16,440 --> 02:42:18,180
So at the top, you're using pumice,

4365
02:42:18,180 --> 02:42:20,069
that very light volcanic stone.

4366
02:42:20,069 --> 02:42:22,348
So where you want it to be light, it's light.

4367
02:42:22,350 --> 02:42:24,359
And it's here 2000 years later.

4368
02:42:24,360 --> 02:42:25,193
I mean, look around you.

4369
02:42:25,192 --> 02:42:26,669
How many buildings that we're building now

4370
02:42:26,670 --> 02:42:29,360
do you think are gonna be here in 2000 years?

4371
02:42:29,360 --> 02:42:31,799
I suspect not many.

4372
02:42:31,799 --> 02:42:33,448
- And it's not only that they lasted,

4373
02:42:33,450 --> 02:42:34,589
but they were beautiful,

4374
02:42:34,590 --> 02:42:37,380
or at least in our current conception of beauty.

4375
02:42:37,379 --> 02:42:39,448
- Yeah, I mean, you know, Vitruvius,

4376
02:42:39,450 --> 02:42:41,459
you know, his principles are things should be functional

4377
02:42:41,459 --> 02:42:43,528
and they should be aesthetically pleasing.

4378
02:42:43,530 --> 02:42:46,050
So that's a winning combination, I think.

4379
02:42:46,049 --> 02:42:48,328
- Yeah, they pulled that off pretty well.

4380
02:42:48,329 --> 02:42:51,329
If you could talk about the long line of emperors

4381
02:42:51,329 --> 02:42:53,518
that made up the Roman Empire,

4382
02:42:53,520 --> 02:42:55,830
how were they selected?

4383
02:42:55,829 --> 02:42:57,329
- Oh boy, this is,

4384
02:42:57,329 --> 02:43:00,208
we've been talking about Augustus's great achievements

4385
02:43:00,209 --> 02:43:02,488
and how clever he was with propaganda and all,

4386
02:43:02,489 --> 02:43:05,189
this is his great failure.

4387
02:43:05,190 --> 02:43:08,190
So his great failure is that he did not solve

4388
02:43:08,190 --> 02:43:10,199
was the problem of succession.

4389
02:43:10,200 --> 02:43:13,170
How do you ensure that the next person who follows you

4390
02:43:13,170 --> 02:43:15,299
is not just the best person

4391
02:43:15,299 --> 02:43:16,591
but is qualified?

4392
02:43:17,430 --> 02:43:18,990
And he fails to do it.

4393
02:43:18,989 --> 02:43:22,018
So the principle he settles on is heredity.

4394
02:43:22,020 --> 02:43:23,970
So the nearest blood relative.

4395
02:43:23,969 --> 02:43:25,198
And he goes through all these people.

4396
02:43:25,200 --> 02:43:27,269
All these young kids in his family die.

4397
02:43:27,270 --> 02:43:28,949
He keeps trying to make the heir.

4398
02:43:28,950 --> 02:43:31,320
And he ends up making his heir Tiberius,

4399
02:43:31,319 --> 02:43:32,369
who he never liked.

4400
02:43:32,370 --> 02:43:34,590
It was his stepson, he didn't like him,

4401
02:43:34,590 --> 02:43:35,910
but he ends up inheriting it.

4402
02:43:35,909 --> 02:43:39,301
And the next set of emperors, the Julio-Claudian,

4403
02:43:40,139 --> 02:43:42,089
which is the family that Augusta starts,

4404
02:43:42,090 --> 02:43:45,570
they all basically are who is the nearest male relative

4405
02:43:45,569 --> 02:43:47,309
to the previous emperor.

4406
02:43:47,309 --> 02:43:49,619
And that's how he get a lot of crazy emperors

4407
02:43:49,620 --> 02:43:51,453
like Caligula or Nero.

4408
02:43:53,190 --> 02:43:55,376
And then the next family, the Flavian,

4409
02:43:55,377 --> 02:43:57,510
the first guy is kind of an Augustus.

4410
02:43:57,510 --> 02:43:58,343
It's Vespasian,

4411
02:43:58,343 --> 02:44:00,359
the one who builds the Flavian Amphitheater.

4412
02:44:00,360 --> 02:44:02,190
And then one of his sons takes over,

4413
02:44:02,190 --> 02:44:03,300
Titus, who's okay,

4414
02:44:03,299 --> 02:44:04,589
and then the next son takes over,

4415
02:44:04,590 --> 02:44:06,360
Domitian, who's nuts again.

4416
02:44:06,360 --> 02:44:09,330
So heredity just isn't working.

4417
02:44:09,329 --> 02:44:11,549
And Rome fights a couple civil wars,

4418
02:44:11,549 --> 02:44:12,591
and in 98 AD,

4419
02:44:13,469 --> 02:44:15,808
we're a hundred years now into the empire,

4420
02:44:15,809 --> 02:44:17,916
and they look back at this track record and say,

4421
02:44:17,916 --> 02:44:20,848
"Okay, we've been picking our emperors by heredity

4422
02:44:20,850 --> 02:44:21,780
and it's been a,

4423
02:44:21,780 --> 02:44:23,580
we've gotten some real duds here,

4424
02:44:23,579 --> 02:44:25,679
some real problematic people.

