5720
03:32:21,870 --> 03:32:24,689
than you could possibly go through in your lifetime.

5721
03:32:24,690 --> 03:32:27,839
If you say, "I wanna write a book about the Roman world,"

5722
03:32:27,840 --> 03:32:30,119
this is a very different thing.

5723
03:32:30,120 --> 03:32:32,220
In my office, I have a bookshelf

5724
03:32:32,219 --> 03:32:33,059
that's, I don't know,

5725
03:32:33,059 --> 03:32:35,398
eight feet high, 10 feet wide,

5726
03:32:35,399 --> 03:32:39,929
and it contains pretty much all the main surviving

5727
03:32:39,930 --> 03:32:43,652
Greek and Roman literary texts.

5728
03:32:43,653 --> 03:32:45,510
- Okay. Wow. Wow. - One bookshelf.

5729
03:32:45,510 --> 03:32:47,340
It's a big bookshelf. - Yeah.

5730
03:32:47,340 --> 03:32:49,529
- But that's what we use to interpret this world.

5731
03:32:49,530 --> 03:32:51,270
Now, there's a lot of other types of texts.

5732
03:32:51,270 --> 03:32:53,279
There's, you know, papyri,

5733
03:32:53,280 --> 03:32:54,150
there's all sorts of things,

5734
03:32:54,149 --> 03:32:55,439
there's inscriptions,

5735
03:32:55,440 --> 03:32:56,910
there's archeological evidence.

5736
03:32:56,909 --> 03:32:58,798
So there's other stuff.

5737
03:32:58,799 --> 03:33:00,569
But honestly, you know,

5738
03:33:00,569 --> 03:33:05,569
99% of things about the world I study are lost.

5739
03:33:07,319 --> 03:33:10,259
Then you get into all the issues are, you know,

5740
03:33:10,260 --> 03:33:12,840
is what we have surviving a representative example?

5741
03:33:12,840 --> 03:33:14,219
We know it's not.

5742
03:33:14,219 --> 03:33:15,658
For example, all the literary texts

5743
03:33:15,659 --> 03:33:18,242
are written by one tiny group, elite males.

5744
03:33:19,260 --> 03:33:21,659
So that's a problem there.

5745
03:33:21,659 --> 03:33:23,068
There's the problem of bias.

5746
03:33:23,069 --> 03:33:25,360
We know that they're not necessarily telling us the truth.

5747
03:33:25,361 --> 03:33:27,779
They have an agenda, you know.

5748
03:33:27,780 --> 03:33:29,940
They're representing history in a certain way

5749
03:33:29,940 --> 03:33:31,770
to achieve certain things.

5750
03:33:31,770 --> 03:33:33,540
Then there's the problem of transmission.

5751
03:33:33,540 --> 03:33:35,669
I mean, all those texts are copies of copies

5752
03:33:35,670 --> 03:33:37,049
of copies of copies.

5753
03:33:37,049 --> 03:33:38,399
And everybody knows that game where, you know,

5754
03:33:38,399 --> 03:33:40,019
you whisper a sentence to someone

5755
03:33:40,020 --> 03:33:41,010
and then go around the room.

5756
03:33:41,010 --> 03:33:43,110
Are you gonna get that same sentence back?

5757
03:33:43,110 --> 03:33:44,670
Well, every ancient text we have

5758
03:33:44,670 --> 03:33:46,172
has gone through that process.

5759
03:33:47,430 --> 03:33:48,990
So this is a real problem.

5760
03:33:48,989 --> 03:33:51,359
And that's just with the sources, right?

5761
03:33:51,360 --> 03:33:53,790
And this is the historic era.

5762
03:33:53,790 --> 03:33:56,249
When you move back just a little earlier

5763
03:33:56,250 --> 03:33:59,040
to the prehistoric era or to civilizations

5764
03:33:59,040 --> 03:34:01,350
that don't have written sources surviving?

5765
03:34:01,350 --> 03:34:04,229
And some of these are ancient Mediterranean ones.

5766
03:34:04,229 --> 03:34:05,612
I mean, anything goes.

5767
03:34:06,450 --> 03:34:09,030
I mean, one of the jokes is that museums,

5768
03:34:09,030 --> 03:34:10,140
archeological museums,

5769
03:34:10,139 --> 03:34:11,368
are full of objects

5770
03:34:11,370 --> 03:34:14,399
which are labeled cult object.

5771
03:34:14,399 --> 03:34:16,259
It's some religious object.

5772
03:34:16,260 --> 03:34:18,179
And I think the honest label

5773
03:34:18,180 --> 03:34:19,476
that should be on that thing is

5774
03:34:19,477 --> 03:34:21,450
"We have no idea what the hell this is,

5775
03:34:21,450 --> 03:34:23,369
but I wanna believe it's something important,

5776
03:34:23,370 --> 03:34:25,559
so I'm gonna say it's a religious object."

5777
03:34:25,559 --> 03:34:26,579
But in reality, you know,

5778
03:34:26,579 --> 03:34:28,889
it's an ancient toilet paper roll holder,

5779
03:34:28,889 --> 03:34:29,722
or something. - Yeah.

5780
03:34:29,722 --> 03:34:34,018
And it's a huge problem when you try to interpret

5781
03:34:34,020 --> 03:34:37,799
a civilization without written texts.

5782
03:34:37,799 --> 03:34:39,448
And my favorite little story

5783
03:34:39,450 --> 03:34:41,499
that kind of illustrates this is

5784
03:34:42,600 --> 03:34:45,120
in the 19th century, this German,

5785
03:34:45,120 --> 03:34:46,607
who had gone to school in England, okay,

5786
03:34:46,606 --> 03:34:48,989
one of the best educated guys of his time,

5787
03:34:48,989 --> 03:34:50,249
goes to North Africa

5788
03:34:50,250 --> 03:34:52,259
and is poking around in the desert.

5789
03:34:52,260 --> 03:34:56,639
And he finds this site with these huge stone monoliths,

5790
03:34:56,639 --> 03:34:59,279
10 feet tall, in pairs.

5791
03:34:59,280 --> 03:35:01,619
And there's a lintel stone across the top.

5792
03:35:01,620 --> 03:35:04,320
So sort of like big, you know, two posts

5793
03:35:04,319 --> 03:35:05,698
with a stone across the top.

5794
03:35:05,700 --> 03:35:08,263
And there's a big stone in front of them too.

5795
03:35:08,263 --> 03:35:09,537
And so he looks at this stuff

5796
03:35:09,537 --> 03:35:13,170
and he says, "Well, what does this remind me of?"

5797
03:35:13,170 --> 03:35:15,537
It reminds me of Stonehenge, right?

5798
03:35:15,537 --> 03:35:16,680
And there's even a site

5799
03:35:16,680 --> 03:35:17,909
where there's multiple of these,

5800
03:35:17,909 --> 03:35:19,409
kind of in a square.

5801
03:35:19,409 --> 03:35:20,996
So he goes back and talks about this,

5802
03:35:20,996 --> 03:35:23,459
and an Englishman goes and studies them,

5803
03:35:23,459 --> 03:35:25,229
and he finds a ton of these sites.

5804
03:35:25,229 --> 03:35:28,528
And he finds some of them where there's 17 of these pairs.

5805
03:35:28,530 --> 03:35:29,699
And so he goes back

5806
03:35:29,700 --> 03:35:31,109
and he writes a whole book about

5807
03:35:31,110 --> 03:35:32,700
how clearly the Celtic peoples

5808
03:35:32,700 --> 03:35:33,839
who once lived in Britain

5809
03:35:33,840 --> 03:35:35,820
came originally from North Africa

5810
03:35:35,819 --> 03:35:37,198
'cause he's found this site.

5811
03:35:37,200 --> 03:35:39,119
And he reconstructs the religion,

5812
03:35:39,120 --> 03:35:41,939
where obviously they practice religious rituals here,

5813
03:35:41,940 --> 03:35:43,530
and they had rites of passage,

5814
03:35:43,530 --> 03:35:45,240
they squeeze between the things.

5815
03:35:45,239 --> 03:35:47,788
And the altar stones have this basin,

5816
03:35:47,790 --> 03:35:50,850
so they had blood sacrifice, and all this.

5817
03:35:50,850 --> 03:35:52,620
And it seemed reasonable.

5818
03:35:52,620 --> 03:35:54,307
And then, you know, you ask some locals,

5819
03:35:54,307 --> 03:35:55,859
"Well, what was that stuff out in the desert there?"

5820
03:35:55,860 --> 03:36:00,150
And they mean, "Oh, the old Roman olive oil factory?"

5821
03:36:00,149 --> 03:36:02,369
And those are the remains of an olive press.

5822
03:36:02,370 --> 03:36:03,270
And we're back to olives.

5823
03:36:03,270 --> 03:36:05,189
I keep dwelling on olives.

5824
03:36:05,190 --> 03:36:08,250
Olives don't grow in England or Germany.

5825
03:36:08,250 --> 03:36:11,160
- Yeah. - So this is cultural bias.

5826
03:36:11,159 --> 03:36:13,618
- If all you have is physical evidence,

5827
03:36:13,620 --> 03:36:15,269
you're gonna interpret that evidence

5828
03:36:15,270 --> 03:36:17,370
through your own cultural biases.

5829
03:36:17,370 --> 03:36:19,019
So if you're an Englishman

5830
03:36:19,020 --> 03:36:21,270
and you see big stone uprights like this,

5831
03:36:21,270 --> 03:36:22,980
you're gonna think Stonehenge.

5832
03:36:22,979 --> 03:36:24,539
If you're from the Mediterranean,

5833
03:36:24,540 --> 03:36:26,790
you're gonna think olive press.

5834
03:36:26,790 --> 03:36:31,620
So that's a salutatory example, I think,

5835
03:36:31,620 --> 03:36:35,430
of the dangers of interpreting physical evidence

5836
03:36:35,430 --> 03:36:37,079
when you don't have written evidence

5837
03:36:37,079 --> 03:36:38,893
to go along with it.

5838
03:36:38,894 --> 03:36:39,990
And, you know, think today.

5839
03:36:39,989 --> 03:36:43,709
Like if our civilization were to blow up in a nuclear war

5840
03:36:43,709 --> 03:36:46,258
and archeologists were to dig this up,

5841
03:36:46,260 --> 03:36:49,050
you know, how might they misinterpret things?

5842
03:36:49,049 --> 03:36:51,598
I mean, if they were to, you know,

5843
03:36:51,600 --> 03:36:54,120
dig up a college dorm, like where I work,

5844
03:36:54,120 --> 03:36:56,459
and that's what you had for the civilization,

5845
03:36:56,459 --> 03:36:57,868
you'd probably go in the dorm rooms,

5846
03:36:57,870 --> 03:36:59,549
you'd find all these little rooms,

5847
03:36:59,549 --> 03:37:00,748
and maybe in every room,

5848
03:37:00,750 --> 03:37:03,839
you'd find this mysterious plastic disc.

5849
03:37:03,840 --> 03:37:05,550
And so everybody has these,

5850
03:37:05,549 --> 03:37:07,558
so it must be a cult object.

5851
03:37:07,559 --> 03:37:08,549
And it's round,

5852
03:37:08,549 --> 03:37:10,828
so obviously, they're sun worshipers.

5853
03:37:10,829 --> 03:37:12,869
And if you can decipher the inscription,

5854
03:37:12,870 --> 03:37:13,703
you'll see that, obviously,

5855
03:37:13,702 --> 03:37:16,733
they all worship the great sun god whammo.

5856
03:37:16,734 --> 03:37:19,140
- You know, it's like, what do you find in every dorm room?

5857
03:37:19,139 --> 03:37:20,159
A Frisbee. - Yeah.

5858
03:37:20,159 --> 03:37:23,699
- So that's the level of interpretation

5859
03:37:23,700 --> 03:37:25,050
you have to be aware of.

5860
03:37:25,049 --> 03:37:28,739
And there's examples where we've done exactly this.

5861
03:37:28,739 --> 03:37:30,748
- So we'll have to have intellectual humility

5862
03:37:30,750 --> 03:37:32,819
when we look back into the past.

5863
03:37:32,819 --> 03:37:36,089
But hopefully, if you have that

5864
03:37:36,090 --> 03:37:38,670
without coming up with really strong narratives,

5865
03:37:38,670 --> 03:37:41,670
if you look at a large variety of evidence,

5866
03:37:41,670 --> 03:37:44,190
you can start to construct a picture

5867
03:37:44,190 --> 03:37:46,140
that somewhat rhymes-

5868
03:37:46,139 --> 03:37:47,818
- Yes. - with the truth.

5869
03:37:47,819 --> 03:37:48,809
- Yes. I mean, that's,

5870
03:37:48,809 --> 03:37:50,669
as a professional historian, that's what you do.

5871
03:37:50,670 --> 03:37:54,239
You attempt to reconstruct an image of the past

5872
03:37:54,239 --> 03:37:58,439
that is faithful to the evidence you have

5873
03:37:58,440 --> 03:38:00,960
as filtered through what you can perceive

5874
03:38:00,959 --> 03:38:03,269
of both the biases and the problems

5875
03:38:03,270 --> 03:38:04,409
of the source material

5876
03:38:04,409 --> 03:38:06,449
and your own biases.

5877
03:38:06,450 --> 03:38:10,019
And it's a interpretation, it's a reconstruction,

5878
03:38:10,020 --> 03:38:11,370
but it's a lot like science

5879
03:38:11,370 --> 03:38:14,729
where you're in a process of constantly reevaluating it

5880
03:38:14,729 --> 03:38:16,499
and saying, "Okay, here's some new evidence.

5881
03:38:16,500 --> 03:38:18,030
How do I work this into the picture?

5882
03:38:18,030 --> 03:38:19,826
How do I, now, adjust it?"

5883
03:38:20,683 --> 03:38:21,719
And that's what's fun.

5884
03:38:21,719 --> 03:38:24,339
I mean, it's a mystery, you know.

5885
03:38:24,340 --> 03:38:25,830
You're being a detective

5886
03:38:25,829 --> 03:38:28,615
and trying to reconstruct and to understand a society.

5887
03:38:28,617 --> 03:38:30,300
And it's even more fun where it's,

5888
03:38:30,299 --> 03:38:32,789
yeah, you have to try to empathize.

5889
03:38:32,790 --> 03:38:34,380
Empathy is a great human thing.

5890
03:38:34,379 --> 03:38:37,528
To empathize with people who are not yourself.

5891
03:38:37,530 --> 03:38:39,449
And we should do this all the time

5892
03:38:39,450 --> 03:38:41,010
with just the people we encounter,

5893
03:38:41,010 --> 03:38:43,559
but this is what we're doing with ancient civilizations.

5894
03:38:43,559 --> 03:38:44,669
And as I talked about earlier,

5895
03:38:44,670 --> 03:38:47,100
sometimes you'll feel great sympathy there,

5896
03:38:47,100 --> 03:38:49,680
sometimes you'll feel incomprehension.

5897
03:38:49,680 --> 03:38:51,660
But by being aware of both of those,

5898
03:38:51,659 --> 03:38:54,029
you can maybe begin to get some grasp,

5899
03:38:54,030 --> 03:38:55,320
however, tentative,

5900
03:38:55,319 --> 03:38:59,549
on the truth as you might perceive it.

5901
03:38:59,549 --> 03:39:01,558
- To ask a ridiculous question.

5902
03:39:01,559 --> 03:39:05,549
When our time, you and I, we, together,

5903
03:39:05,549 --> 03:39:07,079
become ancient history,

5904
03:39:07,079 --> 03:39:09,151
when historians, let's say,

5905
03:39:10,139 --> 03:39:11,999
2, 3, 4,000 years from now,

5906
03:39:12,000 --> 03:39:15,609
look back at our time and, like you,

5907
03:39:15,610 --> 03:39:18,420
tried to look at the details

5908
03:39:18,420 --> 03:39:19,253
and reconstruct from that,

5909
03:39:19,253 --> 03:39:21,123
the big picture, what was going on,

5910
03:39:22,170 --> 03:39:23,549
what do you think they'll say?

5911
03:39:23,549 --> 03:39:25,169
- I would guess it'll be something

5912
03:39:25,170 --> 03:39:26,579
that's actually more of a commentary

5913
03:39:26,579 --> 03:39:28,319
on whatever's going on at that point

5914
03:39:28,319 --> 03:39:30,179
than on the reality of us,

5915
03:39:30,180 --> 03:39:31,950
because that's what we tend to do.

5916
03:39:31,950 --> 03:39:34,170
I'll tell you what I'd like to have them say.

5917
03:39:34,170 --> 03:39:36,480
Is to say, "In this civilization,

5918
03:39:36,479 --> 03:39:38,158
I can detect progress.

5919
03:39:38,159 --> 03:39:41,129
That they have advanced in some way,

5920
03:39:41,129 --> 03:39:43,018
whether kind of in moral terms

5921
03:39:43,020 --> 03:39:44,520
or in self-awareness,

5922
03:39:44,520 --> 03:39:46,193
or have learned from what's come before."

5923
03:39:46,192 --> 03:39:48,029
I mean, that's all you can try and do

5924
03:39:48,030 --> 03:39:50,400
is do a little bit better than whatever came before you,

5925
03:39:50,399 --> 03:39:51,808
to look back at what happened,

5926
03:39:51,809 --> 03:39:53,432
and try to do something.

5927
03:39:54,930 --> 03:39:57,539
Livy, I mean, one of the great Roman historians,

5928
03:39:57,540 --> 03:39:59,040
the beginning of his work,

5929
03:39:59,040 --> 03:39:59,873
a history of Rome,

5930
03:39:59,872 --> 03:40:02,195
which is this massive thing, he says,

5931
03:40:02,197 --> 03:40:05,820
"The utility and the purpose of history is this:

5932
03:40:05,819 --> 03:40:08,729
It provides you an infinite variety

5933
03:40:08,729 --> 03:40:10,891
of experiences and models.

5934
03:40:12,180 --> 03:40:14,010
Noble things to imitate

5935
03:40:14,010 --> 03:40:16,469
and shameful things to avoid."

5936
03:40:16,469 --> 03:40:18,422
And I think he's right.

5937
03:40:19,770 --> 03:40:22,620
- And they would perhaps be better at highlighting

5938
03:40:22,620 --> 03:40:24,689
which shameful things we started avoiding

5939
03:40:24,690 --> 03:40:27,874
and which noble things we started imitating.

5940
03:40:27,873 --> 03:40:29,639
With the perspective of history,

5941
03:40:29,639 --> 03:40:31,082
they'll be able to identify.

5942
03:40:32,040 --> 03:40:34,923
Or maybe with the bias of the historians of the time.

5943
03:40:36,059 --> 03:40:37,829
Well, in that grand perspective,

5944
03:40:37,829 --> 03:40:39,958
what gives you hope about our future,

5945
03:40:39,959 --> 03:40:42,181
as a humanity, as a civilization?

5946
03:40:43,829 --> 03:40:45,002
- We have curiosity.

5947
03:40:46,680 --> 03:40:48,450
I think curiosity is a great thing.

5948
03:40:48,450 --> 03:40:50,490
That you wanna learn something new.

5949
03:40:50,489 --> 03:40:52,439
I think the human impulse to want to knew,

5950
03:40:52,440 --> 03:40:54,240
learn new stuff

5951
03:40:54,239 --> 03:40:56,908
is one of our best characteristics.

5952
03:40:56,909 --> 03:40:58,469
And at least up to this point,

5953
03:40:58,469 --> 03:40:59,549
what makes us special

5954
03:40:59,549 --> 03:41:01,109
is the ability to store up

5955
03:41:01,110 --> 03:41:02,850
an accumulation of knowledge

5956
03:41:02,850 --> 03:41:05,999
and to pass that knowledge on to the next generation.

5957
03:41:06,000 --> 03:41:07,360
I mean, that's really all we are.

5958
03:41:07,360 --> 03:41:09,569
We're the accumulation of the knowledge

5959
03:41:09,569 --> 03:41:10,446
of infinite generations

5960
03:41:10,447 --> 03:41:12,273
that have come before us.

5961
03:41:13,409 --> 03:41:15,179
And everything we do is based on that.

5962
03:41:15,180 --> 03:41:17,010
Otherwise, we'd all just be starting,

5963
03:41:17,010 --> 03:41:18,689
you know, at ground zero

5964
03:41:18,690 --> 03:41:20,609
kind of just from the beginning.

5965
03:41:20,610 --> 03:41:23,279
So our ability to store up knowledge and pass it on,

5966
03:41:23,280 --> 03:41:26,970
I think, is our special power as human beings.

5967
03:41:26,969 --> 03:41:30,061
And I think our curiosity is what keeps us going forward.

5968
03:41:31,020 --> 03:41:31,853
- I agree.

5969
03:41:31,852 --> 03:41:33,809
And for that, I thank you for being

5970
03:41:33,809 --> 03:41:35,989
one of the most wonderful examples of that,

5971
03:41:35,989 --> 03:41:37,888
of you, yourself, being a curious being

5972
03:41:37,889 --> 03:41:39,179
and emanating that throughout

5973
03:41:39,180 --> 03:41:41,789
and inspiring a lot of other people to be curious

5974
03:41:41,790 --> 03:41:44,640
by being out there in the world and teaching.

5975
03:41:44,639 --> 03:41:45,749
So thank you for that

5976
03:41:45,750 --> 03:41:47,070
and thank you for talking today.

5977
03:41:47,069 --> 03:41:48,208
- No, I enjoyed it. It's fun.

5978
03:41:48,209 --> 03:41:50,241
I obviously like talking about this stuff.

5979
03:41:51,600 --> 03:41:53,519
